<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Graham     11-15 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Graham,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former AP Writer Dillon Graham Dead at 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dillon Lorentus Graham Jr., a former
Associated Press bureau chief and reporter who spent much of his
career in Washington, has died at age 81.
   A memorial service was held Tuesday at the Covenant Towers
retirement center, where Graham died Sunday.
   Graham, a native of Gainesville, Fla., was a reporter for The
Gainesville Sun before joining the wire service in 1929.
   Graham worked for the AP in Washington from 1934 to 1937, when
he transferred to New York. He became features editor in New York,
and in 1943 was named chief of the Charlotte, N.C., bureau.
   In 1947, Graham returned to Washington, where he worked until
his retirement in 1973.
   He is survived by his wife, Gilbert ``GiGi'' Graham of Myrtle
Beach; a daughter, Betty Graham Mooney of Arlington, Va.; three
grandchildren and a great-grandchild.
   No funeral was planned.
</TEXT>
