<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-EthnicAlbanians CLARIFICATION   11-15 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethnic Albanians, CLARIFICATION,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds, papers that published a story slugged PM-Yugoslavia-Protest,
a0546 of Nov. 2, may wish to publish the following.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a dispatch Nov. 2, The Associated
Press identified 15 ethnic Albanians on trial in Kosovo province as
``separatists'' but neglected to attribute the term to certain
authorities.
   The 15, who include former Kosovo Communist Party leader Azem
Vlasi, are charged with ``counterrevolutionary activities'' in
connection with ethnic Albanian protests in Kosovo.
   The term separatists has been applied to the 15 by some
authorities in the Yugoslav republic of Serbia, of which Kosovo is
part, who claim the ethnic Albanians sought to make the province
part of neighboring Albania. The term should have been attributed
to those authorities.
   About 85 percent of Kosovo's population are Albanians and most
are described as favoring a restoration of the autonomy the claim
they lost with recent constitutional changes. But there is no
evidence that the majority favors separating from Yugoslavia to
become part of Albania.
</TEXT>
