<FIRST>r a AM-Congress-Cambodia     11-15 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Cambodia,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Restrict U.S. Military Aid to Cambodian Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress has acted to restrict the use of CIA
money to arm the non-communist guerrillas fighting the
Vietnamese-backed government in Cambodia, according to a published
report.
   A bill awaiting final passage would prevent President Bush from
using the agency's contingency funds to send weapons to the
guerrillas unless he first gets approval from Congress, The New
York Times reported in its Wednesday editions.
   Ordinarily, the administration does not need such approval to
use CIA contingency funds.
   The restriction is part of a secret appendix to the military
appropriations bill for the current fiscal year, The Times said.
The bill has emerged from a House-Senate conference committee and
is awaiting final action by both houses.
   The non-communist guerrillas in Cambodia belong to two groups
that are linked in a loose coalition with the Communist Khmer
Rouge, which murdered up to 2 million people when it ruled Cambodia
between 1975 and 1979.
   The United States opposes a return to power by the Khmer Rouge
but favors the non-communist resistance, which Vice President Dan
Quayle has called ``the best hope to see a political settlement
occur in Cambodia.'' The Bush administration has been providing
food, medicine and other non-military aid to the non-communist
guerrillas.
   In September, the State Department said the non-communist forces
should be strengthened as a means of encouraging the Phnom Penh
government to agree to share power. At that time, State Department
spokesman Richard Boucher declined to say whether the United States
was attempting to strengthen the rebel groups with military aid.
   Key members of the congressional appropriations committees
strongly oppose any American military aid to the guerrillas, The
Times reported. It quoted Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., as saying
such aid could lead the United States into ``a major new military
involvement in the wars of Southeast Asia.''
</TEXT>
