<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CivilRights     11-15 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Civil Rights,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Lease on Life for Strife-Torn Civil Rights Panel Clears Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Civil Rights Commission, torn by
internal feuding and under fire in Congress, would gain a six-month
extension under legislation approved by the House Judiciary
Committee.
   ``The time has come in this country to put the petty bickering
and the waste of the taxpayers' money on the Civil Rights
Commission behind us,'' Rep. James F. Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., told
committee members Tuesday.
   The commission will go out of business Nov. 30 unless Congress
extends it. Republicans and Democrats critical of the strife that
has wracked the panel have so far been unable to agree on the
length of the extension.
   Approved by the committee, 25-9, was a Democratic-sponsored,
six-month extension that would keep on the front burner the
question of how to reshape the commission and end its long-running
internal feuds.
   The committee turned down a Republican plan to allow the
commission to go out of business for one day only, thus allowing
the Bush administration to dump any members it opposes. It then
would be reconstituted for six years.
   The Republican plan, offered by Sensenbrenner, was similar to a
version recommended to the committee by the Bush administration.
   ``We should not ram through a six-year bill in the closing days
of this Congress,'' said Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chief
supporter of the Democratic version. He said he had initially
sought a one-year extension but bowed to a proposal by Sen. Paul
Simon, D-Ill., to cut that time in half.
   Twenty-five years ago, civil rights forces hailed the
commission's hearings across the South, its ringing reports on
racial injustice and its bold legislative proposals. ``It served as
the conscience of the nation,'' says Ralph G. Neas, executive
director of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights.
   Over the last six years, however, the commission has been
snarled in fierce internal fighting. Lately, Democrats and
Republicans on Capitol Hill have joined in slashing its budget.
   Controversy has dogged commission member William B. Allen, its
former chairman. He most recently came under fire for a speech to a
conservative group. The title was: ``Blacks? Animals? Homosexuals?
What is a Minority?''
   Allen, who is black, calls himself the only conservative on the
commission and says he does ``not believe in coddling people.''
   In a 6-1 vote, the commission branded the speech ``thoughtless,
disgusting and unnecessarily inflammatory.''
   ``Frankly, it is a waste of the taxpayers' money to continue the
prattle that has been coming out of the commission for another six
months,'' Sensenbrenner said. ``We would be better off with no
civil rights commission than with this civil rights commission.''
   Hostile exchanges between Allen and Democratic commission member
Mary Frances Berry have been at the heart of the controversy, he
said.
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., however, told the committee that
``anyone who was committed to the cause of civil rights who did not
spend a lot of time disagreeing with chairman Allen would be
derelict in his or her duty, since he is one of the more bizarre
public officials in my memory.''
   Sensenbrenner retorted that Berry ``has come up with some
bizarre statements of her own.'' He said it was urgently necessary
to take action to turn around the course of the commission.
   ``They have frankly made themselves into a national
laughingstock,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0020 </DOCNO>
