<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BloodDisorder     11-15 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blood Disorder,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Group Urges Sales Suspension of L-tryptophan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Makers of L-tryptophan are suspending
distribution and sales of the dietary supplement because of its
possible link to a potentially fatal blood disorder, an industry
group says.
   The Council for Responsible Nutrition called for the temporary
sales halt as a ``prudent and cautious course of action'' even
though no link has been established between the non-prescription
supplement and the disorder.
   Some companies started halting sales soon after the council
called for the action Tuesday afternoon, said J.B. Cordaro,
president of the Washington-based council that represents
nutritional supplement companies, including most makers of
L-tryptophan. He said he expected virtually all makers of the
product to comply with the council's call by Thursday.
   Officials were investigating 81 unconfirmed cases of the
disorder, known as eosinophilia, in 17 states and the District of
Columbia, according to the Food and Drug Administration.
   New Mexico on Monday banned L-tryptophan. Oregon's Health
Division recommended the product be withdrawn, and health officials
in Illinois and Idaho recommended that people avoid using
L-tryptophan.
   The council's action pertains to the food supplement that is
sold in tablet and capsule form, which is used for sleeplessness
and premenstrual syndrome. It does not cover multi-ingredient
products that also contain L-tryptophan.
   ``This action should not be viewed as a product recall but an
interim measure pending clarification of the causes of this
outbreak,'' the council said.
   ``Public health agencies investigating have not been able to
establish a scientific basis or isolate medical evidence that links
L-tryptophan with this disorder,'' the council said. ``In addition,
to date FDA and industry testing of L-tryptophan products have not
identified any product contamination.''
   A spokesman for the Food and Drug Administration, Don McLearn,
said the agency was satisfied with the industry's action.
   McLearn said that without a stronger cause-and-effect link, the
FDA has no authority to order a recall. He said the strongest
action the agency could take was announced Saturday when it advised
people taking L-tryptophan to discontinue use of the product.
   At least 12 different brands of L-tryptophan have been
identified as having been used by the individuals who became ill in
recent weeks.
   Eosinophilia is marked by a higher than normal number of white
blood cells known as eosinophils. Symptoms include severe muscle
pain, fever, joint pain, weakness, swelling of the arms and legs
and skin rash.
</TEXT>
