<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     11-15 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORAOPOLIS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. John Dompka and his parishioners
look to the heavens in more ways than one.
   Dompka, 70, a licensed pilot, is pastor of St. Margaret Mary
Roman Catholic Church, located on a hilltop near Greater Pittsburgh
International Airport.
   Many in the congregation of 1,500 families work at the airport,
and Dompka said he sometimes flashes a photo of an airplane on the
audio-visual display screen behind the church altar.
   ``To get their attention immediately, I sometimes use my
aviation experience in my sermons,'' he said.
   The congregation's enthusiasm for flying can be seen on the
church's stationery, which features a picture of an astronaut
conducting lunar experiments.
   On the stationery is this note: ``Saint Margaret Mary Church, a
parish of plane people with a special air about them. Saturday
evening mass at 6:30 to accommodate earthlings.''
   Dompka said he is one of about 150 members of the National
Association of Priest Pilots. He also belongs to the Beaver Valley
Flying Club, whose 60 members share access to three Cessnas and a
Piper Archer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flatnose the tree-climbing dog
disappointed fans in his first public tree-climbing effort since
undergoing surgery to have a pacemaker inserted.
   Panting and slobbering, Flatnose tugged himself a couple of feet
up a pine pole in a demonstration Tuesday at the Mid-Atlantic Farm
Show, but he didn't shimmy like he used to do on ``The Tonight
Show.''
   After four or five tries, with the audience drifting away,
Flatnose went backstage and stretched out on the floor to rest.
   Does it mean his career as ``the world's only tree-climbing
dog'' is over?
   Not according to Barney Odom, the self-described ``old country
boy'' from South Carolina who owns and trains Flatnose. Odom said
the tree set up for Flatnose wasn't thick enough to really grab
with his paws.
   He didn't think the dog was slowed by his September heart
surgery. The pacemaker, inserted at the veterinary school at North
Carolina State University, has helped Flatnose overcome spells when
he would fall on his side with his legs kicking, Odom said.
   ``Old Flatnose is doing right good since his surgery,'' he said.
``I've been exercising him.''
   He said Flatnose scrambled right up a tree in practice recently.
</TEXT>
