<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-ForeignAid     11-15 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Foreign Aid,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress, On Eve of Walesa Speech, Votes Aid to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is moving rapidly to reinforce
Poland's dramatic political and economic changes with U.S. dollars,
creating a three-year, $657 million aid program and providing the
first hard cash to back up that promise.
   The Senate voted 99-0 on Tuesday to support new business
enterprises,stabilize currency, provide emergency food and
encourage democratic institutions in Poland, on the eve of
Solidarity labor leader Lech Walesa's speech to a joint meeting of
Congress. The measure also included $81 million in aid for Hungary.
   ``Lech Walesa, this is for you and a free Poland,'' said Sen.
Paul Simon, D-Ill., a primary sponsor of the aid measure.
   Both Poland and Hungary have been in the forefront of the wave
of reform sweeping Eastern Europe that includes radical opening of
political institutions and restructuring of economies along Western
lines.
   At the same time, the House moved to put the first dollars into
the new program, voting 324-93 for a foreign aid bill that includes
$293 million in the current year, along with another $240 million
in standby credit and trade insurance.
   The House measure, a $14.6 billion bill providing U.S. aid to
allies around the globe, also offered up to $85 million for El
Salvador's besieged military and $125 million to help Andean
countries fight the drug war.
   But the money bill was the subject of a White House veto threat
because of a provision, growing out of the Iran-Contra scandal,
which would bar use of foreign aid to entice other countries to
carry out policies contrary to U.S. law. The administration
believed the language would tie its hands in dealings with allies.
   Another potentially contentious issue in the $14.6 billion bill
was defused when the House voted 219 to 203 to give President Bush
the right to withhold $15 million for the United Nations Population
Fund if he finds the agency supports forced abortions or
sterilizations in China. The measure now goes to the Senate.
   For Poland and Hungary, major elements of the appropriations
measure included a $200 million grant to help stabilize Poland's
battered economy and $45 million for a private enterprise
development fund. Other money would go for environmental cleanup,
agriculture and educational and cultural exchanges.
   The bill creating the long-term aid program represented an
apparent truce in a game of one-upsmanship between the White House
and congressional Democrats over who could provide the biggest
reward to Poland. Bush had proposed a $455 million program which
was immediately labeled ``timid'' by Democrats, who proposed
upwards of $1 billion in aid.
   As passed by the Senate, the measure offers $200 million in
currency stabilization, $400 million in enterprise funds and $125
million in food aid. Recognizing Poland's serious economic problems
and a reform plan advanced to address them, the bill allocates $657
million for that country over three years. Hungary would receive
$81 million.
   Overall, the foreign aid appropriations bill included $4.7
billion in military aid and $3.2 billion in economic aid for U.S.
friends and allies around the world.
   Among major earmarks for countries in the bill were $3 billion
for Israel and $2.1 billion for Egypt, always the largest aid
recipients because of their participation in the Camp David peace
process.
   Other large recipients included Pakistan, with $460 million in
military and economic aid; Turkey, $500 million in military aid;
Greece, $350 million in military aid; and $63 million in military
and economic aid for Morocco.
   In addition, the agreement provides $160 million for the U.S.
contribution to the Multilateral Assistance Initiative for the
Philippines, $83 million for Afghanistan relief, $83 million for
Jordan and $30 million in military aid to countries in Sub-Saharan
Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
