<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDReforms     11-15 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Reforms,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Reforms Headed for Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A package of reforms for the scandal-plagued
Department of Housing and Urban Development is heading for the
Senate after winning House approval.
   The House agreed overwhelmingly on a voice vote Tuesday evening
to approve the HUD reform package, which includes proposals from
Secretary Jack Kemp as well as others arising from a congressional
investigation of the department's multibillion-dollar scandals.
   ``I believe the bill allows us to get the HUD scandals behind
us,'' said Rep. Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House
committee that approved the measure.
   The action came after his panel, the House Banking subcommittee
on housing and community development, last week stripped away a
larger proposal to revamp federal housing programs. Some Democrats
had hoped to keep the two linked as a way to force congressional
action on the housing program revision.
   The bill requires that consultants and lobbyists working on HUD
programs register with the department and identify for whom they
are working, as well as any fees they receive. Civil penalties
would be imposed for those who fail to comply, and recipients of
HUD grants would have to report their use of consultants and
lobbyists.
   Other provisions:
   _Create a new HUD chief financial officer's position, as well as
a comptroller of the Federal Housing Administration, to oversee
financial management. It includes reforms in the FHA-insured
mortgage program, including a prohibition on loans for second homes.
   _Apply new restrictions on the Section 8 moderate rehabilitation
program, which provided subsidies for renovating low-income housing
that were at the heart of evidence of influence-peddling and
political favoritism in the HUD scandals. The bill limits the
number of housing units that may be subsidized per project to 100.
   _Authorize $25 million for HUD to monitor and evaluate its
programs _ less than the one-half of 1 percent of program spending,
or about $100 million, that Kemp sought.
   _Require full disclosure of HUD funding decisions, and place
restrictions on accounts for which the secretary has discretionary
authority.
   _Increase from 60 percent to 75 percent the amount of assistance
under the Community Development Block Grant that must be used for
projects benefiting the poor. Kemp had proposed an even tighter
requirement that spending go for the poor.
   _Restrict the administration's ability to fire the department's
inspector general.
</TEXT>
