<FIRST>r w PM-DrugWitness     11-15 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Witness,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hooded Former Drug Dealer Says Destroy Coca Crops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted drug dealer says the only way to
stop the cocaine trade is to destroy the coca crop in South America.
   ``Cut off the snake's head and the snake will die,'' he said.
``Go after the crop or the chemicals that process the coca. I don't
think anything else will do any good.''
   The witness who wore a black hood to conceal his identity _
``Mr. Witness,'' the congressmen called him _ insisted to a
skeptical House subcommittee Tuesday that stepped up efforts to
interdict the drug flow are fruitless.
   Wiping out the coca crop in Colombia and surrounding South
American nations might result in substitute crops springing up in
other regions of the world, he said, adding that such a move would
buy time.
   ``What we need now is a breather. It would take two to three
years to re-establish a useable crop of coca,'' he said. ``During
that time we could take steps to see that it is not done.''
   Such a move, he said, would be ``more practical than what we're
doing now.''
   The witness, arrested in 1985 after several years of overseeing
huge cocaine shipments from Colombia to Miami, said nothing can
stop the flow of cocaine once the coca crop is harvested and
processed into the drug.
   He said the drug importing cartels can change their tactics
``instantly'' to circumvent U.S. enforcement moves.
   For example, he said if efforts are concentrated on sealing off
borders along the Gulf Coast, the importers say: ``We'll let you
have fun there, we'll bring the stuff through California.''
   The witness was accompanied by a group of federal marshals
during his appearance before the House Banking subcommittee on
financial institutions supervision, regulation and insurance. His
voice was distorted electronically to help protect his identity.
   He said he is convinced the people of Colombia would support
eradication of coca crops if the United States provided economic
aid for poor coca farmers to replace their lost income.
   ``The cartel had the popular support of the people, but not
now,'' he said. ``All these bombings and raids have done more to
hurt the common man than anyone else.''
   He said he didn't ``know anything about money laundering,'' the
subcommittee's main area of jurisdiction in drug laws, but
suggested currency financial restrictions aren't as important as
several subcommittee members believe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
