<DOCNO> AP891115-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Pentagon-Soviet 360   11-15 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Soviet, 360</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Cites Cuts, But Pentagon Can't Provide Estimate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department says the Soviet Union has
cut its defense spending, but the Pentagon says it can't provide an
estimate until the year is over.
   ``It's too early to give a final estimate of Soviet defense
spending for 1989,'' State Department spokeswoman Margaret D.
Tutwiler said Tuesday. ``However, it does appear that Soviet
defense spending this year is less than it was last year.''
   The Bush administration has seen evidence of cuts in Soviet
defense efforts, including reductions in the production of
conventional weapons, she said.
   ``We have also seen withdrawals of conventional weapons and
troops from Eastern Europe and Mongolia,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   CIA estimates of Soviet military spending show a 1.5 percent
decline for this year, and intelligence officials project a decline
of 7 percent for 1990, The Washington Post reported in its
Wednesday editions, citing anonymous sources.
   Last week, at an arms control seminar near Queenstown, Md., a
U.S. official told reporters that the Soviets had cut tank
production and slowed production of Typhoon nuclear submarines.
   The official, who could not be identified under seminar rules,
said there was ``credible evidence'' of a cutback in tank output.
   But Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams, echoing statements made
earlier this week by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, disputed
reports the Soviets had slowed the modernization of some long-range
nuclear weapons or had evidence of cutbacks in conventional arms.
   ``There's obviously no way of knowing for sure what spending for
'89 is until 1989 is over,'' Williams said.
   However, Ms. Tutwiler said ``the experts'' believe there have
been reductions.
   House Armed Services Committee Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., said
two weeks ago that Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev had basically
fulfilled his pledge to reduce tank divisions in Eastern Europe.
   Gorbachev promised last December to withdraw six divisions over
two years. Aspin, who recently visited the Soviet Union and Eastern
Europe, said regiments amounting to three divisions had been
withdrawn.
   Gorbachev also promised to cut military spending by 14 percent
and to remove 500,000 men from the Soviet armed forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
