<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-15 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Market Index Hits Record High; Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at
a record high Wednesday, while the dollar edged down against the
yen.
   The dollar closed at 143.37 yen, down 0.43 yen from Tuesday's
143.80-yen finish. It opened at 143.23 yen and ranged between
143.18 yen and 143.40 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 83.59 points, or 0.23
percent, closing at 35,852.23, yet another high. The index had
gained 18.52 points for a record closing of 35,768.64 Tuesday.
   ``The index rose following Tuesday's release of the domestic
wholesale price index,'' said a Nomura Securities dealer, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Japan's wholesale price index in October fell by 0.6 percentage
points from a month earlier, the first decline in 11 months.
   The dealer said the decline reassured market players that
Japan's interest rates are no longer likely to rise higher. Lower
interest rates encourage stock buying.
   In currency dealings, the dollar's drop followed a similar
downswing overnight in New York, triggered by steeper-than-expected
slides in U.S. economic data.
   The United States reported Tuesday that the nation's retail
sales fell 1 percent in October, while industrial production
dropped 0.7 percentage points that month.
   Dealers said market players were inclined to sell the dollar and
buy the yen expecting that the U.S. monetary policy will be eased.
   A Bank of Tokyo trader said the U.S. currency will contine to
move narrowly around its opening level until the release of the
U.S. trade figures for September, due out in Washington Thursday.
</TEXT>
