<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     11-15 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Upsurge In Sports Cable Broadcasts Defended By Tagliabue, Vincent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professional football and baseball
commissioners say the move of sports programming to cable is making
games available to more, not fewer, fans.
   National Football League Commissioner Paul Tagliabue and
Baseball Commissioner Fay Vincent sat side-by-side during a Senate
Judiciary subcommittee hearing Tuesday, and were grilled by
lawmakers about the shift of baseball and football telecasts to
ESPN and other cable networks.
   The National Association of Broadcasters said in a prepared
statement that Congress should get involved because the trend was
``leading to a sports blackout for nearly half of the nation which
does not have cable.''
   NAB President Edward O. Fritts said Congress could direct the
Federal Communications Commission to reinstitute anti-siphoning
rules, which have not been in place since 1977, to assure viewers
access to sports broadcasts.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., asked Tagliabue for a ``flat
commitment'' that fans would not begin to be assessed a flat fee to
view a broadcast of pro football's jewel, the Super Bowl. Such a
``pay-per-view'' arrangement is used for some top-draw boxing
matches.
   ``For the balance of this century, we do not foresee
pay-per-view for the Super Bowl game,'' Tagliabue said. He said he
could not foresee what might happen after that.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Hawkins Flunks Bush as `Education President'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Education and Labor
Committee says President Bush, the would-be ``education
president,'' is blocking the education secretary from doing a good
job.
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., told reporters Tuesday at the
National Press Club, ``I feel rather presumptive in grading the
president but I've been asked to do so.'' He then harshly
criticized Bush, who pledged to become the ``education president''
if elected.
   ``There is not a single accomplishment, initiative, or
educational credit with which the president can be identified, even
if the summit is so regarded,'' said Hawkins, referring to the
recent two-day meeting of Bush and the nation's governors that
resulted in a push for national performance goals.
   However, Hawkins was kinder to Education Secretary Lauro
Cavazos, noting ``he and I are very, very friendly.''
   ``I think he's a fine, honorable man. I think he has good
motives,'' said Hawkins. ``I think that if he was not restrained,
he probably would do very well. I think under the restraints, he
can't.''
   Hawkins said Cavazos is being hampered by policies pushed by the
Office of Management and Budget and the White House, which ``I
think differ diametrically from his own philosophy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Congressman Would Have Coins Pay to Aid Firefighters</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sponsor of a House bill to help
firefighters wants to pay for it by having the government mint and
sell a commemorative coin.
   A bill by Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., to create a ``fireservice
bill of rights'' would be funded though sale of coins minted to
commemorate the bicentennial of the death of Benjamin Franklin.
   The coins had already been planned, and the bill would earmark
25 percent of the money for a Benjamin Franklin National Memorial,
with the rest going to help train and equip firefighters, set up a
hazardous materials communications network, and help the survivors
of firefighters killed in action.
   Weldon insisted at a hearing of the Science, Space and
Technology subcommittee on science, research and technology that
the measure was not a tax. He said the firefighters' foundation
would take private donations as well.
   The administration, through Edward M. Wall of the U.S. Fire
Administration, said such a sale would provide inadequate revenue.
</TEXT>
