<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CosmicExplorer     11-15 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cosmic Explorer,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Launch Now Saturday For Cosmic Explorer on NASA's Last Unmanned Rocket</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After replacing a flawed computer on its
last unmanned rocket, NASA set Saturday for the launch of the first
of several satellites that will reveal an ``unbelievable view of
the universe.''
   ``Hold on to your hats because this is going to shake up the
world of science,'' program scientist Larry Caroff said of the
Cosmic Background Explorer spacecraft and four observatories that
will be placed in Earth orbit during the 1990s.
   Saturday's launch of the $150 million Explorer spacecraft _ the
centerpiece of a $400 million mission _ ``is going to begin an
explosion of knowledge about the universe,'' program manager David
Gilman told reporters Tuesday at the space agency's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   The 4,850-pound Explorer will provide clues to the development
of the universe by measuring radiation left over from the ``big
bang,'' the explosion scientists say created the universe 15
billion years ago.
   Gilman said the Explorer will be followed by the launches of
what NASA calls its ``great observatories'' _ the Hubble Space
Telescope next March, the Gamma Ray Observatory in June, the
Advanced X-ray Astrophysics Facility in 1997 and the Space Infrared
Telescope Facility in 1999.
   ``These are going to provide us with an unprecedented,
unbelievable view of the universe,'' Caroff said in an interview.
``We will see things we haven't even imagined.''
   The Explorer is scheduled for launch from Vandenberg Air Force
Base during a 30-minute period starting at 6:24 a.m. PST Saturday,
said Roger Mattson, project manager at NASA's Goddard Space Flight
Center in Greenbelt, Md.
   The launch had been scheduled for Friday, then was delayed until
Sunday because of a malfunctioning rocket guidance computer. But
the computer was replaced so quickly last weekend that the launch
was moved again, said Peter Eaton, a NASA rocket official.
   The solar-powered satellite will be carried into a near-polar
orbit by a 116-foot-tall Delta rocket _ the last unmanned,
expendable rocket ever to be launched by the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration.
   NASA will continue to launch manned shuttles and possibly
unmanned cargo shuttles with reusable boosters. But Air Force or
private companies will charge NASA to launch any payloads that
require unmanned expendable rockets.
   After a 30-day shakedown in orbit, the Explorer will spend up to
two years measuring ``cosmic background radiation,'' which makes up
about 2 percent of the static on a television set. It includes
microwaves, heat and other electromagnetic radiation given off by
the big bang.
   The Explorer will measure ``the collective glow of all the stars
and galaxies and whatever else has been there since the
beginning,'' project scientist John Mather said.
   He said NASA will share information from the mission with the
Soviet Union, which has flown one similar research mission and
plans two others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
