<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-15 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks in Tokyo Hit Record High; Dollar Closes Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose to a
record high today, while the dollar closed lower against the
Japanese yen.
   The dollar ended trading at 143.37 yen, down 0.43 yen from
Tuesday's close of 143.80 yen. The currency opened lower at 143.23
yen and ranged between 143.18 yen and 143.40 yen.
   ``Trading today was totally directionless and boring,'' said a
trader with Mitsui Bank in Tokyo on condition of anonymity. ``Ahead
of the release of the U.S. trade figures, the dollar-yen rate moved
only narrowly.''
   The trader said Tokyo is expecting the U.S. trade deficit for
September to shrink to $8.5 billion. Washington's trade figure
announcement is scheduled for Thursday.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues gained 83.59 points, or 0.23 percent. It ended at 35,852.23,
renewing the record high for the third-consecutive time since
Monday.
   The index, which has been rising since last Wednesday, has
gained more than 580 points.
   The index slowed its upward movement in the afternoon session as
participants sold for profit-taking and arbitrary deals, which
resulted in wild fluctuations in the index, dealers said.
   Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities, said market
players' buying incentive was not strong enough for a larger
one-day gain even after a report that Japan's wholesale price index
fell by 0.6 percentage points from a month earlier. It was the
first drop in the last 11 months.
   ``Investors wouldn't start buying all of a sudden just because
of the wholesale price index, becuase our domestic short term
interst rate hasn't fallen,'' he said.
   ``Market players will increase buying gradually as they make
sure external economic factors are stable enough,'' Nomura added.
   An estimated 1.2 billion shares changed hands on the first
section, up from Tuesday's 900 million. Among the winners were
construction, railway and financial issues.
</TEXT>
