<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Akers     11-15 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Akers,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dean of Yo-Yo Men Dead at 80</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard ``Barnie'' Akers, one of the
original Duncan yo-yo men who died at age 80, was remembered as a
man with a smile on his face and a yo-yo in each hand.
   Akers died Friday at a Huntington hospital. A memorial service
has not been scheduled.
   Akers' uncle, Donald F. Duncan, popularized the toy in America
during the Great Depression and set up an exhibition schedule with
dozens of men traveling from town-to-town, telling stories and
selling yo-yos.
   Stuart Crump, editor of Yo-Yo Times, a Washington, D.C.-based
magazine for yo-yo enthusiasts, said Tuesday that Akers was one of
the best.
   ``He was probably the most important link with the great yo-yo
years,'' Crump said. ``He actually almost single-handedly created
the yo-yo contest,'' a competition designed to increase yo-yo sales.
   ``I will remember him with a smile on his face and two yo-yos in
his hands,'' said Crump, who last saw Akers last winter while in
Charleston to record music to yo-yo by.
   Akers never married. He said in an interview last summer that a
yo-yo man's life, like the toy, is up and down.
   ``I had a few girlfriends, but they didn't realize that if you
do something like this 10 months a year, it gets tiring. I would
travel 800 miles in a day just to get to a new market,'' Akers said.
   ``If you get married, a woman thinks she would like that, like
it was a two-week vacation. Not many would like it. Not for 50
years.''
   Akers had surgery for prostate problems during the summer and
fought lymphoma. He died in the hospital, but his brother,
Franklin, another yo-yo man who left the trade, said he believed
Akers died of a weak heart.
   Barnie Akers didn't like calling the yo-yo a toy, saying it
taught too many skills _ like eye-and-hand coordination and
discipline.
   In his spiels, he used to give a history of the yo-yo, telling
how ancient vases discovered in Greece show wooden knobs suspended
on strings.
   ``Go back before the birth of Christ and you can see how the
string is tied on their fingers,'' Akers said.
</TEXT>
