<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Glance, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0463,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania's Abortion Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES to include bill's provisions for penalties against doctors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Abortion, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania's abortion bill passed the
House 143-58 on Oct. 24 and the Senate 33-17 on Tuesday. Gov.
Robert P. Casey has said he will sign the bill.
   The bill would:
   _Ban abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy, except in cases
where the mother faces irreversible harm or death. Doctors who
violate the guidelines would be guilty of a third degree felony,
punishable by up to 7 years in prison and up to $15,000 in fines.
   _Require doctors to inform women about the procedure before
performing an abortion, provide her with the likely age of the
fetus and explain risks and alternatives.
   _Prohibit abortions because of the fetus' sex, proving a prison
term of up to seven years with up to $15,000 in fines for doctors
who violate the provision.
   _Establish a 24-hour wait from the time a woman asks for an
abortion until it is performed.
   _Require women to notify their husbands if they plan to get an
abortion, although there are exceptions. A physician who failed to
get a form indicating the husband's notification would be liable
for civil damages to the husband, punitive damages of $5,000 and
suspension or loss of license.
   _Regulate the medical use of tissue from aborted fetuses.
</TEXT>
