<FIRST>r a PM-ParentsSued     11-15 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Parents Sued,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>4-Year-Old Sues Mom, Wins $75,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 4-year-old Christopher Hoy was
seriously injured in a two-car accident two years ago, he sued the
driver of the car in which he was riding _ his mom.
   On Tuesday, Christopher won a $75,000 settlement of the lawsuit
against his parents. He also won a $50,000 settlement against the
driver of the second car. Both parties' insurance carriers will pay
the boy the money.
   The case was tried last week in state Supreme Court, and his
mother, Barbara J. Hoy, testified she was not speeding before the
accident, as her son's lawsuit claimed.
   Christopher, who is now 6, was placed in the unusual position of
suing his parents over the accident because the court decided his
mother was partly responsible for the crash, said his lawyer,
Edward Menkin.
   A jury had ruled Barbara Hoy was 30 percent responsible for the
accident, and the other driver, Sharon M. Hawthorne, was 70 percent
responsible.
   Because the court decided the mother was partially to blame, the
boy had to sue both parties, Menkin said.
   Barbara Hoy and her husband, Norman, were pleased when the suit
was settled with the $125,000 going to their son.
   ``We're happy about the result,'' said Hoy, who was named as a
defendant because he owned the car. ``It's common for occupants of
a vehicle to sue the driver. This just happened to be mother and
son.''
   Christopher suffered a broken leg, broken nose and broken back
in the Jan. 5, 1987, accident. He spent nine days in a hospital and
three months in a body cast, and has recovered from the injuries
except for a fused spine, Menkin said.
</TEXT>
