<FIRST>r a PM-ShipFire     11-15 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ship Fire,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Aboard Docked Helicopter Carrier Injures 31</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Navy Accidents, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that injured 31 people on the
amphibious assault ship USS Inchon apparently was caused by a short
circuit in an electrical compartment, the Navy said.
   Twelve people were hospitalized; the others treated and released.
   The fire, which started about 9:30 a.m. Tuesday and was
extinguished in about 40 minutes, was one of a series of recent
accidents that prompted the Navy later in the day to order a
48-hour halt to all normal operations for a review of safety
procedures.
   In the past three weeks, the Navy has experienced 10 serious
accidents in which 10 people have been killed or lost at sea and at
least 53 have been injured. The recent series of accidents followed
the April 19 explosion on the battleship USS Iowa in which 47
sailors died.
   The Inchon fire broke out as the ship was in the Metroc Machine
Corp. shipyard for routine repair work.
   Lt. Cmdr. Steve Burnett, a spokesman for the Atlantic Fleet,
said the blaze apparently was caused by a short circuit and that
most of the damage was to electrical cables and insulation in the
shore power compartment. There also was smoke and heat damage to
the hangar deck.
   The compartment holds cables from the pier bringing electricity
to the ship.
   Lt. Cmdr. John Lloyd, another Atlantic Fleet spokesman, said 23
sailors and eight civilians were taken to area hospitals. The
condition of the 12 admitted for smoke inhalation ranged from
stable to serious, according to the hospitals.
   The 602-foot troop and helicopter carrier has a crew of 675 and
can hold up to 2,000 Marines and 20 helicopters when on deployment.
   The Inchon entered the shipyard Sept. 21 for a four-month
overhaul.
</TEXT>
