<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Bridge     11-15 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Bridge,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridge Opening Delayed For Autos, But Big Walk Slated for Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people are expected to
participate in a walk across the 8.5-mile San Francisco-Oakland Bay
Bridge, which lost a 50-foot section in the Oct. 17 earthquake that
tore through northern California.
   The walk Thursday over the Bay Bridge that links Oakland and San
Francisco will cost $5 and feature entertainers Carol Channing and
Tony Bennett. It will be limited to 40,000 people.
   Some of the fees will go to quake relief, but the main purpose
seemed to be to celebrate the bridge's scheduled Saturday reopening
to traffic and the spirit of Bay area residents in dealing with the
quake.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner hailed the cooperation
that mended the bridge.
   ``Bureaucracy has been beaten,'' Skinner told a news conference
Tuesday.
   ``It looks great,'' he said while flanked by the mayors of San
Francisco, Oakland and Alameda on the upper deck's newly installed
concrete.
   He referred to the re-opening as Nov. 17, a month after the
7.1-magnitude earthquake that killed 66 people and caused $7
billion in damage, unaware that the state Department of
Transportation earlier in the day pushed the date to Nov. 18.
   Cars and other vehicles will start rolling across the bridge
``as soon as possible'' on Saturday, said Burch Bachtold, the state
Department of Transportation district director who guided Skinner
during his brief visit to the 53-year-old bridge.
   Department officials said the delay was needed because two days
of damp weather slowed work on the bridge.
   The span's repair represents a ``magnificent effort by state,
local and federal officials,'' said Skinner.
</TEXT>
