<FIRST>r p PM-Twins-Mayor     11-15 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Twins-Mayor,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor's Job Stays in the Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Identical twin brothers who have
monopolized the mayor's office here for 42 years will continue
their small-town dynasty following a 26-vote election victory.
   ``I'm surprised I didn't win by a greater majority, but a win is
a win,'' Knox Ridley said Tuesday night after being re-elected to a
four-year term.
   Unofficial returns showed that Ridley received 1,185 votes to
Denise Esker's 1,159. Mrs. Esker, a homemaker and former city
employee making her first bid for political office, said she would
decide today whether to seek a recount.
   Ridley, who served on the Rutherford County Court for a
quarter-century and was a justice of the peace, was appointed
interim mayor two years ago to replace his brother Sam, who was
ousted for misusing public money.
   The 70-year-old twins, born 30 minutes apart, are still close.
They dress similarly, wear glasses and have gray, balding hair.
Knox is described by locals as ``the one with the hearing aid.''
   It's little wonder, then, that townsfolk speculate that Sam
Ridley, who held the post for 40 years, still pulls the strings.
Sam became mayor in 1947 but was ousted after the courts found he
misused $11,000 from the city's 1980 budget.
   Knox Ridley doesn't try to distance himself from his brother,
referring to Sam as his ``chief of staff.'' Sam campaigned actively
for Knox.
   The cozy relationship between the brothers was the main issue
for Mrs. Esker.
   ``It's still as crooked now as it was then,'' she said during
the campaign.
   Mrs. Esker said the close vote scared the Ridleys. ``I think
they will have even more people watching them now,'' she said.
   She had hammered on the theme that Smyrna needed a change in
leadership, noting the town outside Nashville had 500 people when
Sam Ridley became mayor. Today, Smyrna is a growing city of 13,000,
boasting a sprawling new plant where Nissan produces light trucks
and cars.
   Knox Ridley agrees the times are changing, but says he _
referrring to himself in the the plural _ has changed, too.
   ``We might have old age, but we have a young heart and a young
mind,'' he said.
</TEXT>
