<FIRST>r a PM-Farmers-TradeBoard     11-15 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farmers-Trade Board,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Farmers' Lawsuit Accuses BOT of Illegal Price Manipulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade is denying farmers'
allegations that it illegally manipulated soybean prices with an
emergency order last summer.
   The order led to a 20 percent drop in soybean prices along with
corresponding declines in other commodities, and caused heavy
financial losses among family farmers nationwide, the American
Agriculture Movement says.
   The group, a lobbying organization that represents small farmers
and rural business people in 34 states, and family farmers from
leading soybean-producing states, filed a federal lawsuit Tuesday
against the BOT.
   The lawsuit seeks more than $100 million in damages.
   The complaint stems from the Board of Trade's emergency action
July 11 ordering traders to reduce their holdings in soybean
futures contracts.
   The board's move was widely viewed as an effort to break up an
attempt to corner the market by Ferruzzi Finanziaria SpA, an
Italian company and one of the world's largest soybean processors.
   ``The CBOT's order was a bad faith and self-serving action
initiated by the CBOT's dominant grain merchants and futures
traders to create profits for their accounts and for their
clients,'' said Harvey Joe Sanner, AAM's president and an Arkansas
soybean farmer.
   Sanner spoke at a news conference at a downtown hotel,
accompanied by about 25 other farmers from Illinois, Iowa,
Missouri, Indiana, Minnesota, Ohio, Nebraska, Arkansas, Kansas and
South Dakota _ many of whom said they had been devastated by the
board action.
   ``I'm angry as hell about what has been done to us as producers
of this nation,'' said Corky Jones, a soybean farmer from
Brownville, Neb.
   The BOT, meanwhile, has slapped Ferruzzi's Central Soya unit
with a $1,000-a-day fine for failing to provide documents the
exchange says are needed for an investigation into the Italian
company's actions.
   But a Central Soya spokesman said the company is cooperating
with the investigation and has agreed to provide the documents _
rail contracts between the company and its shippers.
   The lawsuit filed Tuesday names as defendants the exchange, BOT
Chairman Karsten Mahlmann and 21 other directors, along with five
other exchange officials.
   After the news conference, the group _ carrying banners and
buckets of soybeans _ marched five blocks to the Board of Trade.
   BOT spokesman Raymond Carmichael said officials were in
meetings. He agreed to take the soybeans to exchange officials as a
symbol of the complaint.
   In a news release, Mahlmann said exchange officials had not seen
the lawsuit, but are ``confident in the action taken ... by the
board of directors to maintain an orderly liquidation in our July
1989 soybean futures contract.''
   He said board officials ``expect this lawsuit to be proven
frivolous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FaxedBallot     11-15 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Faxed Ballot,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Absentee Ballots Cast by Fax in Vermont Referendum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALAIS, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Age-old tradition met the information age as
absentee ballots sent by fax to a couple on a trip to California
were returned by an overnight delivery service in time to be
counted.
   Resident Chris Lynn set up his facsimile machine Tuesday in the
town clerk's office so absentee ballots in a school bond vote could
be sent to his friends, Richard and Teri Barnaby.
   ``This is certainly unique,'' said Deputy Secretary of State
Paul Gillies when he heard of the new way of distributing paper
ballots. ``I don't think this has ever happened in Vermont before.
... It's really kind of exciting.''
   The Barnabys had gone to the West Coast on a business trip.
   Facsimile machines allow transmission of printed matter over
telephone lines. But they don't allow the for the sealed envelopes
required for secret ballots, Town Clerk Eva Morse explained.
   Residents were voting for the second time on a $1.05 million
plan to expand the town elementary school. The measure passed
narrowly in September. Opponents gathered enough signatures on a
petition to call for another vote.
   Gillies said Morse called him Monday to ask whether the fax was
a legal way to distribute absentee ballots.
   ``I don't think that the people who drafted the absentee ballot
laws in the 18th century knew about fax machines,'' he said.
   But he said a fax would probably meet the legal definition of a
mailed ballot, and consequently could be allowed.
</TEXT>
