<DOCNO> AP891115-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     11-15 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crackdown Continues against Sinhalese Extremists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops raided a clandestine radio
station and captured its operator in a dragnet that is decimating
the leadership of an extremist group of Sinhalese nationalists,
military officials said today.
   In addition, the bodies of 31 suspected Sinhalese extremists
were discovered at daybreak in the central hills, the officials
said. They blamed the killings on pro-government vigilante groups.
   The government's 2-year-old battle to subdue the People's
Liberation Front took a dramatic turn Monday with the reported
capture and killing of the group's senior leader, Rohana Wijeweera.
   According to a military source, the avowed Marxist ``sang like a
bird'' about the whereabouts of his top lieutenants. In less than
18 hours, Wijeweera and the front's No. 2 and No. 3 men were killed
by security forces, according to government announcements.
   More than 6,000 people have been killed since August 1987 in
violence associated with the People's Liberation Front's
assassination campaign targeting governing officials and supporters.
   The front professed outrage that the Sinhalese-dominated
government made concessions to the Tamil minority, and its battle
escalated into a challenge of the government's right to exist.
   The military officials said the raid on the front's clandestine
radio station was carried out Tuesday night in Boralesgamuwa, six
miles southeast of Colombo.
   The front member in charge of the station, Andreas Costa, was
captured and radio equipment worth $1.3 million seized, according
to the officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   The short-wave radio station was called Voice of the Revolution.
It broadcast three days a week, varying its hours to avoid jamming,
and transmitted Wijeweera's speeches, revolutionary songs and
allegations of government atrocities.
   The front, as well as human rights activists and opposition
politicians, have long accused the government of fielding or
tolerating death squads bent on wiping out the front.
   Some government officials have privately acknowledged that
``excesses'' may have occurred, but they usually blamed the
killings of suspected front members on shadowy vigilante groups.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne claimed Tuesday that six of
the front's seven Politburo members had been killed. But the
military officials said today the Politburo had expanded to nine
members, of whom seven were known to have been killed.
   Although killings blamed on the front have tapered off this
week, it is too soon to say whether the front is finished or simply
regrouping.
   The bodies of the suspected front members were found in two
locations in the center of the island Wednesday.
   Twenty-three badly mutilated bodies were discovered in
Keppitipola, about 65 miles east of Colombo. Eight more bodies were
found in Kandy, 55 miles northeast of Colombo.
   The violence by the Sinhalese extremists erupted after the Sri
Lankan government signed an Indian-sponsored peace accord on July
29, 1987, in an effort to end a Tamil insurrection that started in
1983. The accord spawned a Sinhalese backlash as members of the
ethnic majority accused their government of making too many
concessions to the Tamil minority.
   Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
are mostly Hindus and claim the predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese
majority discriminated against them in jobs and education.
   Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population, have
dominated the government and military since Sri Lanka, formerly
called Ceylon, became independent from Britain in 1948.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ParkJogger     11-15 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Park Jogger,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jogger Who Was Beaten and Gang-raped in Central Park Released From
Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jogger who was gang-raped and badly beaten
in Central Park will spend Thanksgiving at home with her family,
her father said.
   She was released Tuesday from a Connecticut hospital after what
doctors said was a remarkable recovery after being left for dead.
   Her father said he was ``thrilled to have her back,'' and was
preparing a ``quiet Thanksgiving family celebration.''
   In state Supreme Court on Tuesday, the prosecution rested after
four weeks of testimony in a hearing on whether statements six
defendents gave police should be allowed as evidence at their
upcoming rape and attempted murder trials.
   Defense lawyers maintain the statements, in which nearly all the
youths implicate themselves or their co-defendants, were coerced
and therefore illegal.
   A spokesman for Gaylord Hospital in Wallingford, Conn., said the
jogger would continue to be treated there on an outpatient basis.
   ``She continues to have post-traumatic amnesia,'' said spokesman
Gerald Main, ``but she has made good recovery and rehabilitation.''
   Head injuries often lead to post-traumatic amnesia, in which the
victim cannot remember what took place immediately before, during,
and for some time after the injury.
   The jogger, a 29-year-old investment banker, was dragged 200
feet into the underbrush, raped, beaten with a pipe and a rock and
left unconscious April 19. She had been on her nightly run.
   When police found her 3{ hours later, she was in a coma and had
lost almost 80 percent of her blood. She had suffered brain
contusions, two head fractures, broken facial bones and bruises
from head to toe.
   She remained in critical condition at a hospital until May 1,
when she raised her hand and appeared to raise her eyebrows as her
name was called. She was walking a bit when she was moved June 7 to
Gaylord.
   By midsummer, she was reading novels, relearning basic math
skills and calling colleagues at Salomon Bros., where she had
worked before the attack.
   Main said the jogger and her family thanked the public and press
for their support over the past seven months, saying it ``made a
difference in her ability to recover.''
   The family also thanked the news media for respecting her
privacy and anonymity and stressed that the woman's continued
recovery ``is highly dependent'' on these being maintained, Main
said.
</TEXT>
