<FIRST>r a PM-Carter-Nicaragua     11-15 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carter-Nicaragua,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter: Sandinistas Trying to Smear Foes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter said the Sandinista
government was attemptingm to unfairly tie Nicaragua's civilian
opposition coalition to the U.S.-backed Contra rebels.
   Carter, who will lead an official team monitoring Nicaragua's
Feb. 25 elections, said at a seminar Tuesday at his Presidential
Center that he has complained privately to Sandinista
representatives about a news article in the official Sandinista
newspaper, Barricada.
   The publication attacked Alfredo Cesar, a member of Nicaragua's
National Opposition campaign committee. Carter said the newspaper
``has apparently published a totally fraudulent letter ostensibly
written'' by Cesar.
   Carter said Barricada has tied the opposition coalition ``with
the Contra military activity in a completely illegitimate fashion.''
   Cesar, speaking at the seminar, claimed that President Daniel
Ortega's decision to end a 19-month ceasefire in the war with the
Contras was due to the tight race he faced for reelection against
Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, the candidate of the National
Opposition Union, a coalition that represents 12 of 21 registered
Nicaraguan parties.
   A new, independent poll of Nicaraguan voters commissioned by a
Miami television station and released Tuesday showed Ortega and
Chamorro in a dead heat. The poll was taken in late October.
   Ortega announced two weeks ago he was canceling the ceasefire,
citing increased attacks by Contras trying to disrupt the elections.
   Cesar, however, cited Nicaraguan government figures showing that
such attacks had decreased in October.
   When the Sandinistas agreed last summer to advance the elections
from November to February, he said, they did not think they would
be seriously challenged.
   ``That equation has changed,'' he said.
   Cesar also accused the Sandinistas of forging documents that
tied the opposition coalition to the Contras. He said the coalition
has condemned violence from all sides.
   Alejandro Bendana, secretary-general of Nicaragua's foreign
ministry, said fair and free elections are an issue but so is
sovereignty.
   ``Independence is a prerequisite of democracy. American policy
fails to recognize the link between the democratic process and
self-determination,'' he said.
   ``We are not running these elections to satisfy the United
States,'' he said. He said the United States may ``have to live
with a democratically elected government that is not of its
liking.''
   Carter said he believes the Bush administration will honor the
results and probably lift the 4-year-old trade embargo with
Nicaragua no matter who wins if the independent observer groups
report clean elections.
   Carter said his team will try to monitor voting at about 10
percent of the Nicaraguan polling places and compare the vote
tallied there with the votes turned in to the central counting
point.
   The former president led an official monitoring team at
elections May 7 in Panama. Carter denounced that election as
fraudulent.
</TEXT>
