<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in thin trading in Europe late
this morning. Gold prices rose.
   Currency dealers said the market was waiting for Thursday's
scheduled release of U.S. trade figures.
   ``In Europe, it's quiet again, the movements come only in the
Far East and New York,'' said a dealer at a major West German bank.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.43 yen to a closing 143.37 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 143.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8395 West German marks, down from 1.8540
   _1.6235 Swiss francs, down from 1.6380
   _6.2470 French francs, down from 6.2925
   _2.0742 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0925
   _1,348.25 Italian lire, down from 1,357.00
   _1.1690 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1710
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5872 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5810 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $391.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $390.00. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $390.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $391.00 compared with $389.00 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 43 cents to close at a bid
$391.94.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.38 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.31.
