<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-EGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0495 11-15 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-EGermany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Warns West Not to Take Advantage of East Bloc Changes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Yakovlev comment. Picks up
4th pvs, `Gorbachev issued...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev, concerned by Western powers'
response to the democratic upheaval in Eastern Europe, urged them
not to sour the new spirit of international cooperation by
``exporting capitalism'' to the region.
   He made the comments six days after East Germany's embattled
Communist leaders let their citizens travel freely to the West and
as Western countries appropriate hundreds of million of dollars in
aid for Poland and Hungary.
   Other top Soviet officials joined their president in condemning
any Western attempts to exploit the current instability in the East
bloc and throwing cold water on calls for German reunification.
   In Tokyo, Gorbachev adviser Alexander Yakovlev said he was
surprised by Western commentators who interpret the tumult in the
region as demonstrating the failure of socialism and Soviet policy.
   ``This is an obsolete, archaic way of thinking,'' the Politburo
member told a news conference today. ``We would like to have a
common European house based on freedom. If someone interferes in
that process, we might go back to the time of the Cold War. We are
standing at such a juncture.''
   Gorbachev issued his warning to the West in a Kremlin meeting
Tuesday with Foreign Minister Roland Dumas of France.
   ``It is useless to clamor about victory in the Cold War, about
the disintegration of some or other social system,'' Tass
paraphrased Gorbachev as saying. ``Everything should be analyzed
realistically and interests should be balanced.''
   He then urged Western leaders not to practice their own form of
socio-economic imperialism.
   ``When accusations of `exporting revolutions' are replaced with
calls for `exporting capitalism,' we have at hand a dangerous
manifestation of old thinking,'' Tass paraphrased Gorbachev as
saying.
   Gorbachev made the comments as West Germany's economics
minister, Helmut Haussmann, offered to rebuild East Germany's
economy through broad-based investments and joint ventures and to
overhaul the country's moribund communications and transport
systems.
   While not offering details, Haussmann said such aid would occur
only if East Germany carried out a ``thorough change'' of its
centrally planned economy.
   In a June 15 news conference in Bonn, West Germany, Gorbachev
declared the Cold War over but did not take credit for ending it,
as he now apparently is accusing the West of doing.
   The Kremlin has called for negotiating an end to the Warsaw Pact
and NATO as military alliances, turning them into purely political
groups that cooperate more closely. Gorbachev also has called for
cooperation between the European Economic Community and COMECON,
the East bloc's economic alliance.
   On Tuesday, Gorbachev indicated these groups should not be
scrapped but rather transformed into bodies that foster stability.
   ``It is no time to destroy the established international
political and economic institutions. Let them transform themselves
with taking into account internal processes, let them find
themselves a niche in the new situation and interact,'' Tass quoted
him as saying.
   Gorbachev praised the changes that have taken place in
individual Eastern European countries without identifying them.
   In the past several months, dizzying changes have swept through
the East bloc.
   East Germany's ruling Communists ousted their longtime leader,
Erich Honecker, last month and on Thursday opened their borders in
an effort to win credibility with a people demanding free elections
and an end to the Communist monopoly on power.
   Czechoslovakia on Tuesday granted its citizens free travel
abroad.
   On Friday, Bulgaria replaced its longtime Communist leader,
Todor Zhivkov.
   In August, Poland became the first East bloc nation with a
government not led by Communists.
   Last month, Hungary's Communists changed the name of their party
to the Hungarian Socialist Party and endorsed a transition to
parliamentary democracy, promising free elections by June.
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and his French
counterpart clashed Tuesday over whether reunification of East and
West Germany is desireable.
   According to Tass, Shevardnadze expressed ``great concern'' with
West German officials pushing for reunification.
   He said such talk encroaches on East Germany's sovereignty. In a
separate speech, the Soviet envoy added that other countries should
not ``profit by the complications, tie on various kinds of advice
or conditions.''
   In his speech, however, Dumas said France and West Germany want
``European unity'' and he called for resolving the ``German
question,'' Tass reported. Dumas said this should not be seen as a
threat, risk or danger by other countries.
   The Soviet Union has about 380,000 troops in East Germany, which
has since the end of World War II been the linchpin in their
European defense corridor.
</TEXT>
