<BYLINE>William Thomas Harris</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Thomas Harris, who started as a
clerk and built a grocery store chain, died Tuesday at age 81 after
giving a speech demanding that a Baptist convention change the name
of a local college.
   Harris had called for Wingate College to be changed to
Cannon-Wingate University to honor Charles Cannon, a textile
magnate who has given millions to the school. Harris had been
embroiled in a year-long dispute with state Baptists over the name
change.
   His motion was defeated after Harris collapsed and was taken
away.
   Harris grew up on a farm in his native Cordele, Ga., quitting
school in the 10th grade and working his way up to become an A&amp;P
grocery store manager before starting his own Charlotte store in
1936.
   His Harris-Teeter Supermarket chain, which has 128 stores in
Virginia, North Carolina, South Carolina and Tennessee, did more
than $1 billion in sales last year.
