<FIRST>r i PM-EastGermany-Lottery     11-15 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany-Lottery,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Visiting the West Hits the Lottery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Of the millions of East Germans who
rushed to the West when travel barriers were lifted, one man really
hit the jackpot.
   The 40-year-old mechanic, identified only as Guenther, arrived
Friday just in time to buy a ticket for the Lower Saxony state
lottery, the Bild newspaper said. On Saturday night, he learned he
won 1.2 million marks ($650,000).
   ``I saw the numbers drawn on television and knew I had all
six,'' Bild quoted Guenther as saying. Lottery drawings are
broadcast regularly on Saturday evening television in West Germany.
   Guenther contacted the state lottery office on Monday by
telephone and asked what he had won, Bild said.
   ``You have won 1.2 million marks,'' he was told.
   ``What can I buy with it?'' he asked.
   ``A Mercedes, a house, and the rest I can put in the bank for
you and you'll draw 5,000 marks ($2,700) a month in interest after
taxes,'' Bild quoted the lottery official as responding.
   The lucky East German has since returned to his home in Herzberg
where he said he intends to continue to live and work, while making
regular weekend visits to West Germany, Bild said.
   Identities and addresses of lottery winners in West Germany are
not normally made public in order to protect their privacy.
  
