<FIRST>r a PM-Dukakis     11-15 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Puts Final Nail in `Massachusetts Miracle' Coffin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis conceded for the
first time that the Massachusetts Miracle that nearly carried him
to the White House is no more.
   But the former Democratic candidate for president said Tuesday
that the formula that produced a white-hot economy in the early
1980s can bring Massachusetts back from the brink of recession.
   ``The miracle of the '80s may be over, but the fundamental
strengths that made it happen are still here _ daring entrepreneurs
and productive workers, great universities and great hospitals,''
the governor said.
   ``I don't plan to spend the next 14 months ... debating whether
or not we're in a recession. I plan to spend that time laying the
foundation we will need to make the 1990s every bit as good or
better than the '80s.''
   Declining revenue has left the state with a $720 million budget
deficit and budget cuts are threatening already strapped social,
construction and educational programs.
   Dukakis' comments came in an address at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology in which he outlined his blueprint for
economic success in the 1990s. Dukakis has said he will leave
office when his term is up after 1990.
   The governor called for revitalized state construction,
expansion in manufacturing and the troubled high-tech industry and
aggressive recruitment of international investment to capitalize on
the European Community's economic merger in 1992.
   ``Massachusetts must go international with a vengeance,'' he
said.
   Dukakis was chatty and joking at the outset of his speech, the
first time he was visibly at ease in public since his wife, Kitty,
was hospitalized last week after drinking rubbing alcohol.
   ``I believe in the economic future of this commonwealth because
I believe in the time-tested qualities of the people of this state
_ their creativity and innovation and determination,'' he said.
</TEXT>
