<FIRST>u i PM-Brazil 2ndLd-Writethru a0517 11-15 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0517,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilians Vote in First Presidential Election in 29 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with polls opening, color, ADDS
background on TV personality. Pickup 13th graf, `Paper ballots...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD LEWAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil today made a final stride
toward full civilian rule as voters cast ballots in the country's
first popular presidential election in nearly three decades.
   The vote, on the 100th anniversary of the founding of the
Brazilian Republic, follows two decades of rapid economic
development in spite of massive foreign debt and widespread poverty.
   The favorite is a conservative former state governor, Fernando
Collor de Mello of the National Reconstruction Party, but he is not
expected to win enough votes to avoid a runoff with one of two top
two leftist candidates.
   Early reports indicated voting was peaceful across the country.
   In Rio de Janeiro, voters waited good-humoredly in huge lines
that snaked around city blocks, despite a threat of rain. Many
voted early to take advantage of the national holiday, which marks
the 100th anniversary of the founding of a republic that overthrew
Emperor Pedro II.
   Brazilians lined up to vote hours before the polls opened at 8
a.m. (5 a.m. EST). Polls were to close at 5 p.m., with partial
results expected at around 9 p.m. An official projection of the
winner was due Saturday.
   Collor de Mello's attacks on President Jose Sarney for 1,300
percent annual inflation and widespread corruption have struck a
chord with many of the 82 million registered voters, most of whom
earn less than $36 a week.
   In a national TV address Tuesday night, Sarney called the
election ``an extraordinary spectacle'' that demonstrated ``the
flourishing of Brazilian democracy.''
   ``The democratic transition is complete,'' said Sarney, who was
chosen in 1985 by an electoral college after the military ended 21
years of rule. ``God has won in Brazil.''
   Fighting for second place are two leftists _ ex-governor Leonel
Brizola, who pledges West European-style socialism, and Rep. Luis
Inacia Lula da Silva, a former factory worker and strike leader who
wants a ``workers' republic,'' with nationalized banks and
cancellation of Brazil's $110 billion foreign debt.
   If no candidate wins a majority _ and it's doubtful anyone will
_ the top two vote-getters will meet in a runoff Dec. 17.
   Collor de Mello had a comfortable lead, but far short of a
majority in the 21-candidate field, according to two opinion polls
announced Tuesday.
   Many voters wore red bandanas, the symbol of Brizola, who was
about even with da Silva in voter surveys. But in Brasilia, the
capital, election officials made Brizola sympathizers take off the
bandanas to vote.
   Other than Brizola or Lula, only two other candidates were given
any chance of squeaking into the No. 2 spot: center-leftist Sen.
Mario Covas, and rightist Rep. Paulo Maluf.
   The two-month campaign has been marred by some personal insults,
but enthusiastic crowds have gathered at street rallies across this
nation of 150 million people, South America's largest. Silvio
Santos, a television personality, tried to enter the race at the
last minute, but officials ruled he had violated election rules.
   Paper ballots with squares beside each candidate's name were
waiting at 250,000 polling stations, from the southern plains to
the remote jungle villages in the northwestern Amazon region.
   Special stations were set up for the blind and for the estimated
half-million people with leprosy. In some places, voting equipment
had to be carried in by canoe or on mules.
   Federal troops were stationed in 39 of Brazil's 4,445 counties _
mostly in the remote north and northwest _ to keep order and to
prevent last-minute campaigning.
   Brazilians under 47 _ nearly 73 percent of the electorate _ have
never voted for president.
   In the last election in 1960, Janio Quadros won, but he stunned
the nation by saying he was plagued by ``occult forces'' and
resigned after seven months in office. His vice president, Joao
Goulart, took over but was ousted in a military coup in 1964.
   The military regime banned direct voting for president but it
was restored by a new constitution enacted last year. Voting is
mandatory for everyone between age 18 and 69.
   And for the first time in the country's history, 16- and
17-year-olds may vote, though it's not mandatory. Some 3.3 million
_ more than half of those eligible _ have registered.
   The election comes a century after republicans in Brazil
overthrew Latin America's only independent monarchy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
