<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--LATrucks     11-15 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--LA Trucks,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Approves Rush-Hour Ban on Trucks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed ban on rush-hour truck traffic on
all Los Angeles streets won unanimous initial approval from the
City Council.
   The council Tuesday directed the city attorney to draft the
needed ordinances following an 11-0 vote. The ordinances require
final council approval.
   Mayor Tom Bradley proposed the ban, saying trucks are the
biggest contributor to rush-hour gridlock. The ban, fiercely
opposed by the trucking industry, would reduce rush-hour truck
traffic on city streets by 70 percent.
   Exempted would be grocery delivery trucks, trucks carrying cargo
from the harbor and trucks making deliveries of seasonal produce _
with Christmas trees and watermelons specifically mentioned.
   Trucks delivering liquor would not be affected because they are
regulated by the state.
</TEXT>
