<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   11-15 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0508,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Confines 350,000 to Homes; Clashes Leave 10 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 10 wounded, tear gas fired at doctors
and nurses, clash in southern Lebanon. ADDS background on uprising. No
pickup. ^By ELLEN SCHECHET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers ordered at least
350,000 Palestinians not to leave their homes in the occupied lands
today, the first anniversary of the PLO's declaration of a
Palestinian state.
   But festivities were held in several towns and refugee camps in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip in which youths shot off fireworks,
danced in the streets and carried balloons painted with the colors
of the Palestinian national flag.
   Violent protests occurred in at least five towns where soldiers
fired live ammunition and rubber bullets, injuring 10 people during
stone-throwing demonstrations, Arab reports said. Police said they
arrested seven stone-throwers in East Jerusalem.
   Police also fired tear gas to disperse a protest march by 200
doctors and nurses from two hospitals in East Jerusalem after rocks
were hurled at the troops from behind fences, a spokesman said. No
injuries were reported.
   Troops were under orders to respond firmly to any violence and
were warned that uprising activists had received orders to increase
the use of firearms following the fatal shooting Monday of a
soldier in the Gaza Strip.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told legislators Tuesday that
Arab activists had received secret orders from uprising leaders to
attack Israelis with firearms, rather than stones or firebombs,
newspapers reported.
   The day marks one year since the Palestine Liberation
Organization's parliament-in-exile proclaimed statehood in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which have been under Israeli military
occupation since the 1967 Middle East War.
   About 1.7 million Palestinians and 70,000 Israeli settlers live
in the occupied territories. The Israeli government has ignored the
PLO declaration and refused negotiations with the organization,
which it calls terrorist.
   Since the uprising against Israeli occupation began 23 months
ago, 615 Palestinians and 41 Israelis have been killed.
   Palestinians launched celebrations of the holiday Tuesday night,
setting off fireworks in some towns, where women also danced in
streets.
   In Tilat Al-Haritiya village near Ramallah, children gathered on
the streets Tuesday night singing nationalist songs and draping
displaying photographs of PLO chief Yasser Arafat across
electricity poles.
   The army today curtailed festivities by imposing curfews in more
than 20 towns, villages, refugee camps and cities throughout the
disputed lands.
   At least 350,000 Palestinians were affected.
   Soldiers also blocked transport in the Gaza Strip for a second
straight day. Two Palestinians were shot and wounded during
stone-throwing protests in Nozeirat refugee camp in Gaza, Arab
reports said.
   Also today, a U.N. peacekeeper in south Lebanon shot and killed
an Israeli-allied militiaman and wounded another who tried to force
their car through a roadblock and clashed with U.N. troops,
officials said.
   The incident occurred near the village of Ibil As-Saqy, five
miles north of the Israeli border, inside Israel's self-proclaimed
6-to10-mile security zone in south Lebanon, Timor Goksel, a
spokesman for the peacekeepers said.
</TEXT>
