<FIRST>u a PM-RiotTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0542 11-15 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0542,0870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnically Mixed Jury Seated in Case That Sparked Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead and 2nd graf; SUBS 6th graf pvs, `The defense ...'
with 2 grafs to UPDATE with defense's opening arguments. SUBS 13th graf
pvs, `Decisions by ...' to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a Hispanic policeman in the slaying of
a black motorcyclist opened today with the prosecution arguing that
the officer was in no danger and did not have to fire the shot that
set off three days of riots.
   Circuit Judge Joseph Farina cleared the way Tuesday for the
manslaughter trial of Miami officer William Lozano by refusing to
move the case out of Miami. He rejected defense arguments that the
threat of violence hung over the trial and could frighten jurors
into convicting Lozano to avoid another riot.
   Assistant State Attorney Don Horn told the racially mixed jury,
seated after three weeks of questioning, that the 31-year-old
officer failed to act as a prudent policeman should have in the
slaying of Clement Lloyd, 23.
   ``It was not a life-or-death situation. It was not a
split-second decision, and he did not have to shoot,'' said Horn.
   He said Lozano shot Lloyd in the head after taking two steps
into the street and putting himself closer to the path of Lloyd's
speeding motorcycle, which was being chased by a patrol car.
   Defense attorney Roy Black, in his opening arguments, said the
shooting ``had nothing to do with race.''
   ``Officer Lozano did not shoot his gun because he's a Hispanic.
Clement Lloyd was not shot because he is black,'' Black said. But
within moments, he said, ``race had everything to do with this
case'' as a crowd formed in a prelude to a night of rioting.
   The Jan. 16 shooting, which also led to the death of Lloyd's
passenger, exploded into three days of rioting. One looter was shot
to death, 11 people were wounded by gunfire and 13 buildings were
burned down.
   Some black leaders said the jury's ethnic mixture _ two blacks,
one Hispanic and three non-Hispanic whites _ could head off a
repeat of rioting that followed acquittals by all-white juries in
1980 and 1984 of two other officers who had killed blacks.
   ``The fact that the jury resembles the tri-ethnic balance of
this community goes a long way to reducing that level of tension,''
said William Sims of Dade County's Community Relations Board.
   A televised forum Tuesday night in the predominantly black
Overtown neighborhood where the shooting occurred illustrated the
community's continuing anger, as many participants complained that
they were mistreated by Hispanics who arrived in this country only
recently.
   The anger led the defense to enter into the record scores of
items showing that more violence was expected if Lozano was
acquitted.
   The exhibits included violence-threatening posters by the
``Overtown Comrades,'' and documents showing police contingency
plans to combat a riot if Lozano is found innocent.
   Decisions by the judge have sharply limited how much the defense
can reveal to jurors about the slain motorcyclist's police record
and allegations that he was picking up drug profits the night of
the killing.
   ``We have to start out with the the court already excluding 75
percent of our defense,'' Black said Tuesday. ``Needless to say,
we're operating under a great handicap.''
   The shooting took place during the week of the Super Bowl in
Miami. The Colombian-born Lozano and his partner were on an
Overtown street, talking to the victim of a minor crime.
   As they talked, another squad car was chasing down a speeding
motorcycle driven by Lloyd and carrying his friend Allan Blanchard,
24.
   When the motorcycle turned onto the street where Lozano was
standing, the officer fired one shot, killing Lloyd instantly and
sending the motorcycle crashing into a car.
   Blanchard died later. Lozano was charged with two counts of
manslaughter.
   If convicted on both counts, he would face a maximum penalty of
60 years imprisonment.
   Within an hour after the shooting, a mob gathered at the scene
and began pelting officers with rocks and bottles, starting the
rioting.
   Lloyd was found to have high levels of alcohol and THC _ the
active chemical in marijuana _ in his blood at the time of his
death.
   He also had 5.5 grams of marijuana and $1,500 in his pocket,
facts the defense contends showed he was a drug dealer desperate
enough to run down a policeman to avoid arrest.
   The city later set up a commission to examine the roots of the
racial disturbance, the fourth to hit Miami in the 1980s.
   The first occurred in 1980 after an all-white jury in Tampa
acquitted a group of Metro-Dade policemen in the fatal beating of
black insurance executive Arthur McDuffie. The case was moved to
Tampa because of pretrial publicity.
   In 1982, a riot broke out when Miami policeman Luis Alvarez
entered an Overtown video arcade and shot and killed Nevell
Johnson, a black. Two years later, violence broke out again when an
all-white jury acquitted Alvarez of manslaughter.
</TEXT>
