<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia     11-15 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Draft Laws on Civil Rights Under Review in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government panel has proposed
revising laws on assembly and association to comply with
international human rights accords without discarding traditional
Communist principles, an official said today.
   The state-run Human Rights Committee submitted the three draft
laws to Premier Ladislav Adamec, who on Tuesday announced that
Czechoslovaks wishing to travel to the West will no longer need
exit visas, beginning Jan. 1.
   Despite some easing of restrictions, however, the hard-line
government continued to crack down on dissent. A court in
Bratislava on Tuesday sentenced an activist who urged his
countrymen to honor those killed in the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion
that crushed reforms in Czechoslovakia.
   Zbynek Vokrouhlicky, a member of the Human Rights Committee that
worked out the draft laws, told The Associated Press they will go
to a legislative commission before being considered by Parliament,
probably in the spring.
   The Communist Party organ Rude Pravo on Tuesday said the
committee submitted the drafts to Adamec on Nov. 1O. Copies of the
drafts could not be obtained immediately, and there were few
details on their contents.
   Czechoslovakia is rewriting its laws to conform with human
rights commitments signed at a 35-nation conference in Vienna early
this year.
   Those accords commit the signatory nations to allow freer travel
and guarantee human rights. It was not immediately clear if the
laws under discussion will translate into more freedoms for the
country's population.
   Adamec said the easing of travel, which has been introduced
gradually over the past two years, was designed to reduce
bureaucracy and contribute to the ``satisfaction of its citizens.''
   Czechoslovaks have been allowed to travel more freely than their
counterparts in other hard-line Communist countries, and Western
analysts said the new rules will not have a marked effect on who
will be allowed to travel.
   People wishing to travel west still must apply for visas from
the country of destination and must prove they have sufficent hard
currency to cover travel expenses.
   Analysts, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there was no
indication that political activists, many of whom have had their
passports confiscated, would be allowed to travel under the new
regulations.
   In Bratislava, a court sentenced activist Miroslav Kusy to an
eight-month suspended sentence after a two-day trial and acquitted
three others who signed a statement urged Slovaks to mark the 21st
anniversary of the 1968 invasion.
   The court refused the defendants' request to be tried together
with a fifth activist, Jan Carnogursky, whose case goes to trial
separately next week. He could face up to 10 years in jail.
</TEXT>
