<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhonePorn     11-15 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Porn,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dial-A-Porn Services to Stop Two-Way Calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The telephone company in metropolitan New
York is free to pull the plug on live dial-a-porn services after
today, a federal judge ruled in a free-speech case.
   U.S. District Judge Neal McCurn on Tuesday refused to block New
York Telephone Co. from barring two-way conversations on its 970
exchange.
   The exchange, available only in four area codes around New York
City, allows callers to participate in sexually explicit
conversations as well as hear taped messages.
   Companies that operate such services set fees of $3 per minute
or more that New York Telephone is responsible for collecting. The
phone company was taken to court by dial-a-porn providers when it
refused to continue billing.
   The services won a temporary order from a state court in
September that allowed the services to continue, and then brought
the matter to federal court as a fight over freedom of speech.
   McCurn ruled that the services had not proved the case was a
First Amendment issue, but he also refused to throw out the case,
leaving open the possibility the vendors can seek court relief on
other grounds.
   Two-way dial-a-porn services provided by five companies will
cease at the end of the business day today, said their lawyer, Joel
Dichter. But he said he would file a motion as soon as possible to
allow the services to resume.
   New York Telephone attorney Kevin Walsh said the case was never
a fight over freedom of speech. He said the phone company has no
power to regulate the content of taped messages or live
conversations.
   ``No one is prohibiting them from speaking. If people want to
spend 50 minutes on the phone with Stella or 30 minutes with
Raquel, they have the right and the companies have the right to
provide that service,'' said Walsh.
   ``But we're not going to do the billing and collecting. With
this kind of thing, it's easy to see people getting carried away
and then not wanting to pay the bill when it comes due.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
