<DOCNO> AP891115-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia     11-15 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Judges and Court Workers End Strike in Colombia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 judges and 12,000 court
workers ended a two-week strike today after the government agreed
to give them bulletproof vests, bodyguards and reinforced cars to
protect them from drug traffickers.
   The strike, which shut down Colombia's judicial system, ended as
a result of a meeting Tuesday with the minister of justice, said
Consuleo Herrera, a board member of the National Association of
Court Workers.
   Justice Minister Roberto Salazar also promised that judges'
offices will be moved to government buildings offering better
security, Mrs. Herrera told The Associated Press. The government
also will study the possibility of salary increases for judges
dealing with drug trafficking cases, Mrs. Herrera said. Judges are
paid an average of about $400 a month.
   The government will start providing the bulletproof vests,
bodyguards and bullet-resistant cars next week, she said.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. Embassy said today the U.S. government had
donated 300 bulletproof vests, 12 bullet-resistant cars, 12 metal
detectors and $500,000 for buying other security equipment.
   Britain sent a Hercules cargo plane loaded with weapons,
munitions and security equipment for the judges, the Colombian
radio network Caracol said. A spokeswoman for the British Embassy
in Bogota, Mery de Castello, said she was unable to confirm or deny
the report.
   The strike was declared after a federal judge was shot and
killed in the drug trafficking center of Medellin. The judge was
the third killed in three months. Although no one claimed
responsbility for the killings, government security forces and the
judges' union blamed drug traffickers.
   The government declared war on the traffickers after they killed
a popular presidential candidate, Luis Carlos Galan, on Aug. 18.
The traffickers then began a wave of bombings and assassinations
and threatened reprisals for any traffickers extradited to the
United States. There have been 253 attacks attrributed to drug
traffickers, with 39 people killed.
</TEXT>
