<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Killed in Street Battles; Aoun Threatens Christian Moderates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quarrel between two brothers touched
off street battles between rival Shiite Moslem militiamen loyal to
Syria and Iran, killing one combatant and wounding three, police
said today.
   In a separate development, the Christian army commander, Gen.
Michel Aoun, threatened to cut the throats and tongues of moderate
Christian leaders who support an Arab-brokered peace plan to end
Lebanon's civil war.
   His threat appeared aimed at blocking moderates in the Christian
heartland he controls from joining a national reconciliation
Cabinet under premier-designate Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem.
   Police said the brothers' quarrel began after Sheik Hassan
Nasrallah, a senior leader of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, went to visit his ailing mother at the sprawling
Shiyah district at nightfall Tuesday.
   He was stopped by gunmen guarding the house under his younger
brother, who goes by the nom de guerre of Abul-Rou'b, or father of
horror, and commands Shiite fighters of the pro-Syrian Amal
militia, according to police.
   Nasrallah's bodyguards fired in the air to clear way for the
sheik. His brother shouted orders to his men from the mother's
bedside to shoot back and ``all hell broke loose,'' said a police
spokemsan.
   Fighting quickly engulfed the entire Shiyah district and then
spread to Bir el-Abed and Hay Madi neighborhoods as Sheik
Nasrallah's motorcade raced back under gunfire to
Hezbollah-controlled territory, said the spokesman.
   He said the command of a Syrian army contingent in charge of
security of Beirut's Moslem sector intervened with the leaders of
Amal and Hezbollah to curb the flare-up.
   It tapered off briefly but picked up again at midnight, when
militiamen of the two factions shot at each other with machine
guns, 106mm jeep-mounted recoiless guns and rocket-propelled
grenades until dawn, the spokesman said.
   He said Syrian troops patrolled Shiyah and other Shiite slums
this morning to prevent a new outbreak of violence.
   Hezbollah and secular Amal have long been fighting for dominance
of the 1.2 million Shiites, who make up the largest single sect
among Lebanon's 4 million population.
   Aoun's threat was reported in a statement released by his press
office in the shell-battered presidential palace in suburban
Baabda, five miles east of Beirut.
   ``Those who support the Arab solution deserve to have their
throats and tongues cut,'' the 54-year-old Maronite general said.
``We are not going to be lenient with them.''
   Aoun appeared to be responding to a statement by Maronite
Parliament member Butros Harb, who publicly ridiculed the ``war of
liberation'' Aoun declared in March to drive Syria's 40,000 troops
from Lebanon.
   Harb represents the independent Maronite bloc, which has 14
deputies in the Lebanese Parliament that approved the Arab League
peace plan forged at a special session in Taif, Saudi Arabia, which
shifts power to the Moslem majority. Aoun, who heads an interim
military Cabinet, rejected the accord, demanding a timetable for a
total Syrian withdrawal
</TEXT>
