<FIRST>r a PM-GrandJuryWalkout     11-15 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grand Jury Walkout,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hispanic Grand Jurors Quit to Protest Lack of Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO CITY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Hispanics quit a grand jury to
protest what they said was a ``railroad job'' by prosecutors to
help a former policeman avoid trial in the shooting death of a
Mexican-American rape suspect.
   District Attorney Frank Conard said Tuesday he expects the grand
jurors to return when their session resumes Friday. ``They took an
oath to do a duty,'' he said.
   The grand jury was the second in this town of 5,500 to refuse to
indict the former part-time policeman, Billy Ray Williamson, in the
1988 slaying of Sammy Gomez.
   A grand jury cleared Williamson a week after the shooting. After
pressure from Hispanic leaders and state and federal officials, a
grand jury reviewed the case again but did not have the nine votes
to indict.
   ``We are resigning because we cannot be party to this railroad
job performed by the state and district attorney's office,'' the
five grand jurors said in a statement Tuesday. ``We are willing to
risk the consequences, whatever they may be.''
   Chris Castillo, one of those who resigned, said the proceedings
were unfair, but he declined to elaborate. ``I'm just too upset
about it,'' she said. ``Maybe later, when I've gotten over it.''
   The district attorney said there is no provision in the law for
grand jurors to resign.
   ``It's kind of like being drafted _ you get selected and serve
that term of court,'' he said. The 12-member grand jury's term ends
in February.
   District Judge Weldon Kirk was researching the law to determine
if the grand jurors are in contempt of court, district clerk Bill
Erwin said.
   The League of United Latin American Citizens has said the case
is a watershed in Mexican-Americans' struggle for equal treatment
in the smaller cities of West Texas.
   They have said they want Williamson tried for civil-rights
violations in federal court because they perceive bias in the state
justice systems.
   Williamson told officials he was trying to arrest Gomez when
Gomez lunged at him with a knife. Williamson said he shot Gomez in
self-defense, and local investigators agreed.
   But an autopsy that LULAC hired an El Paso medical examiner to
perform concluded from the the wounds and bullet trajectories that
Gomez had his hands above his head.
   Gomez was shot in the side of the chest, in the back below the
shoulder blade and in the back of the head.
</TEXT>
