<FIRST>r p PM-MiamiElections 1stLd-Writethru a0483 11-15 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Re-elect Commission's Lone Black; Alonso Wins Second Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to ADD that `tri-ethnic' is commissioner's description;
SUBS 9th graf pvs, `In the ...' with 2 grafs to CLARIFY that commission
has appointed black member.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lone elected black member of Miami's city
commission attributed his re-election to ``tri-ethnic'' support,
although ballots were cast mainly along ethnic lines in this
racially tense city.
   Miller Dawkins was re-elected in Tuesday's runoff by carrying
nearly 99 percent of the black vote and 75 percent of the non-Latin
white vote.
   Dawkins' Cuban-born challenger, Joe Carollo, carried the largest
bloc of votes, Hispanics, with 78 percent.
   With all 86 precincts and absentees counted, Dawkins, a two-term
incumbent, had 18,245 votes, or 52.7 percent, to 16,402 votes, or
47.3 percent, for Carollo.
   ``I got the majority of the black votes, I got enough of the
Latin to win away from a Latin opponent, and I got the white
votes,'' Dawkins said. ``So that's why I have a tri-ethnic vote.''
   Carollo, a former commissioner, had Spanish-language ads
suggesting ``all the Cubans vote for Carollo.''
   On the other hand, Dawkins, 64, had said he didn't believe his
was ``the black seat,'' but added that the city's black residents _
about 30 percent of the voters _ deserved representation on the
commission.
   The turnout among Hispanic voters was 40.5 percent, black
turnout 35.6 percent, and non-Latin white turnout 22.6 percent.
   When Dawkins is sworn in, he will become the only black on the
city commission. Athalie Range, who is black, had been appointed
last summer to complete Rosario Kennedy's term but did not seek
election on Tuesday.
   In Tuesday's other race, Kennedy, 44, lost a bid to regain her
seat to Miriam Alonso, 48. Ms. Alonso received 17,561 votes, or
53.2 percent, compared with Ms. Kennedy's 15,461 votes, or 46.82
percent.
   ``Miriam Alonso is going to bring a voice that is going to be
the voice of the people, the voice of Miami,'' Ms. Alonso said
after her victory. ``I'm going to be working with everyone in the
city of Miami to prove that I can be the person that will unite
Miami.''
   Dawkins, a college administrator, led a six-candidate primary
Nov. 7 by 691 votes. He was supported by some Hispanic leaders who
said it was important symbolically to have at least one black
commissioner.
   Carollo, a 34-year-old former policeman who served two terms
before losing the 1987 election, ran a slashing campaign that
linked Dawkins with a drug trafficker and called him the worst
commissioner in Miami history.
   Mayor Xavier Suarez, last week easily re-elected to a new
four-year term, called Carollo disruptive and supported Dawkins.
   Ms. Kennedy, who resigned her seat to run unsuccessfully for
Congress, charged Ms. Alonso with ``a penchant for demagoguery.''
   Her commercials called Ms. Alonso ``an opportunist who does not
respect the law,'' a reference to a 1988 court decision that
knocked Ms. Alonso off the Metro-Dade Commission ballot because of
a residency violation.
   Ms. Alonso concentrated her campaign among Hispanic voters. She
picked up 65.3 percent of the Hispanic vote to Ms. Kennedy's 34.7
percent. Ms. Kennedy carried the other ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
