<FIRST>r a PM-DenverHousing     11-15 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Denver Housing,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Housing Authority Director Resigns Amid Furor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the Denver Housing Authority has
quit after 33 years with the agency, citing blame heaped on him
over a plan to move poor people into middle-class neighborhoods.
   ``Everybody has called for my head without cause,'' Bill
Ratzlaff said Tuesday. ``The focus has turned from housing to
witch-hunting, head-hunting, which has really taken away from what
the housing authority is all about.''
   Ratzlaff began working for the agency as a handyman in 1956 and
had been director since 1976. He supervised public housing for
27,000 people and earned $70,000 a year.
   Ratzlaff and his staff were faulted, most notably by Mayor
Federico Pena, for misjudging community concerns about a plan to
relocate several hundred residents of inner-city projects to homes
in middle-class neighborhoods.
   Pena said Ratzlaff's departure will restore public confidence in
the agency and added that he didn't agree with the five-member
housing commission's decision to keep Ratzlaff on as a consulant at
his annual salary.
   The approach of scattering public housing in middle-class
neighborhoods has been tried in various cities, with the goal of
avoiding the drug and crime problems that plague big, inner-city
projects.
   Opponents say it simply transplants problems and can isolate
those involved from social services and public transportation that
they rely on.
</TEXT>
