<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Healer     11-15 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Healer,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Patient Says Psychic Healer Didn't Stop Her Pain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lesya Yurshova smiled for the TV camera while
doctors operated on her hernia with no other anesthetic than the
mental energy of one of the country's popular psychic healers.
   Eight and a half months later, however, she has stopped smiling
and started talking: she was in ``monstrous pain, which tormented
me from the first minute of the operation until the end.''
   Her revelation in an interview with the weekly Literaturnaya
Gazeta was the most damaging of several reports this week clouding
the reputation of Anatoly M. Kashpirovsky, which quickly drew the
attention of many Soviets.
   Kashpirovsky is one of the two best-known healers who have
gripped Soviet society this year with their claims to be able to
cure illnesses with mental energy, even over TV. Many people have
turned to them out of despair over a medical system in which many
medicines are not available, and much of the equipment and
scientific knowledge is out of date.
   Miss Yurshova underwent the operation in the capital of the
Georgian republic, Tbilisi, while Kashpirovsky was hundreds of
miles away. His mental energy, transmitted to Miss Yurshova over
television, was to block the pain. The operation helped build
Kashpirovsky's reputation as a healer among Soviets.
   She said in the interview published in Wednesday's edition of
Literaturnaya Gazeta, that she endured the pain _ and even smiled
for the camera _ because she did not want to let him down.
   The faith healer promised she would feel nothing worse than a
mosquito bite, and that after recovering that she would travel
abroad to advertise his method, Miss Yershova said.
   In a TV session shown Tuesday night on the late evening program
``Good Evening, Moscow,'' Kashpirovsky claimed that Miss Yurshova
attacked him only because he did not send her abroad as promised.
Kashpirovsky, staring straight into the TV camera with his dark
eyes, also told his followers he could not be blamed for ``pure
coincidences.''
   Kashpirovsky and another healer, Alan Chumak, have appeared all
over the Soviet Union, including at news conferences at the Soviet
Foreign Ministry's information department. Their popularity has
spread widely through their exposure on television.
   Citing viewer surveys that indicate many people believe Chumak's
sessions have helped them, the Tass news agency said that beginning
Wednesday, Radio Moscow's world service would begin transmitting a
5-10 minute program with the healer in more than 10 languages.
   Miss Yurshova said she broke her silence because of her
worsening health and Kashpirovsky's indifference. Her eyesight and
hearing have worsened and she suffers headaches and chest pain, she
said.
   ``After the operation, which was another step toward Olympus for
Anatoly Mikhailovich, he became indifferent to my fate, and he told
me so,'' she told the respected newspaper.
   Leningrad TV reported earlier this week on claims that a
7-year-old boy lost consciousness and was paralyzed after watching
one of Kashpirovsky's televised sessions.
   Doctors familiar with the boy's case told the daily
Komsomolskaya Pravda the boy was suffering from an infection of the
brain, and that Kashpirovsky had nothing to do with it one way or
the other.
   In another case detailed by the Communist Party daily Pravda on
Wednesday, a Moscow cooperative is being investigated for allegedly
trying to organize a phony healing session in the southern city of
Krasnodar for an advance price of $97,000.
   Officials said they have determined Kashpirovsky was not
involved in the plan.
</TEXT>
