<FIRST>u w PM-NavyAccidents 2ndLd-Writethru a0521 11-15 1051</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Accidents, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0521,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy to Conduct Worldwide Safety Check</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First 8 grafs new with White House comment; picks up 4th graf
pvs, The order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said today an unprecedented
48-hour cutback in naval operations is ``important for the safety
of the Navy'' and would not compromise U.S. readiness at sea.
   ``It's exactly the right thing and it was done in the right
manner,'' said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   The unprecedented operations cutback and 48-hour safety check _
designed to stem the string of deadly accidents plaguing the
service _ was announced Tuesday by Adm. Carlisle A.H. Trost, the
chief of naval operations.
   He ordered that a ``safety stand-down'' be conducted at all Navy
facilities within three days.
   Fitzwater said the order ``does not involve the front-line
forces and those in places like the Med(iterranean) and the Indian
Ocean and so forth that are involved in militarily sensitive
situations.''
   The spokesman said President Bush did not have advance notice of
the safety review because ``it's an administrative action that the
Navy has taken ... and there was no need to notify the White
House.''
   However, Fitzwater added, ``We do support it. We think it's
important for the safety of the Navy.''
   Trost, in announcing the decision, told reporters that ``prudent
leadership demands that we take a look at everything that might be
a possible cause for this recent spate of accidents, regardless of
their severity.''
   The order requires ships, flying squadrons and shore facilities
to interrupt normal operations and review basic safety and
operating procedures.
   However, it allows such operations as ship movements in the
Persian Gulf and drug-interdiction activities to continue, the
four-star admiral said.
   ``A stand-down ... does not say, bring ships in from sea, stop
flying airplanes completely. ... Clearly, operations around the
world must continue,'' Trost said.
   In his statement, Trost told fleet commanders and other senior
Navy leaders that they should ``leave no stone unturned to ensure
the safety of operations is foremost in the minds of all hands.''
   The order also requires all commanders to report their findings
after the 48-hour interruption in operations.
   The action came as the Navy has suffered through a series of
mishaps since Oct. 29 in which 10 people have been killed or lost
at sea and at least 53 people injured.
   Between Jan. 1 and Nov. 1, the Navy counted 101 ``operation and
training related'' fatalities in the service, including 47 in the
explosion aboard the USS Iowa on April 19.
   The admiral defended the Navy's safety record, saying that
absent the Iowa fatalities, this would be the service's safest year
in this decade.
   Trost said he has found no common thread in the recent spate of
accidents, that some were due to mechanical failure while others
were caused by human error, such as a lapse of attention to
procedure.
   He said he did not believe commanders were working their sailors
too hard, but he wanted to ensure that no short cuts were being
taken during the many dangerous activities that Navy personnel must
conduct every day.
   The admiral said all commanders should ask: ``Are we adhering to
all the proper procedures, are we doing what we should be, the way
we should be doing it? ... Is there something we're overlooking?
Are people getting careless?''
   ``I would say there are three problems here,'' James Webb, who
was Navy secretary during part of the Reagan administration, said
today on ``CBS This Morning.'' ``One is the continuous operating
environment where you can get careless. The second is the technical
nature of the equipment, but I would say by and large the people
are very good right now.
   ``The third is the training environment, teaching people how to
anticipate problems and to make sure ... junior leaders are
supervising when the people under them are in a dangerous
environment,'' Webb said.
   Overall, the Navy has 599,000 full-time personnel and some 566
ships _ and usually a third of those are at sea for training
operations at any one time.
   The announcement came as three more incidents were added to the
Navy's accident list:
   _A Navy F-14 jet fighter crashed in the Gulf of Mexico 60 miles
northwest of Key West, Fla., with the crew escaping serious injury.
   _A fire broke out aboard the amphibious assault ship USS Inchon
in Norfolk, Va., injuring 31 people, as the vessel was undergoing
shipyard maintenance.
   _A Navy ordnance technician suffered minor burns and possible
eye injuries when an experimental explosive mixture detonated in a
research laboratory at the Naval Surface Weapons Testing Center in
White Oak, Md.
   In recent weeks, the service has been plagued by a number of
deadly accidents including a training jet crashing into an aircraft
carrier off Florida in which five people were killed; sailors who
have been washed overboard on two different aircraft carriers and
the accidental bombing of a ship by a Navy pilot in the Indian
Ocean.
   On Monday, the destroyer USS Kinkaid and a freighter collided in
the Malacca Strait, 240 miles northwest of Singapore, killing one
Navy crewman, injuring five, and starting fires on both vessels.
   Last Thursday, a Navy reserve pilot flying an A-7E jet crashed
into an apartment complex in Smyrna, Ga., killing two civilians and
injuring two others, including himself.
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the Senate
Armed Services Committee, called the action ``a prudent step.''
   ``If I were the secretary of the Navy today I would be taking
the exact same steps,'' said Warner, a former Navy secretary.
   Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo., a member of the House Armed Services
Committee, said that although the recent accidents didn't appear to
be related, it was a ``very wise move'' on the Navy's part to
review safety procedures.
   Rep. Charles Bennett, D-Fla., chairman of the House Armed
Services subcommittee on seapower and strategic and critical
materials, also said the Navy's decision was wise, but he added
criticism of the service's leadership.
   In particular, he complained the Navy has decided to make Capt.
Fred Moosally, skipper of the USS Iowa, eligible for another major
command.
   The Iowa explosion killed 47 sailors, including the gunner's
mate that the Navy later said ``most likely'' caused the blast
intentionally.
</TEXT>
