<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Britain     11-15 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Britain,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Drama Forces Britain to Rethink its Place in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drama in East Germany is forcing Britain to
ponder anew its place in Europe.
   Some analysts say now is the time to get into closer step with
the Continent, to join forces in order to absorb a unified German
colossus and thus render it harmless.
   Others argue the opposite: that as the old order unravels and
long-held certainties disintegrate, Britain should keep its
distance and wait for the dust of the crumbling Berlin Wall to
settle.
   The question of Britain's place in Europe is an old one, but it
had become urgent well before the momentous changes overtook
Poland, Hungary and the Germanys.
   The 12-nation European Economic Community, of which Britain is a
member, is to become a single tariff- and passport-free trading
bloc at the end of 1992, and has ambitious plans for monetary union
and Europe-wide standards on workers' rights and social welfare.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, the crusading free-marketeer,
believes these are corporatist tendencies, and that the EEC
bureaucracy in Brussels is trying to foist on her the very
socialist constraints she has fought for 10 years to eradicate in
Britain.
   Economic and monetary union, which France is pressing, would be
an intolerable encroachment on national sovereignty, says Mrs.
Thatcher.
   The EEC, she insists, is primarily a trading bloc, and that by
unshackling the markets, abolishing currency controls and opening
Britain to outside investment, she is being a good European.
   She repeated this position Monday, signaling that events in
Germany had not changed her mind at all. But the conflicting
reactions to her speech underlined the differing attitudes. While
The Times of London praised ``Mrs. Thatcher's realism,'' the
Guardian denounced her as ``the supreme nitpicker of Europe.''
   Britons who share Mrs. Thatcher's view ``tend to see the
internal market as the end of a process, while the others see it as
the beginning of something more dynamic,'' said Vernon Bogdanor, a
constitutional expert at Oxford University.
   Until recently, Mrs. Thatcher's approach seemed like smart
politics. The British never have shared the Continent's romantic,
philosophical notion of ``Europe.''
   They sometimes seem to relish being odd nation out, whether in
refusing to join the exchange rate mechanism that harmonizes the
European currencies, or in resisting attempts by Brussels to impose
new health warnings on cigarette packs.
   They cling to what sets them apart, whether it's driving on the
left or measuring distances in miles. Their biggest-circulation
newspaper repeatedly derides the French as ``Frogs,'' and union
featherbedding is known as ``Spanish practices.''
   In the election campaign for the European Parliament in June,
Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative Party built its propaganda around the
specter of interfering EEC bureaucrats, complete with feeble puns
about force-feeding the British on Brussels sprouts.
   But the Tories were routed by the opposition Labor Party, and
many analysts sensed a sea change in public opinion. Perhaps, it
was suggested, Europe-bashing was no longer a vote-catcher.
   The issue of the exchange rate mechanism triggered a crisis last
month that prompted the resignation of Nigel Lawson, chancellor of
the exchequer and architect of the boom of the mid-1980s. Now comes
a new and bigger challenge in the shape of Berlin.
   The pro-integrationists paint a scenario of a united Germany
with an economy as big and Britain's and France's combined. To
prevent Germany going neutral and drifting to the new markets of
Eastern Europe, Western Europe must tighten its bonds, thus tying
Germany inextricably to the EEC and dampening any temptation by
German to flex its nationalist muscle.
   The counterargument says harmonization of social law and
monetary union are difficult enough when economies as different as
Portugal's and West Germany's are involved. Add East Germany, and
later, perhaps, Hungary and Poland, and harmonization begins to
look like a joke.
   ``(For) those who worry about a Germany getting back to its old
style through reunification, the only answer is to bind Germany
more tightly and tightly to the Community,'' says former Prime
Minister Edward Heath, who took Britain into the EEC in 1973.
   ``If West Germany is going to be bound more tightly into the
Community, then we in Britain have got to be as well,'' he said
Wednesday. ``If we drag our feet, then they'll go ahead and just
leave us outside.''
</TEXT>
