<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Walesa-Embassy     11-15 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa-Embassy,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0574 to restore dropped material at end</HEAD>
<HEAD>Just Kidding, Walesa Reassures Startled Polish Embassy Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Walesa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The staff of the Polish Embassy, consisting
mainly of career Communist Party members, gave a collective gasp
when Solidarity leader Lech Walesa cheerfully said he hoped to see
them all in Poland soon.
   But Walesa, giving a pep talk to the embassy staff, assured them
he was just being friendly, that he thought they were doing a great
job improving relations with the United States, and that the
Solidarity-led government has no plans to call them home.
   ``I am not taking the place of the government. I am not
replacing anybody at the embassy,'' Walesa said.
   That was good news for Ambassador Jan Kinast, who served as
deputy foreign minister in the communist-led government that
preceded Solidarity to pwer and who has been working long hours
since then to rally U.S. economic support for the new reform
government.
   The embassy staff played virtually no role in arranging the
Walesa visit, which was sponsored by the AFL-CIO labor federation.
But its diplomats have had their hands full getting ready for
visits by many Polish government dignitaries and an unending stream
of U.S. congressional and administration figures headed for Poland,
Ryszard Krystosik, the No. 2 embassy official, said in an interview
this week.
   Many of Poland's foreign service professionals shared the
conciliatory sentiments expressed by Walesa.
   ``We should forget our differences,'' Walesa told them. ``We
have had many over the last 45 years. Many of those were caused by
others.''
   ``This is the time for ... all Poles to work together for
Poland,'' Walesa told the diplomats, assembled in the second floor
reception room of the stately turn-of-the century mansion atop
Meridian Hill in Washington. He spoke to them Tuesday during a
hectic week, and his remarks were recounted by three Poles who were
present.
   Walesa, who is chairman of the Solidarity trade union but holds
no government post, arrived in Washington on Monday on a trip that
includes numerous honors as well as non-stop exhortations for
Americans to send aid and investment to bolster the Polish reforms.
   His remark about seeing the Polish diplomats soon in Poland,
delivered at the end of a short pep talk, was taken in the same
good humor it was made, said one Pole who was present.
   ``It didn't have any overtones at all,'' said a Polish diplomat
who spoke on condition he not be further identified. ``He was very
courteous and was very well received.''
   Although courtesy cannot entirely ease the tension caused in the
diplomatic corps by the fall of the communist government after 45
years in power, Krystosik said the embassy staff is dedicated to
seeking U.S. aid to bolster the Poland's reform government.
   ``We know very well how important is the role of the United
States as the leader of the Western world. We know very well the
initiative of the United States organizing and sponsoring
assistance to Poland, a program that paves the way for the
implementation of Polish reforms,'' he said.
   ``The embassy presents the policy line of the government of
Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki,'' the Solidarity adviser that
heads the government, said Krystosik.
   Besides, said other Polish diplomats, the presence of a
Solidarity rather than a communist government in Warsaw has eased
one of their main tasks, promoting U.S.-Polish friendship.
   Polish diplomats, showing a reporter around the embassy this
week, eagerly pointed out icons of Polish-American friendship,
including a letter to Thomas Jefferson from Thaddeus Kosciusko, a
Pole who served as a colonel in the American Revolution then
returned to Poland and led two uprisings against Russian domination.
   In one corner of the main reception area stands a Steinway grand
piano owned by Ignace Paderewski, who was Polish premier in 1919
and who performed many times in the United States as a reknowned
concert pianist.
   One Polish diplomat played a few bars on the piano, looked up
thoughtfully and said, ``we really ought to get this thing tuned.''
</TEXT>
