<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writhru a0445 11-15 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writhru, a0445,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Drops Demand for Immediate Demobilization of Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 7 grafs new with comments by Nicaraguan officials, deletes
9th graf pvs, which now obsolete. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Meanwhile, President.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan government, in a bid to break
an impasse in negotiations with the Contras, has dropped its demand
for the immediate demobilization of the rebels, a Sandinista
official said today.
   Vice Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco said the government
instead is insisting, as its price for a restoration of a
cease-fire, the evacuation of the rebels from Nicaraguan territory
to Contra base camps in Honduras.
   ``We think that is a very important change in our position,''
Tinoco told a news conference at the Nicaraguan Embassy.
   When the two sides recessed Tuesday evening after their fourth
round of talks, Nicaraguan Cardinal Miguel Ovando y Bravo was
downcast as he spoke to reporters.
   ``I was more optimistic last Thursday (when the talks started)
than I am now,'' he said.
   The talks were to resume later today. The Sandinistas and the
Contras both agree a cease-fire should be a first step, but beyond
that there is a large gap between their respective positions.
   Meanwhile, President Bush said Tuesday that he is sending a
20-member congressional team to monitor the elections in Nicaragua,
and he vowed to make East Bloc arms shipments to Managua an issue
at the Malta superpower summit in 18 days.
   Bush said the Soviets can help facilitate free elections by
cutting off arms deliveries to Nicaragua, ``the one country that
seems to be swimming against the (democratic) tide.''
   Chief Contra negotiator Col. Enrique Bermudez said the
Sandinistas ``are conditioning everything on the withdrawal of our
forces from Nicaraguan territory and their demobilization.''
   The estimated 5,000 Contras based in Nicaragua, Bermudez said,
should be allowed to remain in place when the cease-fire goes into
effect.
   The two sides had been informally observing a cease-fire reached
in March 1988 but President Daniel Ortega, contending there had
been widespread violations by Contra forces, allowed the truce to
lapse Nov. 1.
   He has said that elections set for Feb. 25 will go ahead as
scheduled even if there is no settlement with the Contras. The
rebels are wary about demobilizing without ironclad guarantees that
they will be able to return in safety to a democratic Nicaragua.
   Bermudez complained that the Sandinista delegation refused to
consider a truce even for the duration of the peace talks.
   Helping to prod the delegations toward a settlement were
representatives from the United Nations and the Organization of
American States. They are members of the International Commission
for Support and Verification, which was set up to oversee the peace
process. Ovando y Bravo is attending the talks as a ``witness.''
   Bush alleged anew that the Sandinistas for their part are arming
the Marxist rebels in El Salvador.
   Salvadoran rebels are engaging in ``senseless bloodshed'' and
are ``aided and abetted by Nicaragua and the Cuban government'' in
Central America, Bush said Tuesday at a luncheon meeting for OAS
foreign ministers gathered here.
   The Salvadoran rebels launched the biggest offensive of their
10-year war over the weekend, virtually paralyzing much of San
Salvador and leaving hundreds dead.
   The State Department announced the administration was enlisting
retired diplomat Harry Shlaudeman to give advice and monitor the
Nicaraguan talks.
   Shlaudeman, 63, has agreed to work as a consultant to the
department but State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said
he will not participate directly in the discussions nor have
substantive contact with Sandinista officials.
   Nonetheless, a senior official said Shlaudeman did have a
half-hour meeting in recent days with Sandinista diplomats at their
request. ``He was in a listening capacity,'' said the official,
asking not to be identified.
</TEXT>
