<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   11-15 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0826</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the country:
   Nov. 10
   The Herald, Everett, Wash., on East Germany:
   The Iron Curtain is up. The Berlin Wall is down. Communism is on
the rocks, or so it seems, based on the most recent news from East
Germany.
   A propaganda minister for that nation announced ... the opening
of East German borders to unrestricted travel, a liberty denied
citizens since the infamous wall was erected in 1961. This dramatic
policy turnaround, although a long-awaited step toward freedom,
seems likely to accelerate the recent exodus from East to West.
   That could pose enormous social and economic difficulties for
both Germanys. So far in 1989 more than 200,000 discontent East
Germans have fled their country seeking better lives in West
Germany. As the East is losing its workers and young people, the
West is running out of jobs and housing.
   Not a moment too soon _ perhaps 28 years too late _ the East
German government has heard its citizens' demands. ...
   Egon Krenz, East Germany's new head of state, advocated a law
... that would ensure ``free, democratic general elections with a
secret ballot'' and with ``public supervision in every stage of the
balloting.'' ...
   Krenz also has been pleading publicly for his countrymen to
remain in their homeland and help build a new nation. Western
leaders should join in encouraging East German citizens to stay and
shape their free, democratic destiny.
   But why should East Germans heed this call and take a chance on
a bloody crackdown?
   That's nearly impossible to answer. Yet an active role by the
West might help push forward reforms and guard against a Tiananmen
Square-type massacre.
   West Germany Chancellor Helmut Kohl already has pledged to meet
with ... Krenz and has offered far-reaching aid if real political
and economic changes take root. President ... Bush and leaders of
the other Western European nations would do well to follow ...
Kohl's lead.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 11
   Baraboo (Wis.) News-Republic on East Germany:
   There could be no greater symbol of the changes in Europe than
(the) announcement that the Berlin Wall no longer would stand in
the way of free travel for East Germans.
   The news must come as a special joy to the millions of veterans
in the United States who fought in two world wars to retain
freedoms in Europe. ...
   The Wall has stood for 28 years as a stark reminder that sharp
divisions existed between East and West.
   While the Wall was effective in holding East Germans hostage to
a totalitarian regime, it could not bend the minds of citizens who
knew its true meaning _ not a wall to protect them from the West,
but rather, a wall to prevent them from getting to the West.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 13
   Delta Democrat-Times, Greenville, Miss., on Panama:
   If Hollywood made a movie of the Bush administration's handling
of recent events in Panama, it would be called ``The Gang that
Couldn't Coup Straight.''
   As more facts are revealed, the bungling becomes even more
embarrassing. A Newsweek cover story called it ``Amateur Hour,''
but that's an inaccurate tag. The men involved have years of
experience in government.
   This is one of the most credentialed administrations ever to
hold office. They should simply admit, ``We goofed. It's our
fault.'' ...
   Bush set the trap himself. He made the mistake of setting up
Gen. Manuel Noriega as a target, calling repeatedly for his ouster,
and working with the coup's unsuccessful plotters. ...
   Bush's best policy would be for him to simply say that the
United States has no compelling interest in overthrowing ...
Noriega. Such an assertion by ... Bush would be true leadership.
   However ruthless a thug ... Noriega is, he does no great harm to
U.S. interests. Even his arrest as part of the phony drug ``war''
would hardly dent the influx of drugs into our country.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 13
   Argus Leader, Sioux Falls, S.D., on former presidents:
   Much has been reported and debated lately about the proper role
that ex-presidents should play. ...
   Current members of the exclusive fraternity are Richard Nixon,
Gerald Ford, Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan.
   The consensus of scholars and self-proclaimed political experts
seems to be that of the four men, Carter is the model of public
behavior. ... Carter decided even before leaving the presidency
that he would not join any boards of directors or otherwise
``commercialize the presidency.'' ...
   Based on the citizenship Carter has demonstrated since leaving
office, he would be a welcome addition to public service.
   The same can't be said of the nation's other three living
ex-presidents. At least, it can't be said with as much enthusiasm.
</TEXT>
