<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     11-15 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>TV Broadcasts Radical's Appeal For Peace Hours After He Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government TV on Wednesday broadcast
an appeal for peace by a radical Sinhalese leader that was
videotaped while he was in custody and hours before he was shot to
death by government troops.
   Officials also reported finding the bodies of 31 suspected
Sinhalese radicals Wednesday and blamed the killings on vigilantes
in favor of the Sinhalese-dominated government in a country wracked
by ethnic and factional strife.
   ``I appeal to all my followers to give up their armed struggle
against the government and take to the democratic process to
achieve our goals,'' said Rohana Wijeweera, the founder of the
People's Liberation Front, in the broadcast.
   Wijeweera, who was captured Sunday, voluntarily made the appeal
for peace and ``sang like a bird'' about the whereabouts of his top
lieutenants, said a senior military source. He and the front's No.
2 and No. 3 men were shot and killed within the next 18 hours,
according to government announcements.
   The avowed Marxist, who used to have a beard and mustache, was
clean-shaven and the television clip showed him wearing a red beret
and a white shirt. He looked nervous but appeared to be in good
health while making the Sinhalese-language broadcast.
   The government said Wijeweera led security personnel to the
group's Colombo headquarters Monday to question D.B. Herath, the
third-ranking leader of the front.
   ``Herath pulled a pistol and began firing at Wijeweera and
troops opened fire, killing both of them,'' said Foreign Minister
Ranjan Wijeratne.
   The front's No. 2 man, Upatissa Gamanayake, was killed while
trying to escape capture Monday, the government said.
   Political leaders sypathetic to the front predicted more
violence could follow the death of Wijeweera, whose personal safety
had been guaranteed by President Ranasinghe Premadasa.
   Samuel Dias Bandaranaike, leader of the Sri Lanka Progressive
Front, said the public would not believe the government's version
of Wijeweera's death.
   The 31 bodies of suspected members of the group were discovered
Wednesday in the central hills and were likely killed by
pro-government vigilante groups, said the officials, who cannot be
identified under briefing rules.
   More than 6,000 people have been killed since August 1987 when
the People's Liberation Front started assassinating government
officials and supporters. The front professed outrage that the
Sinhalese-dominated government was making concessions to the Tamil
minority, and its battle escalated into a challenge of the
government's right to exist.
   Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
are mostly Hindus and claim the predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese
majority discriminate against them in jobs and education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     11-15 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts See Warning in Inventory Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growth of business inventories outpaced
business sales in September, the government said Wednesday in a
report that analysts said contained a warning of growing backlogs
due to the slowing economy.
   The Commerce Department reported that inventories held on
shelves and backlots climbed 0.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted
$791.8 billion after advancing 0.4 percent in August.
   Business sales, on the other hand, fell 0.3 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $524.6 billion following a 3 percent gain the
previous month.
   The business activity produced a slight increase in the
inventory-to-sales ratio to 1.51, meaning it would take 1.51 months
to exhaust inventories at the September pace. It was 1.50 in August.
   ``At the moment, the ratios do not appear excessive,'' said
Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co. ``But they show the
first signs of increases related to a declining business climate.''
   Robert G. Dederick, chief economist at the Northern Trust Co. in
Chicago agreed that on the surface the report suggests inventories
are not yet a problem.
   ``But there are some warning signals in it of some excess at the
consumer level,'' he said.
   Inventories often rise during periods of slow economic growth as
output exceeds demand, a process that could lead to production cuts
and loss of jobs. The economy has been experiencing sluggishness as
the Federal Reserve tries to contain inflation by keeping a tight
rein on credit.
   Retail inventories, up 1 percent in September, were of
particular concern since an earlier report indicated they could be
worse in October. The Commerce Department said Tuesday that retail
sales fell a full 1 percent in October, including a 5.1 percent
decline in car sales.
   Manufacturers' inventories, which represent about 45 percent of
the total, slipped 0.1 percent and wholesale backlogs, accounting
for 25 percent of the total, dropped 0.3 percent.
   Manufacturers' sales, on the other hand, fell 1.6 percent in
September. Retail and wholesale sales both were up 0.7 percent.
   Overall inventories were 6.4 percent above those of a year ago.
Sales increased 6.7 percent over September 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
