<DOCNO> AP891115-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Bonn     11-15 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Bonn,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Says It's Not Trying To `Export Capitalism'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday denied it was
trying to ``export capitalism'' to East Germany but reiterated that
its Communist neighbor must undertake major economic reforms.
   ``We do not export capitalism. We export a lot of things, but
not capitalism,'' chief government spokesman Hans Klein told The
Associated Press.
   Klein also indicated Chancellor Helmut Kohl may postpone a
crucial summit with East Germany until after an emergency Dec.
15-17 Communist Party congress that could choose a new party
leadership.
   Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann has proposed a massive
economic aid program for East Germany, contingent upon concrete
reforms in its state-controlled economy.
   East Germany has promised sweeping economic reforms, without
elaborating on specific plans.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has warned Westerners not to
gloat over the shaky condition of communism in the East bloc and
cautioned that ``exporting capitalism'' could hurt the growing
climate of cooperation in Europe.
   On Saturday, Kohl said economic assistance to East Germany
cannot be successful unless the ``system of a state-planned
economy'' gives way to a ``socially responsible market economy.''
   Klein rejected any suggestion that West Germany wanted to impose
its own type of economic system on its Communist neighbor. He said
major economic reforms are needed if East Germany expects to
attract investors.
   ``We say there must be market conditions which make it
reasonable to invest there,'' Klein said.
   But he shied away from stating flatly that a drastic economic
overhaul in East Germany was a pre-condition for financial aid.
   Volker Ruehe, general secretary of the Christian Democrats, said
there were some ways to help East Germany soon, including renewal
of its telephone communications network and environmental projects.
   But ``far-reaching changes in the current economic system'' are
needed for East Germany to be able to attract desperately needed
private investment, Ruehe said.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher, a leader of the Free
Democratic Party, said Bonn should not set conditions for its aid.
He did say reform must show ``definite signals,'' without
explaining what the signals should be.
   ``We must tell them we are ready to be helpful,'' said Juergen
Chrobog, Genscher's chief spokesman.
   At a news conference earlier in the day, Klein indicated Kohl
may postpone his summit with East German leaders until the end of
December.
   Kohl initially said he would meet with East German Communist
Party chief Egon Krenz either this month or in early December to
discuss East Germany's direction and possible financial assistance.
   But Kohl's latest position is that the meeting will occur
``sometime this year,'' Klein said.
   That left open the possibility the summit would be put off until
after the Communist Party emergency congress.
   Rudolf Seiters, Kohl's chief of staff, plans to fly to East
Berlin on Monday to prepare Kohl's visit. Kohl on Wednesday met
with the heads of eight ministries to discuss the situation in East
Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
