<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     11-15 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nujoma Promises to Protect Individual Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former guerrilla leader who is
likely to become Namibia's first president promised Wednesday to
protect individual rights but said he might establish a one-party
political system.
   Sam Nujoma, leader of the leftist South-West Africa People's
Organization, also said he would try to avoid dealings with the
white-run government in South Africa, which is ceding control of
Namibia after a 74-year rule.
   And he said English will become the sole official language of
Namibia's government and schools, with Afrikaans _ the language of
South Africa's dominant white group _ losing its official status.
   SWAPO, which began a guerrilla war for independence against
South Africa in 1966, was declared the winner Tuesday of United
Nations-supervised elections for an assembly that will draft a
constitution and declare independence.
   SWAPO will have 41 of the 72 seats in the assembly, which will
convene next week. At least 48 of the 72 members, or two-thirds,
must approve decisions by the assembly, and SWAPO will have to
bargain with at least some of the five other parties that won seats.
   The Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, a multiracial coalition that
favors a capitalist economy, has 21 seats. No other parties won
more than four seats.
   Nujoma said at a news conference that Namibians would not be
pressured to join SWAPO, but added: ``If the Namibian people chose
to go one-party and it is done at the polls democratically, it will
certainly be so.''
   Asked about civil liberties under a SWAPO-led government, he
replied: ``Certainly there will be freedom of the press, freedom of
assembly, freedom of movement, freedom of association, and there
will be also be freedom of religion.''
   ``We have no intentions of imposing our views on others and
anticipate no serious disagreements,'' Nujoma said. ``We stand
ready to be guided by the democratic principles of open discussion
and decision by the majority.''
   The last 1,500 South African troops will be withdrawn Nov. 23,
said Louis Pienaar, the territory's South Africa-installed
administrator. Most soldiers left by June, and remaining units have
been confined to two northern bases.
   Nujoma said his future government would demand that South Africa
surrender control of Walvis Bay, a South African enclave which
serves as Namibia's only deep-water port. South Africa says its
ownership of Walvis Bay is upheld by international law, but Foreign
Minister Pik Botha on Wednesday offered to negotiate terms of usage
of the harbor.
   ``I have always said there are two South Africans: one led by
white-minority settlers there _ that one we certainly will not deal
with,'' Nujoma said. ``But we respect non-racial South Africa _
that's why we will deal with it.''
   SWAPO wants to declare independence as soon as possible, but
Nujoma declined to set a date. Most observers believe Namibia will
become independent early next year as long as there are no serious
hitches in writing the constitution.
   During his 30 years in exile, Nujoma, 60, and his movement were
considered orthodox Marxists. Since SWAPO leaders began returning
to Namibia earlier this year, however, they have taken a more
moderate approach.
   Nujoma said SWAPO favors some government controls on the
economy, welcomes foreign investors and wants good relations with
East and West. He has repeatedly urged Namibia's 75,000 whites, and
civil servants in particular, to remain in the territory and help
develop the emerging nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
