<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-Pay 3rdLd-Writethru a0610 11-15 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Pay, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0610,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush and House Leaders Agree on Pay Raises and Ethics Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS figure in 3rd graf, The pay, to about $120,700 sted
nearly $125,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and House leaders agreed today
on a package of congressional pay raises and ethics reforms,
clearing the way for swift action before Congress adjourns next
week.
   ``I am very confident the president will make a statement later
today,'' House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., told reporters.
   The pay plan would bring House salaries from $89,500 to about
$120,700 in just over 13 months, and impose new ethics rules on the
amount and type of outside income members could earn.
   The House plan would apply to top officials government-wide,
except for the Senate, which was consiering a separate ethics and
pay package.
   The House would get a 7.9 percent raise by Jan. 1, as a
``cost-of-living adjustment'' for the two years since salaries were
last increased. A 25 percent raise would take effect a year later,
to coincide with the loss in income House members would suffer when
a prohibition takes effect on accepting fees for speeches before
interest groups.
   The bill also would tighten rules for other outside income and
gifts, require more disclosure of personal wealth and make other
ethics reforms.
   On Tuesday, White House counsel C. Boyden Gray told lawmakers
their plan failed to impose enough ethics restrictions on
legislative branch officials and their staffs, similar to those
governing the executive branch, according to sources who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
   House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., met with White
House Chief of Staff John Sununu today and settled the dispute, the
sources said.
   The pay increase itself was supported by the White House because
it also applied to federal judges and top officials in the
executive branch.
   House Democratic and Republican leaders had hoped to settle
their discussions with the White House by day's end Tuesday. They
were forced to postpone until Thursday party caucuses planned for
today as the first step in the final push.
   ``We want to make sure we can tell the caucus that we have an
understanding,'' said Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., chairman of the
House Democratic Caucus.
   To demonstrate for rank-and-file members the bipartisan support
for the pay raise, Foley and Majority Leader Richard Gephardt,
D-Mo., plan to appear before the House Republican Conference, and
their GOP counterparts, Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., and
Minority Whip Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., were going before the
Democratic Caucus.
   Foley expressed confidence the House would approve the
pay-and-ethics plan. Senate sentiment remained uncertain, but Foley
said he had received ``very strong assurances'' from the leaders of
that chamber that it would not block the plan.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, said he
envisioned a different pay and ethics plan, one in which senators
would take only part of the pay raise and phase out speech
honoraria more slowly.
   But many House members expressed strong reservations about the
Senate, saying they feared the other chamber would stick the House
with the worst of all worlds _ a politically difficult vote
recorded in favor of a pay raise, and no pay raise.
   The new pay raise proposal is more modest than the 51 percent
raise with no ethics package that Congress rejected last winter in
response to a storm of public criticism.
   Instead of looking for ways to capitalize on the issue,
Republicans and Democrats lingered on the House floor discussing
arrangements for mutual political protection so they both could
vote for the pay raise.
   ``It's better than Monte Carlo out there,'' said one Democrat,
who insisted his name not be used.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
