<FIRST>r i AM-Irish     11-15 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Part-Time Soldier Injured in Letter Bomb Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A part-time soldier was injured
Wednesday when a letter bomb sent to his home near Belfast exploded
as he opened it, police said.
   The man, a member of the Territorial Army reserve force, escaped
serious injury but was being treated in hospital for his wounds and
for severe shock, the Royal Ulster Constabulary said.
   The bomb was sent to the soldier's home in the Rathcoole area of
Newtownabbey on the northern outskirts of Belfast, police said. He
was not identified.
   Lt. Gen. Sir David Ramsbotham, 55, commander of the British
Field Army and inspector general of the Territorial Army, was
identified Tuesday as the target of a botched car bombing in London.
   No group claimed responsibility for either attack but suspicion
fell on the Irish Republican Army which is fighting to end British
rule in Northern Ireland and unite the mainly Protestant province
with the overwhelmingly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
   Home Secretary David Waddington earlier Wednesday urged the
public to be alert for bombing campaigns following Monday's
discovery of a car bomb outside Ramsbotham's house in London's
fashionable Kensington district.
   Scotland Yard said the bomb, containing a plastic explosive, was
placed under the wrong car and fell off because it probably was not
attached properly. It was seen on the ground by a painter working
nearby who called police.
   The car bomb bore the hallmarks of the IRA, police said.
   ``I do not think the IRA are respecters of our religions,''
Waddington said in a BBC radio interview. ``I think there is just
as much likelihood of there being a dastardly campaign at Christmas
as any other time of the year.''
   Also Wednesday, the Belfast to Dublin railway line reopened
after troops searched the track near Lurgan, County Armagh,
following a bomb warning. The security forces said nothing was
found.
   Train service between the two cities has been disrupted more
than 60 times this year because of bombs and bomb hoaxes, blamed on
the IRA.
</TEXT>
