<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--EagleLove     11-15 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Eagle Love,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>One-Eyed Eagle Chosen as Mate for Widower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matchmakers think the timing is right to
introduce a widower to a partially blind potential mate.
   Syracuse's Burnet Park Zoo plans to introduce its recently
widowed bald eagle to a bird from Florida, according to Ken
Reininger, curator of birds at the zoo. The Florida bird was
captured by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service after it lost an eye
to a shotgun pellet.
   ``We do expect to have her before the weather gets cold,'' he
said. ``It's a perfect time of year to try this type of thing.''
   The zoo's previous female bald eagle died of a heart attack in
May during a crucial egg-tending period. The male eagle tended the
eggs and took over the parental responsibilities. The only
surviving chick was removed later that month and given to wild
foster parents.
   Reininger said the male eagle hasn't been lonely since the death
of his mate and the departure of his chick.
   ``(Loneliness) doesn't make much sense evolution-wise,'' he
said. ``He just continued on with his life. He's just not that
shortsighted.''
</TEXT>
