<FIRST>u i AM-Walesa-Poland     11-15 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa-Poland,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poles Pleased by Walesa's Speech to Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Walesa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poles expressed pride and satisfaction at
Lech Walesa's speech Wednesday to a joint session of Congress,
which was carried live nationwide on Polish TV and radio.
   ``I was really very nervous about him, but he was very good. I
am very happy,'' said Walesa's wife, Danuta, speaking from their
home in Gdansk where she watched the speech with some of their
eight children.
   ``I never dreamed Lech would address the Congress, but I never
dreamed about lots of other things that have already happened and
things are now happening so fast. I hope everything will be better
now and it will be even faster,'' she said by telephone.
   Mrs. Walesa said that she had spoken with her husband earlier in
the day. ``He said he would have a difficult day today. But I am
satisfied with him,'' she said.
   Mrs. Walesa had visited the United States in July to represent
her husband at a ceremony in Philadelphia where he was awarded the
first Philadelphia Liberty Medal.
   It has been a year of triumph for the electrican who helped
found the independent Solidarity trade union in Gdansk nearly nine
years ago and guided it through the difficult years after it was
crushed during the 1981 martial-law crackdown and later banned.
   Solidarity was legalized for the second time in April, and
candidates backed by the movement scored a landslide victory in
partially democratic legislative elections in June.
   Walesa then engineered the parliamentary coalition that led to
the election of his close adviser, Tadeusz Mazowiecki, as the head
of the first non-Communist government in the East bloc.
   The Citizens Parliamentary Club, as the Solidarity group of
deputies and senators is called, watched the speech in the main
chamber of the Polish legislature.
   Elsewhere, hundreds of people gathered around TV sets in
Warsaw's main train station to watch the speech.
   ``I think he expressed what many Poles could have expressed. It
was the right thing to do and it was a pleasure to listen to him,''
said a police officer who declined to give his name.
   ``It was very good. You cannot add to anything he said because
he said everything there was to be said,'' said a construction
worker. He said the reaction of the Congress was very positive and
hoped the Americans would help Poland as much as possible.
   Another viewer also was impressed.
   ``It was good. We have to do something with the Reds
(Communists),'' said a young man from Czechoslovakia who stayed in
Poland after attending an independent cultural symposium last week
in the southwestern city of Wroclaw.
   The evening TV news later carried excerpts of the speech.
</TEXT>
