<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1459EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     11-15 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank Langella Stars in `Tempest'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York theatergoers have seen so many
established actors jump into Shakespeare and fall flat that failure
has become the expectation.
   Therefore it is with unusual appreciation that one finds Frank
Langella in ``The Tempest'' playing Prospero with poetry,
rich-voiced grandeur and the wisdom accumulated and tempered by a
sensitive elder statesman.
   ``The Tempest'' opened Tuesday night at the off-Broadway
Roundabout Theater.
   Langella doesn't carry the play by himself. B.D. Wong, in his
next assignment after Broadway's ``M. Butterfly,'' is the spirit
Ariel. Wong, wearing only black Bermuda shorts on his thin frame,
looks the epitomy of an other-world sprite.
   Wong's Ariel adores Prospero and trusts that Prospero will keep
his promise to set him free.
   Langella's Prospero who, in the last scene, forgives his
enemies, is neither an overbearing father nor a bookish recluse. At
the beginning, he talks about his books but acts like a man who has
already digested their contents and now is a person of informed
action.
   He loves his daughter, Miranda, and hates to give her up. He
makes it clear, though, that he is putting obstacles in her
relationship with her swain so their path to happiness won't be so
easy that they fail to appreciate it.
   Angela Sherrill has such an unclouded brow and innocent aspect
that she looks younger, not older, than Miranda's 15. Miranda and
Ferdinand, son of the King of Naples, fall in love at first sight.
John Wittenbauer as Ferdinand seems weak at first, then his voice,
as sweet as a young tenor's, grows on one. Prospero has caused the
tempest that shipwrecked on his island the King of Naples (a hearty
Jack Ryland), Prospero's brother who stole the Dukedom of Milan
from him (Rocco Sisto), the King's brother who plans the same
maneuver (Gabriel Barre), Gonzalo, who saved Prospero's life (an
avuncular Robert Stattel) and another lord (Erik Knutsen).
   Also washed ashore are the jester (Michael Countryman) and
butler (Michaeljohn McGann) who play the low comedy scenes with
Caliban. Jay Patterson is good as Caliban, who has a real grievance
against Prospero but whose personality is so loathsome that he
forfeits sympathy.
   Jude Kelly, artistic director of the West Yorkshire Playhouse in
England, made her New York directing debut.
   Franco Colavecchia designed the set of Prospero's abode, with
additional playing space on the roof. Lindsay W. Davis designed
costumes, with loose underwear and a burlap cape for Prospero, a
white nightgown for Miranda and contrasting elaborate garb and wigs
for the court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
