<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RingoSuit     11-15 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ringo Suit,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Ex-Beatle's Album Release as Trial Begins</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ringo Starr won a permanent court order Wednesday
blocking the release of a 1987 album he says was made in an alcohol
haze, then testified that he never agreed to pay the producer's
studio costs.
   The former Beatle, who sued producer Chips Moman and College
Park, Ga.-based CRS Records to prevent the release of the album,
was the first witness as the trial on the rest of the issues began
Wednesday in Fulton County Superior Court.
   Starr said he went to Memphis in February 1987 to work with
Moman and his part of the agreement was to do the recording
sessions and pay for his plane fare and living expenses. Moman was
to provide the studio and produce the recordings.
   There was no formal contract, Starr said. Moman contends that
Starr owes him $146,239 for studio costs and out-of-pocket expenses.
   ``I felt some (contractual) agreement would be reached but it
always hinged on if the album was a success,'' Starr testified. ``I
had no understanding that any studio time would be billed to me.''
   Starr, who has said in court documents that he was under the
influence of alcohol during the recording sessions, said after
returning home to England and listening to the tapes he decided
they needed more work.
   Starr sings on the recordings, but did not play drums. Before he
would approve the album, he wanted to overdub his own drumming.
   Judge Clarence Cooper did not elaborate on his ruling Wednesday
to make permanent the temporary injunction against release of the
album. But court personnel said pre-trial evidence indicated that
Starr all along had the right to block the record _ under certain
conditions.
   Moman's attorneys have said Starr came to the producer in an
attempt to revive his waning music career. Though acknowledging he
had not had a hit record in several years, Starr testified he was
not desperate when he first talked with Moman.
   ``It was just a move for your career,'' he said. ``I wasn't
looking for Chips and Chips probably wasn't looking for me.''
   Starr embarked on a successful U.S. concert tour during the
summer, but according to testimony Wednesday, he refused a request
by Moman to include songs from the Memphis sessions in his live
shows.
   Starr's appearance drew several courthouse employees for a look
at Starr and his wife, actress Barbara Bach. After getting some
laughs by asking, ``Is it on?'' as he approached the witness stand
microphone, Starr was serious during most of his testimony.
   He appeared annoyed with some questions as his testimomy
extended more than an hour, asking the judge at one point: ``Can I
speak plainly? This `yes' and `no' is impossible for me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
