<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Cuba     11-15 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cuba,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Says Soviets Shipping Advanced Jet Fighters to Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Wednesday that the
Soviet Union has shipped advanced MiG-29 aircraft to Cuba, a move
it called ``wholly inconsistent'' with Moscow's stated desire to
promote peace in Central America.
   ``We see no legitimate Cuban need for such advanced aircraft,
and we do not consider this a helpful step,' said Richard Boucher,
the department's spokesman, who confirmed a report in The
Washington Times.
   Citing a need to protect intelligence data, Boucher refused to
provide details on when the aircraft arrived in Cuba, how many
planes had been shipped and whether Moscow also provided trainers.
   But the Times said one high-tech combat aircraft _ believed to
be the first of a squadron _ was discovered in Cuba late last
month. The MiG-29 was first photographed in crates by a U.S.
intelligence satellite after delivery to a Cuban port, the paper
said. It was identified as a MiG-29 after assembly.
   ``We find the action wholly inconsistent with the Soviet Union's
professed desire to cooperate in promoting the peaceful settlement
of disputes in the region,'' Boucher said, adding that Cuba is
under no threat from the United States.
   ``We are making our concerns known to the Soviets,'' he said.
   Boucher said Secretary of State James A. Baker III knew about
the MiG-29 aircraft earlier in the week, when he criticized the
Soviets for continuing to support ``violence, destruction and war''
in Central America by shipping weapons and money through Cuba and
Nicaragua.
   ``Soviet behavior toward Cuba and Central America remains the
biggest obstacle'' to improving relations between the superpowers,
he said in a speech.
   On Tuesday, President Bush charged that Cuba and Nicaragua,
Moscow's clients in the region, have ``aided and abetted'' the
leftist rebels in El Salvador, who have mounted bloody attacks in
that country this week. Baker said the rebels are using Soviet
rocket-propelled grenades.
   Bush said he would call on Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
to shut down the pipeline of weapons into the region when the two
leaders meet Dec. 2-3 on ships in the Mediterrean.
   ``I hope maybe we can have some action from him that will help
the democracies in this hemisphere,'' Bush said. ``This will be
very much on my mind.''
</TEXT>
