<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Romania     11-15 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Romania,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Ceausescu Rally in Berlin</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Berlin, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 East Germans, bolstered by democratic
advances in their own country, demonstrated Wednesday outside the
Romanian Embassy to denounce the Bucharest leadership as Stalinist
and repressive.
   The demonstration was called by supporters of exiled Romanian
writers to put pressure on Nicolae Ceausescu, the most hard-line
leader Eastern Europe.
   Only two months ago, East Germans themselves faced brutal
crackdowns by police for taking part in unauthorized protests. But
the nation has been swept up in a storm of reforms and democratic
changes since Oct. 18, when Egon Krenz was named to succeed his
ousted mentor, Erich Honecker, as Communist Party leader in East
Germany.
   Hundreds of thousands of demonstrators have been marching weekly
through Leipzig in demand of further reform, including free
elections.
   In the anti-Ceausescu rally, the group marched from the
Gethsemane Church to the Romanian Embassy, hoisting placards
reading ``Down with Stalinism.''
</TEXT>
