<FIRST>r a AM-Wendy'sWendy     11-15 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wendy's Wendy,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wendy, Not Her Real Name, Now Married, Living in the South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Would you buy a single cheese, large fries
and a Frosty from Melinda's?
   In 1969, R. David Thomas, founder of Wendy's International Inc.,
proudly named his downtown Columbus restaurant after his daughter,
Melinda.
   ``My brother and sisters couldn't pronounce Melinda, they called
me Wenda,'' said Wendy (or is it Melinda?) Thomas in an interview
prior to joining her father in the restaurant's 20th anniversary
celebration Wednesday.
   ``I don't even respond to Melinda. When people say it, I say
`WHO are you talking to?'''
   Thomas, Mayor Dana Rinehart and other Wendy's officials joined
store employees flipping burgers behind the counter of the original
Wendy's after a brief ceremony during which Rinehart proclaimed
Wednesday as Wendy's Day.
   Ms. Thomas, now 28, not only goes by the name Wendy, but swears
she still eats at Wendy's ``every chance I can.'' A single with
cheese, ketchup, tomato and lettuce is her favorite.
   She said growing up as the namesake for a business that has
sales of $3 billion a year had its ups and downs.
   ``It wasn't an ego thing. I just thought it was neat because Dad
would bring home hamburgers and thick chocolate milk shakes and we
didn't have to eat green beans,'' she said.
   She felt uncomfortable at times during her years at high school
and the University of Florida when she was introduced as Wendy of
Wendy's.
   ``I was extremely protective of myself,'' she said. ``I could
tell if I was being used. I was very selective _ too selective. Now
I hear about the dates I had and I wish it were true with some of
them. I wish I'd had of half the dates I hear about.''
   At college in Gainesville, Fla., she said: ``When people found
out who I was, they felt like I was this rich kid who had the world
in my hands. But I had a budget, a lot of times I was broke and
drank the cheapest beer I could find.''
   Ms. Thomas said she now works with her husband, Paul, the
manager of a Columbia, S.C., country club. She said she never
worked in a Wendy's store but as a teen-ager helped out at the
Wendy's at the state fair and worked a summer at the corporate
offices in suburban Dublin.
   She indicated no desire to return to the family business,
saying, ``I don't want to make other people uncomfortable because
I'm Dave Thomas' daughter.''
   She recalled her first Wendy's job at age 8 as ``really itchy.''
   ``We went downtown to a studio photographer and stuck my hair up
in braids and stuck pipe cleaners in it and it was real hard to sit
still,'' she said, recalling the photo session that led to the
Wendy's logo.
   Ms. Thomas said people in her new home are starting to learn who
she is and complain to her if the local Wendy's gets an order wrong.
   ``I ask them to please tell the manager. They'll fix it. These
people think I run every store.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
