<DOCNO> AP891115-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Arts-FederalSupport     11-15 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arts-Federal Support,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrat Says Conservatives Stirring Up Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democratic congressman concerned about
continued federal support for the arts said Wednesday that
conservatives are stirring up controversy over a few questionable
art projects to kill the National Endowment for the Arts.
   ``The right is using Mapplethorpe as their new Willie Horton,''
said Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont., during a hearing of his Education
and Labor subcommittee on postsecondary education.
   Willie Horton, a convicted rapist who committed more crimes
after failing to return from a prison furlough in Massachusetts,
was used as an issue in last year's presidntial campaign against
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Congress banned federal financing of ``obscene'' art and reduced
its $171 million appropriation for the NEA by $45,000 this year
after learning that federal funds had helped support two artists,
Andres Serrano and Robert Mapplethorpe, whose work was considered
obscene.
   That effort was led by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
   Williams, whose subcommittee is considering legislation to keep
the endowment operating, said, ``Those who want to see NEA unfunded
are utilizing the unwillingness of Congress to explain Serrano to
get their way.''
   He said members of Congress would find it easier to take action
against the NEA than engage in complicated discussions with their
constituents about the value of aid that sometimes supports
questionable taste.
   ``The endowment has given out 85,000 grants and run into
controversy on 20 of them,'' said Leonard Garment, an attorney who
helped establish the NEA.
   He said that NEA ``officials and panels have behaved overall
with an admirable sense of responsibility.''
   Bruce Fein, an attorney who opposes federal support of art,
argued, ``There is no First Amendment right to be subsidized by the
government.''
   ``Creative art does not need government subsidies to flourish,''
he said.
   But Williams, Garment and attorney Floyd Abrams said government
aid attract private donors and government refusal to fund art would
lead them away.
   ``There is a real problem that if corporate America begins to
think of the arts as tainted, the easy way out is to find something
else.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
