<SECOND>AM-Bush-Personnel,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Hampshire Educator Gets Bush Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will nominate John T.
MacDonald, New Hampshire's commissioner of education, as an
assistant secretary in the U.S. Department of Education, the White
House said Wednesday.
   MacDonald, if confirmed by the Senate, would succeed Beryl
Dorsett in the post in charge of elementary and secondary education
programs.
   MacDonald, 56, has been New Hampshire's commissioner since 1986.
He is a former teacher and superintendent of schools in Dartmouth,
Mass., Walpole, Mass., and Wallingford, Conn.
   The White House also announced Bush will nominate:
   _Harriet Winsar Isom as ambassador to Benin. Ms. Isom, 53, is a
career foreign service officer who has been charge d'affaires at
the American Embassy in Vientiane, Laos, since 1986. She would
succeed Walter Edward Stadtler.
   _Ronald Frank Ederer, an El Paso, Texas, lawyer to be U.S.
attorney for the western district of Texas. Ederer, 46, served as
an assistant U.S. attorney there in 1972-76 and was a part-time
U.S. marshal in El Paso in 1976-80.
