<DOCNO> AP891115-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-BisonPlan 1stLd-Writethru a0583 11-15 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bison Plan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0583,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede HELENA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with wildlife director briefing congressmen.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montana's hunters and ranchers will be free to
kill bison that stray from northern Yellowstone National Park this
winter and as many as 200 of the animals might be killed, the
state's wildlife director said today.
   Last year more than 500 Yellowstone bison were killed in Montana
after they roamed from the park. That was an unprecedented number
and prompted outcries from some environmentalists and
conservationists.
   K.L. Cool, Montana's director of fish and game, said the state
and officials of the National Park Service have agreed that the
northern bison herd at Yelowstone should be limited to about 200 to
300 animals, so they can be better managed.
   Cool and Bob Barbee, superintendent of the park, briefed some
congressmen as well as environmental and conservation leaders, on
the bison management plan. But Barbee told reporters he still
hasn't determined how the herd will be reduced from the current
roughly 400 animals, or how the bison will be kept from roaming
onto Montana rangeland this winter.
   ``On the long haul, trying to herd a buffalo doesn't work.
Buffalo are herded where they want to go,'' said Barbee, adding
that efforts will be made to keep the bison in the park by ``gentle
hazing'' and whatever else might work.
   But Cool said the state will maintain its policy of shooting any
bison that cross into Montana until the northern Yellowstone herd
is reduced to about 200 animals.
   ``Montana does not want to be viewed as being unrealistic or
uncooperative,'' he said. But he said the state legislature has
required that hunters be free to shoot the bison that roam into the
state.
   Ranchers have complained vigorously that the buffalo cause
damage to property and they fear the animals will transmit
brucellosis _ a disease the interferes with reproduction _ to their
cattle. Blood tests have shown that more than half of the bison
killed in Montana last year had brucellosis, he said.
   Under the Montana plan, bison will be shot in warden-supervised
hunts this winter and spring if they leave the park.
   Yellowstone has about 2,500 bison in three major herds on its
more than 2.4 million acres. But only the northern, or Lamar, herd,
poses a concern to Montana ranchers. Because of a series of mild
winters and other factors, the northern bison herd grew to more
than 900 last year and most of them roamed along the Yellowstone
River Valley into Montana where 569 of the animals were killed.
   Barbee said the Park Service will try to develop ways to better
control the size of the northern herd to keep it below 300 animals.
But he said ways to do that ``haven't been worked out'' yet. He
ruled out the possiblity that hunters would be allowed to hunt the
bison within park boundaries.
   Wyoming, on the park's southern edge, does not allow the
shooting of stray bison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1522EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru   11-15 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0643,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Claims Kidnapping of American, Two West Germans</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: CORRECTS name in lede to The Organization of Just Revenge. Inserts
3 grafs after 8th, ``The kidnapping...'' to UPDATE with no confirmation
from West German Embassy. ADDS final graf with hostage background information.
No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously unknown group calling itself
The Organization of Just Revenge claimed Wednesday it has kidnapped
an American and two naturalized West Germans in Beirut.
   The claim came in a typewritten statement delivered to a Western
news agency along with photocopies of the passports and visas of
the three victims.
   The American's name was given in the documents as Deborah
Fahrend, 54, of San Francisco. The brief Arabic statement said she
is a publisher-journalist.
   The documents identified two Germans as Mounir Shamseddin Sami,
39, born in Lebanon, and his 7-year-old son Danjel, born in Berlin.
   The statement said: ``The Organization of Just Revenge announces
its responsibility for kidnapping the West German Mounir Sami (born
in Lebanon) and his son Danjel Sami and American
publisher-journalist Deborah Fahrend in Beirut for their activities
in Lebanon.''
   There was no further elaboration in the poorly typed statement,
which failed to say when the abduction took place and made no
demands.
   One photocopy showed a visa issued for Ms. Fahrend by the
Lebanese Embassy in Nicosia, Cyprus, on Nov. 1 along with an entry
stamp by the Lebanese security department Nov. 3.
   The two West Germans also entered Lebanon on Nov. 3 on similar
visas, issued by the Lebanese Embassy in Nicosia on the same day
Ms. Fahrend got hers.
   The kidnapping claim could not immediately be verified.
   The American Embassy in Beirut has been closed since Sept. 22.
   The West German Embassy in Beirut said it had no knowledge of
the abduction before the statement was released after nightfall.
   ``But the two victims could be naturalized Germans from Lebanese
descent who are not registered with the embassy in Beirut,'' said a
German official who answered the phone at the embassy. He declined
to give his name.
   Not counting the three people mentioned in the claim, there are
18 foreign hostages being held in Lebanon, including eight
Americans, four Britons, two West Germans, two Swiss, an Italian
and an Irishman.
   The longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Most of the hostages are believed held by pro-Iranian extremist
factions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0141 </DOCNO>
