<FIRST>r w AM-GarbagePoll     11-15 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Garbage Poll,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Americans Ready for War on Garbage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About one in every two Americans believes that
garbage disposal problems rank among the three most pressing issues
facing local governments, exceeded only by fighting drugs and
providing adequate education, according to a survey released
Wednesday by the garbage industry.
   The poll, released by the National Solid Waste Managagement
Association, said 52 percent of the people surveyed nationally
consider ensuring adequate garbage collection is a serious or
extremely serious problem for their local officials.
   That reflected a higher level of concern about garbage
collection than for providing affordable housing or expanding
police and fire protection, said Allen Moore, president of the
trade group that represents waste disposal industry.
   The survey was conducted by Cambridge Reports and included
telephone or face-to-face interviews of 3,000 people during a
four-month period this year. There was a 3 percent margin of error.
   The survey also indicated that public opposition to incinerators
that turn garbage into energy is easing in most parts of the
country amid increasing worries about finding places to bury solid
wastes.
   It said that 44 percent of those surveyed nationwide said they
would favor locating such incinerator plants in their area, 8
percentage points higher than those reponding similarly in a poll a
year earlier. Thirty-six percent of the people opposed such plants
and 20 percent said they didn't know.
   Opposition to burning garbage continued to be greatest in the
Northeast, where a new waste-to-energy plant was favored by only 36
percent of those surveyed, compared to 42 percent who opposed. Even
in that region, however, those who favored a plant incrased by 5
percentage points compared to the 1988 survey.
   The Northeast, however, had the largest percentage of people, 67
percent of those surveyed, who considered garbage collection as a
serious or extremely serious issue facing local governments,
ranking only behind the battle to curb drug abuse.
   Garbage collection issues were found to be of the least concern
in the central part of the country, where it ranked last among five
areas of concern with only 37 percent of the people saying they
considered it a serious local problem.
   In other findings, the poll indicated an increased interest in
recycling programs, but it said the public no longer considers
recycling ``a simple `magic bullet' solution'' to the disposal of
waste products, said Moore, the trade group's president.
   Two-thirds of those surveyed said they had participated in
recycling cans, bottles or papers and 44 percent said they would
buy products containing recycled materials if given a choice,
according to the survey.
   In a related report, the trade group said that as of the end of
September, 38 states and the District of Columbia have enacted some
form of waste recycling laws, although in many cases the full
requirements do not go into effect until the early to mid-1990s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RuralVeterans     11-15 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rural Veterans,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Derwinski Promises Rural Hospitals in Sparsely Populated Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterans Secretary Edward J. Derwinski pledged
Wednesday that rural VA hospitals in Montana, South Dakota and
other sparsely populated areas will remain open despite budgetary
constraints.
   ``I have no intention of closing and no intention of making
changes that in any way would diminish hospital care in rural
areas,'' Derwinski told the Veterans Affairs Committee. ``These
kinds of locations must stay.''
   Derwinski testified at a hearing into the delivery of health
care to rural veterans. Other witnesses and western state senators
complained that rural veterans suffer from a lack of medical
personnel, a lack of access to health care facilities and a lack of
resources at the rural hospitals since most are unaffiliated with
medical schools.
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., complained that policy makers in
Washington are fundamentally oblivious to the needs of rural
America. ``They really don't understand the sense of space and
distance,'' he said.
   Although 95 percent of all veterans live within a 100-mile
radius of the nearest VA facility, according to the American
Legion, in Montana 83 percent of the veterans served by the Miles
City hospital live more than 100 miles from it.
   Baucus noted that Los Angeles has nine centers compared with two
in Montana, and Derwinski noted that in his native Chicago three
hospitals were within six miles from one another.
   Sen. Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D., complained that veterans with
non-service-connected disabilities and incomes above $16,500 if
single or $20,000 if married are being denied VA care because of
service cutbacks over the last five years.
   Those ``Class B'' and ``Class C'' veterans are generally
provided care when resources are available. The poorer and
service-connected disabled _ ``Class A'' _ receive first-priority
care.
   Dr. Daniel Winship of the VA's medical division said there was
no policy decision to cut out the B and C patients. He said the
demand for care by Category A patients has ``virtually consumed''
the VA's resources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Gate     11-15 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Gate,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>200-Year-Old Gate Again a Stage for History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle-scarred sandstone columns of the
Brandenburg Gate, which were the backdrop for Hitler's last stand
and a workers' uprising against Communism in 1953, once again tower
over the stage of history.
   The 200-year-old gate, Berlin's most famous landmark, has stood
as the symbol of German division for 28 years.
   With the Berlin Wall quickly crumbling, the gate is being called
the symbol of German unity. It also has been the backdrop for much
of the television coverage beamed around the world in the past week
of fast-moving developments.
   East Germany has said it is considering opening a Berlin Wall
border crossing at the Brandenburg Gate. There was wide speculation
in West Berlin that an opening would be knocked through the wall
Thursday, although there was no official confirmation.
   The gate _ the size of a five-story building _ remained on the
Eastern side when the Berlin Wall was built in 1961. The famous
Unten den Linden boulevard ends at the gate.
   On the Western side, the sprawling avenue that leads to the gate
was renamed June 17 Street, after the date of the workers' uprising
in East Berlin in 1953 that was bloodily crushed by Soviet tanks.
   East Berlin workers, angered by the nationalization and
collectivization policies of the Communist government, began their
street demonstrations at the Brandenburg Gate and tore down the red
flag from the top of the gate.
   In the closing days of World War II, Soviet tanks rumbled by the
gate as they closed in on Adolf Hitler's bunker in the chancellery.
Only a few hundred yards away was the heart of Hitler's government
in a small complex on Wilhelmstrasse, which also served as the seat
of the imperial government. The Reichstag also is not far away.
   The Brandenburg Gate also marked Hitler's rise to power. Nazi
brown shirts staged a triumphant torch parade through the gate when
Hitler was named chancellor on Jan. 30, 1933.
   Built from 1788 to 1791 by Carl Gotthard Langhans, the
six-column gate was commissioned by Prussian King Frederick Wilhelm
II. When it was built, it opened the road to the region of
Brandenburg, getting its name.
   The gate was modeled after the Acropolis in Athens to reflect
the king's intention to make Berlin a city of learning and arts.
   On top of the gate is a bronze chariot with the goddess
Victoria. It was hauled away to Paris when Napoleon defeated the
Prussians at Jena and Auerstadt on Oct. 27, 1806. He marched into
Berlin through the Brandenburg Gate.
   The chariot was brought back to Berlin after Napoleon's defeat
in 1814. After the Franco-German war in 1870-71, the victorious
Prussians made a triumphal return to Berlin, the new imperial
capital, again through the Brandenburg Gate.
   The gate was heavily damaged in the last days of World War II
and marked the border between the Soviet and British sectors of
conquered Berlin.
   It was restored between 1956 and 1958. The chariot was repaired
and paid for by West Berlin under Mayor Willy Brandt, but East
Berlin authorities removed the Prussian eagle and the iron cross
from Victoria's staff before mounting it again.
   In 1963, Communist soldiers dropped huge red drapes over the
gate to prevent President John F. Kennedy from looking into East
Berlin when he visited West Berlin and delivered his ``Ich bin ein
Berliner'' speech.
   The gate, the last of the 20 gates to Berlin still standing, is
66 feet high, 215 feet wide and 36 feet deep.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Parkinson'sDrug     11-15 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Parkinson's Drug,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Confirms Drug Slows Parkinson's Disease</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Parkinson's Research</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 6 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly approved drug appears to be the first to
slow Parkinson's disease, seeming to cut the destructive
progression of the incurable brain illness in half, a major study
confirms.
   The research, conducted on 800 people, found that the drug
deprenyl helped people who were not yet sick enough to require
levodopa, the standard medicine for Parkinson's.
   The results are similar to a smaller study, conducted on 54
patients, that was published in August.
   ``It does not stop the disease,'' said Dr. Ira Shoulson. ``But
it may well slow the disease. This may be the first treatment for a
neurodegenerative disorder that actually slows the disease.''
   Until now, levodopa has been the mainstay of Parkinson's
treatment, easing symptoms but not slowing the underlying disease.
Doctors usually reserve this drug until relatively severe symptoms
develop.
   The incurable disease attacks a region of the brain, causing
shuffling gait, difficulty talking and other symptoms. It typically
strikes people in their 50s and 60s and affects about 500,000
Americans.
   The latest study began in 1987 and was scheduled to continue
until late next year. However, researchers stopped the study in
February because of indications of a dramatic effect from the
medicine.
   When the results were analyzed, doctors found the treatment had
reduced the need for levodopa by 57 percent.
   ``Over 12 years, this might buy 50 percent more time of less
impaired disability,'' said Shoulson, who directed the study at the
University of Rochester Medical Center.
   In their report, the researchers wrote that ``the results
translate into a delay in the development of disability of nearly
one year (over the two-year study period) and an extended capacity
for full-time employment.''
   The study was conducted by members of the Parkinson Study Group
at 28 medical centers in the United States and Canada. It was
published in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine.
   In the study, 399 people with early, untreated Parkinson's
disease were given deprenyl, while 401 others received another
experimental medicine or dummy pills. During the followup, 97 of
those who got deprenyl worsened enough to need levodopa, compared
with 176 in the comparison group.
   At the start of the study, people's symptoms included mild
tremors, stiffness and slow movement. By the time they needed
levodopa, they often had to stop working or had trouble caring for
themselves.
   The doctors are not sure how deprenyl works, but they speculated
that it somehow slows the underlying disease process rather than
simply easing symptoms.
   The drug, sold under the brand name Eldepryl, was approved by
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration for routine use in September.
   The latest study will continue to test the effect of the
medicine when combined with levodopa in people with advanced
Parkinson's disease.
   The earlier study with the drug was conducted by Dr. J. William
Langston of the California Parkinson's Foundation in San Jose and
published in the journal Science.
   In another report Wednesday on Parkinson's disease, University
of California researchers said they have found that implanting
genetically altered skin cells in the brains of rats can reduce
symptoms of Parkinson's disease. The skin cells were genetically
altered to make them produce L-dopa, a chemical that is lacking in
the brains of Parkinson's disease patients.
   The research does not portend a cure for Parkinson's and is not
ready for human testing, but it may offer a possible alternative to
fetal cell implants, which have proved effective against the
disease but which have become mired in political and ethical
controversy, scientists said.
   The results of the study, conducted by Gage and colleagues at
the University of California at San Diego, including Dr. Theodore
Friedmann, a pioneer in the development of genetically modified
cells, were to be published in the latest issue of Proceedings of
the National Academy of Sciences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
