<FIRST>u w AM-AFL-CIOConvention     11-15 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AFL-CIO Convention,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kirkland Re-Elected; Five New Members of AFL-CIO Governing Body</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lane Kirkland was elected Wednesday to a sixth
term as AFL-CIO president and the labor federation reshaped its
governing body to include the leader of its newest union, the
United Mine Workers.
   UMW President Richard Trumka was among five new members elected
to the 14.1 million-member federation's executive council, a
symbolic gesture to cap the union's decision to rejoin the umbrella
organization after four decades outside.
   Trumka, 40, also adds young blood to a council made up
predominantly of white men in their 50s, 60s and 70s. A woman and a
black union leader also were elected Wednesday, but because of
retirements the number of blacks on the 33-member board fell from
three to two and the number of women held at three. That comes at a
time when some contend that women and minorities are the labor
movement's best hope if it is to reverse its organizing setbacks of
the past decade.
   The federation elections came on a day when the convention
delegates also heard from President Bush and prepared for a debate
Thursday on whether the AFL-CIO should endorse abortion-rights
resolutions.
   A compromise struck this week will allow for debate on the issue
Thursday before the question, which has divided many labor leaders
at a gathering whose theme is solidarity, is referred to he
Executive Council for further study.
   The elections of Kirkland, Secretary Treasurer Thomas Donahue
and the new council members all were by unanimous vote but not
before Hispanic labor leaders protested about being excluded from
the board at a time of mounting efforts to organize Hispanics.
   ``Once again the Hispanics have been excluded from the process
and excluded from the AFL-CIO,'' said Jack Otero, a vice president
of the Transportation and Communications Union. ``This is an
unhappy day.''
   Added United Steelworkers international representative Oscar
Sanchez: ``I leave this conventiom a disillusioned delegate but not
a defeated trade unionist. We will return.''
   Kirkland, in thanking the delegates for their support, said:
   ``I say to you without hesitation or reservation that this is
the most exciting, the most inspiring and the most enthusiastic
time in modern history to be at the center of everything in the
American trade union movement. There is no place on earth I would
rather be and there is nothing that I would rather do.''
   In addition to Trumka, elected to the Executive Council were:
John Sturdivant, president of the American Federation of Government
Employees; Susan Bianchi-Sand, president of the Association of
Flight Attendants; George Kourpias, president of the International
Association of Machinists, and Moe Biller, president of the
American Postal Workers Union.
   ``I see myself as a representative of the service industry and
of women in the work force,'' said the 43-year-old Bianchi-Sand, a
United Airlines flight attendant.
   Trumka, a miner-lawyer whose union is in the midst of a bitter
strike against Pittston Co. coal mines in Virginia, West Virginia
and Kentucky, won a seat on the board just weeks after the United
Mine Workers affiliated with the AFL-CIO.
   Sturdivant, 51, who is black, replaced Kenneth Blaylock, the man
he defeated for the presidency of AFGE, a 700,000 member union
representing federal employees.
   Kourpias, 57, took the slot held by his predecessor, William
Winpisinger, who retired.
   Biller, 73, the longtime New York APWU leader who has been the
365,000-member union's president for nine years, became the second
leader of a postal union on the board, joining National Association
of Letter Carriers President Vincent Sombrotto.
</TEXT>
