<SECOND>PM-AFL-CIO Convention, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0567,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Calls for Joint Effort to Aid Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 14 grafs new with Bush remarks; picks up 12th graf pvs,
AFL-CIO President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush told the AFL-CIO today that
labor, business and government should form a new alliance to be
``partners and activists'' for Poland's future.
   He also told the labor federation's biennial convention that he
would discuiss the importance of trade unions in ``building a free
country'' in his Dec. 2-3 shipboard summit off Malta with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Steering clear of issues on which his administration and
organized labor disagree, Bush lavished praise on Solidarity leader
Lech Walesa and praised the federation for its long active support
of Walesa.
   Walesa was present as the president spoke.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, speaking a few hours
before Bush at the labor federation's convention, accused the
president of praising Solidarity while working to undermine U.S.
labor unions.
   ``American workers are entitled to as much support from an
American president as workers in Poland and other countries,'' the
Maine Democrat said.
   He also criticized Bush for refusing to intervene in the
eight-month Eastern Airlines strike.
   But the president focused on Solidarity and the changing face of
Eastern Europe. ``Across Eastern Europe, we see vindication of the
AFL-CIO's refusal to deal with puppet unions controlled by either
employers or governments,'' he said.
   ``The AFL-CIO has fought for ... freedom around the world, and I
will carry that message to Mr. Gorbachev. I also want to talk with
President Gorbachev about the opportunities to move beyond
containment in U.S.-Soviet relations _ to find areas of mutual
advantage in our relationship.''
   Congress is moving to provide more than a half-billion dollars
in economic aid for Poland and Hungary, steps that have the backing
of the administration.
   But Bush said, ``I call on the American labor movement, the
business community and government to look for ways to support a
partnership for progress in Poland.''
   ``Labor, business and government can and should be partners and
activisits for Poland's future,'' he said.
   Earlier, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush is
ready to sign a bill raising the minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.25
by April 1991 _ a measure labor helped negotiate.
   Bush's speech came a week after the White House, labor and
congressional Democrats struck a deal to raise the hourly minimum
wage. That has tempered somewhat the criticism of Bush by labor
leaders, but praise for the president is hard to find among the 800
delegates to the 14.1 million-member federation's biennial
convention.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland was unanimously re-elected today
to a sixth-two year term. Thomas Donahue was the unanimous choice
to continue as the federation's secretary treasurer.
   ``I am honored that you have moved to keep me on the bridge as
we move into the last decade of the tumultuous 20th century,''
Kirkland said. ``There is no place on earth that I would rather
be.''
   Many union leaders took the convention floor the past two days
to criticize Bush's stance on issues ranging from child care and
national health care to the Eastern Airlines strike, which Bush in
March refused to block by using his power to name an emergency
mediation board.
   Congress last week gave final passage to a measure creating a
congressional study of the strike designed to produce
recommendations for a settlement, and the labor leaders said a Bush
veto would end any pretense of cordiality between the AFL-CIO and
the administration.
   ``He missed a golden opportunity,'' Air Line Pilots Association
President Henry Duffy said of Bush's refusal to intervene in March.
``He's got another chance now.''
   George Leitz, president of the Transport Workers Union
representing striking Eastern flight attendants added: ``That
kinder, gentler George better not veto this legislation.''
   Moe Biller, president of the American Postal Workers Union,
called on Bushoward labor by lifting the ban on rehiring the air
traffic controllers Reagan fired in 1981 after they struck.
   ``By any measure of justice, these workers have paid the price
for taking actions they felt necessary at the time,'' Biller said
in a Tuesday letter to Bush. ``I ask you to give us a sign
(Wednesday) that there is room for clemency in your
administration.''
   The delegates broke into loud cheering and applause Tuesday when
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said Democratic congressional
leaders planned to seek another increase in the minimum wage in
1992, a presidential election year.
   ``If he will not sign it, then we we'll just have to get another
president after 1992 who will,'' Kennedy said.
   Kirkland, who recently referred to Bush as ``Reagan Lite,'' has
tempered his criticisms of late, in part because of the minimum
wage compromise.
   ``We have channels of communication that I think are superior to
those that we had during the Reagan years,'' he said in an
interview last week. ``I think you'd have to say any judgment is
still pending.''
   No such uncertainty clouds labor relation's with Mitchell, who
has increased his stature among the union leaders by successfully
fighting Bush's effort to cut capital gains taxes.
   ``I have considerable and growing admiration for Sen.
Mitchell,'' Kirkland said.
   Kennedy pledged to get a national health care measure to Bush's
desk next year.
   That promise came as delegates approved an aggressive lobbying
effort designed to sway Congress and business leaders into a
compromise agreement on such a plan.
</TEXT>
