<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     11-15 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urged to Meet With Allies Before _ Not After _ Gorbachev Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush should meet with the
NATO allies before _ not after _ his summit next month with
President Mikhail Gorbachev, the head of NATO's legislative arm
said Wednesday.
   Patrick Duffy, president of the North Atlantic Assembly, said it
was ``unthinkable'' Bush would meet with Gorbachev without first
consulting the other members of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   Duffy, a member of Britain's House of Commons, said the agenda
for the Dec. 2-3 shipboard meeting off the island of Malta was
likely to be dominated by the dramatic changes in Eastern Europe,
particularly in East Germany.
   NATO sources, who demanded anonymity, said a senior U.S.
official will meet with the allies in Brussels on Dec. 4 to discuss
the summit, but it was not yet certain who that would be.
   In Washington, administration officials have said Bush was
considering calling a NATO summit in Brussels after the Gorbachev
meeting to discuss new political and military strategy for the West.
   The NATO sources said contingency plans were being made for such
a presidential visit.
   French President Francois Mitterrand hurriedly scheduled a
meeting Saturday of all 12 leaders of the European Community, the
Common Market trading bloc, to discuss Eastern Europe.
   Some analysts believe the move was designed to give the
community leaders a chance to discuss the developments before the
Bush-Gorbachev summit.
   Duffy reminded Bush that the political atmosphere in Europe was
sensitive.
   ``There is a great joy and genuine emotion, but there is also a
good deal of confusion and concern about where this process will
eventually take us,'' he said.
   ``It is absolutely imperative,'' he said, ``that the U.S.
president demonstrates a true awareness of the current situation by
offering reassurance and predictability to the European allies.''
   He said Bush has ``a special responsibility and the
international situation demands nothing less than he meet this
responsibility.''
   Duffy cautioned against a replay of the 1986 summit at
Reykjavik, Iceland, between President Ronald Reagan and Gorbachev,
which turned into a much more ambitious meeting than had been
expected.
   Gorbachev arrived with sweeping arms control proposals that
caught the Americans off guard. The allies were furious such
discussions took place without consultations.
   ``Politicians of every stripe in Europe are agreed there must be
no more Yaltas or Reykjaviks,'' Duffy said. ``The present system
would be unable to contain a repetition along these lines.''
   Yalta refers to the controversial 1945 meeting of President
Franklin D. Roosevelt, Soviet leader Josef Stalin and British Prime
Minister Winston Churchill at which the shape of post-war Europe
was determined.
   The North Atlantic Assembly is made up of legislators of the
NATO nations.
</TEXT>
