<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     11-15 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Calls for Renewed Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed concern
Wednesday about recent fighting in Cambodia and urged various
factions to return to the negotiating table to seek a political
settlement.
   The statement came on the eve of a U.N. vote on Cambodia's seat
at the international body. The United Nations is expected to
confirm retention of the seat by an opposition coalition that
includes non-communist factions backed by the United States.
   ``There has been military activity by the Khmer Rouge and other
elements in Cambodia,'' said Richard Boucher, a department
spokesman. ``We regret the return to the battlefield in Cambodia
and we support all efforts to return to the negotiating table as
soon as possible.''
   ``A comprehensive settlement, which we think is still needed,
will require agreement among the Cambodian facions and the other
involved parties on the formation of an interim coalition
authority,'' he said.
   Last summer, a Paris peace conference on Cambodia dissolved over
the failure to reach agreement on the Khmer Rouge's involvement in
an interim government. Under leader Pol Pot, the Khmer Rouge killed
more than one million people before Vietnam invaded Cambodia in
1978.
   Vietnam, which installed a puppet government in Phnom Penh, said
its occupation troops have been withdrawn as of Sept. 31. Last
week, Britain became the first Western nation to acknowledge that
Vietnamese forces are no longer in Cambodia.
   The Chinese, who have supplied the Khmer Rouge, and the
non-communist opposition coalition contend Vietnamese troops remain
in Cambodia disguised as Cambodians.
   In a related development, Congress is continuing restrictions on
President Bush's ability to send weapons to non-communist factions,
according to congressional sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The restrictions, adopted over the administration's objections,
prevent the president from using contingency funds from the CIA to
arm the Cambodian guerrillas unless Congress approves the action
first. The restrictions are contained in a secret appendix to the
military appropriations bill.
</TEXT>
