<FIRST>r w AM-FingersSaved 1stLd-Writethru a0684 11-15 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fingers Saved, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fingers Reached Two Days After Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restores garbled copy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEROY TILLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Through what was called ``a miracle of
international cooperation,'' three of four fingers were reattached
to a Polish sailor's hand, more than two days after they were
severed in a shipboard accident.
   Dr. Jimmy Chow, director of replantation and chief of the
microvascular surgery team at the Washington Hospital Center, said
Wednesday the fingers were not reattached to the hand of Zbyskyo
Kajowski for more than 54 hours.
   This appears to be a record because the longest time previously
known between this type of accident and reattachment was 39 hours,
said Chow, who coordinated the surgery.
   The accident occurred aboard the Greek freighter, SS Success, on
Nov. 6 some 500 miles off Bermuda when Kajowski's hand was caught
under falling machinery, doctors said.
   Kajowski, 39, suffered what Chow characterized as ``a severe
crush-amputation'' injury that severed the four fingers of the left
hand where they meet the palm.
   The ship captain received emergency advice from Dr. Edward
Schultze, head of the emergency room at King Edward VII Hospital in
Bermuda. That included immersion of the digits in a saline solution
and keep them cool but not frozen.
   Paramedics on the ship gave Kajowski emergency first-aid and
doctors on Bermuda contacted the U.S. Coast Guard, which called
Chow, the doctor said.
   ``Right then time was important,'' Chow said. ``The ship was two
days away from where it could meet a U.S. Navy helicopter that
could take the sailor to Bermuda. ... It was a miracle of
international cooperation.''
   Once the freighter reached the rendezvous point, Kajowski was
flown to Bermuda by a Navy helicopter.
   Kajowski received emergency treatment in Bermuda and the Greek
shipping company authorized a private air ambulance to fly the
sailor to Washington.
   The surgery, performed on Nov. 8, took nearly 15 hours, Chow
said.
   All of the severed digits except for Kajowski's index finger
were able to be saved.
   Chow said the prognosis for a full recovery by his patient was
excellent. He said that although the sailor was still hospitalized,
he has made a fist and straightened his damaged fingers.
   Kajowski will be able to return to sea, Chow said, and should be
able to perform all the duties he could in the past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
