<DOCNO> AP891115-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 2001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SexReporting     11-15 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sex Reporting,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policy Requires Teachers, Counselors to Report Sexually Active Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new state law on child abuse has prompted
Arizona's largest school district to enact a policy requiring
teachers and counselors to report to police the names of sexually
active students.
   The legislator who co-sponsored the child-abuse law said
reporting sexually active students wasn't her intent and she'll
work to revise the measure.
   ``We rewrote the law to bring the state's child abuse reporting
laws up to federal specifications,'' said Rep. Leslie Johnson. ``We
never thought it could be construed as it has been in the Mesa
district.''
   In the meantime, school officials say some students won't talk
to them about such problems as pregnancy and sexually transmitted
diseases, knowing a police investigation might ensue.
   ``The youngsters tend to clam up when we tell them we can no
longer promise confidentiality,'' said Mountain View High School
Principal James Curlett said. ``They will turn to their friends for
help, and when it comes to advice about subjects like communicable
diseases, that would be disastrous.''
   Dobson High School counseling director Bob Merlene, said the
policy probably will deter some students from seeking counseling.
   ``This policy does more to scare than to help our students,'' he
said.
   Changes made this year in Arizona's child-abuse reporting
statute require schools to report to police any student who they
have reasonable grounds to believe has been a victim of sexual
abuse, sexual conduct with a minor, sexual assault, sexual
molestation, commercial sexual exploitation of a minor, incest or
child prostitution.
   The previous law required reporting only in cases of sexual
molestation.
   However, as interpreted by Mesa schools and Mesa police, school
officials must inform police of any and all sexual activity. The
Mesa district has 61,700 students and covers most of Mesa, parts of
two other Phoenix suburbs, and the Salt River Indian Reservation.
   ``Our interpretation of the law is that the school district must
report all sexual activity among students, and then it is up to the
police to determine if it is a situation in which there is
reasonable grounds to believe a minor has been abused,'' said Sgt.
Mike Hayes, Mesa police spokesman.
   Hayes said that if two 15-year-olds are kissing and fondling
each other under the bleachers, and a teacher sees them, the
teacher is obligated under the new law to report the incident to
police for investigation.
   The number of child abuse reports to police by school officials
hasn't increased since the district policy went into effect in
September, Hayes said.
   Fred Skoglund, assistant superintendent of the Mesa district,
said the problem is in the wording of the legislation.
   ``We believe we are forced to comply with the letter of the law,
even though we do not believe it was the intent,'' Skoglund said.
   However, officials from the neighboring Tempe and Chandler
districts said they interpreted the law differently. They said
their reporting procedures haven't changed and that police are only
called in instances of obvious abuse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
