<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--DrugProbe     11-15 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Drug Probe,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Undercover Investigation Finds No Drugs in School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTLE ROCK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheriff's deputies posing as students
spent six months in high schools looking for drug use, but came up
empty-handed.
   ``It's great news,'' Jill Fox, Douglas County schools
spokeswoman, said Tuesday. ``It really gives a strong picture of
the teachers and administrators and the kids.''
   Sheriff's Lt. Bill Walker said the operation was planned in
August 1988 after a school district survey showed an alarmingly
high amount of drug use by young people outside the schools.
   The sheriff recruited an undisclosed number of officers to
mingle with students in the county's three high schools last spring
and this fall.
   The officers fooled students and teachers, by doing homework,
going to football games and hanging out with students. But they
failed to make a single drug purchase, officials said.
   ``We're not denying there's a drug problem, but we're saying
we're being successful at keeping it out of the schools,'' Walker
said. ``It shows a lot of the drug education and concern by the
schools and the sheriff's department is starting to pay off.''
