<FIRST>u a AM-RiotTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0687 11-15 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0687,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Calls Shooting by Officer Unjustified</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 15th, `When the...,' to UPDATE with later
testimony. Picks up 16th graf pvs, `Within an...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A policeman who fatally shot a black motorcyclist
acted recklessly and in defiance of police regulations, prosecutors
said Wednesday as the trial opened into two deaths that touched off
racial violence in January.
   Defense attorneys said their client shot in self-defense.
   William Lozano 31, faces two manslaughter counts in the slayings
of the driver, Clement Lloyd, 23, and his passenger, Allan
Blanchard, 24, who died of injuries suffered when the motorcycle
crashed after the shooting.
   Assistant State Attorney Don Horn told the racially mixed jury
that Lozano violated police regulations when he stepped into the
street and fired at Lloyd.
   ``This shooting was not justified,'' Horn said. ``At the time
Lozano fired the shot, he was in no danger of being struck by the
motorcycle.''
   Testimony will show, he said, that Lozano fired at the
motorcycle as it was about to pass him, not hit him.
   ``It was not a life-or-death situation, it was not a
split-second decision and he did not have to shoot,'' the
prosecutor said.
   But defense attorney Roy Black said Lozano acted not out of
racism, but in self-defense as the speeding motorycle headed
directly at him to escape a pursuing squad car. He said no one the
night of the shooting could see each other well enough in the
Overton neighborhood to determine skin color.
   ``Officer Lozano did not shoot his gun because he is Hispanic,''
Black said. ``Clement Lloyd did not die because he was black.''
   Lozano shot only because the motorcycle, driven by a desperate
Lloyd, was about to run into him, the defense contends.
   ``He had a second, a half second, to make a decision to save his
life,'' Black said.
   Dade Circuit Judge Joseph Farina cleared the last barriers to
the trial by rejecting defense contentions that the threat of
violence hung over the trial and could frighten jurors into
convicting Lozano to avoid another riot.
   The six-member jury is made up of two blacks, one Hispanic and
three whites. The alternates are two Hispanics and two whites.
   The shooting took place Jan. 16 as the Colombian-born Lozano and
his partner were stopped on a street in the predominantly black
Overtown, talking to the victim of a minor crime. As they talked,
another squad car was chasing down a speeding motorcycle driven by
Lloyd and carrying Blanchard.
   When the motorcycle turned onto the street where Lozano was
standing, the officer fired one shot from his police weapon,
killing Lloyd instantly and sending the motorcycle crashing into a
car. Blanchard died later.
   One of the prosecution's star witnesses, Eddie Johnson,
testified later Wednesday that he had been talking to Lozano and
his partner about his stolen license plate tag when the shooting
occurred.
   Johnson said he spotted the motorcycle and called it to the
attention of Lozano, who was looking for a theft form in the trunk
of his police car.
   ``He went a few steps and put his radio up,'' said Johnson. ``He
took a few more steps with his weapon. He aimed it in that general
direction. ... I ducked. When I ducked, I heard the shot,'' Johnson
said.
   He estimated the motorcycle was going at 50 or 60 miles per
hour. But on cross examination by Black, Johnson admitted he had
given a higher speed in his initial statements to police and he
also acknowledged telling police he could not determine if the
motorcyle was heading directly for Lozano.
   Within an hour after the shooting, an angry crowd of Overtown
residents had gathered and began pelting officers with rocks and
bottles. The violence quickly spread into a three-day riot during
the week leading up to the Super Bowl in Miami.
   The disturbances left one looter shot to death, 11 people
injured by gunfire and 13 buildings burned down.
   Lloyd was later found to have high levels of alcohol and THC _
the active chemical in marijuana _ in his bloodstream at the time
of his death. He also had 5.5 grams of marijuana and $1,500 in cash
in his pocket, facts the defense contends shows he was a
drug-crazed dealer desperate enough to run down a policeman to
avoid arrest and more jail time.
   The city later set up a commission to examine the roots of the
racial disturbance, the fourth to hit Miami in the 1980s. The
previous disturbances were sparked by the killing of black men by
officers or the officers' acquittals on similar charges.
   If convicted on both counts, Lozano faces up to 60 years in
prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
