<FIRST>r a AM-DrugBarricades     11-15 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Barricades,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seek Permanent Barricades Around Dealers Haven</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police want to permanently barricade streets
surrounding a 12-block area in the San Fernando Valley plagued by
drive-through drug dealing and gang violence.
   ``This would make this area a vastly safer community for the
law-abiding people who live there,'' police Cmdr. Chet Spencer said
Tuesday. ``Why should they be subjected to the danger and the
shootings that go along with drug activity when there is something
that can be done about it?''
   The blockade plans include a guard station to be built and
staffed using donations by apartment owners in the Sepulveda-area
neighborhood. A meeting of residents and city officials is planned
for January to try to work out details.
   Sawhorse barricades were first erected there last week and
police increased patrols in the heavy drug-dealing area, limiting
entry to residents and their guests.
   The effort has been so successful at curbing crime that police
want to make it permanent, said Capt. Mark D. Stevens.
   The plan must first go to the City Council, which holds the
authority to close city streets to the general public, said John
Haggerty, an assistant city attorney.
   Councilman Joel Wachs, who represents the area about 15 miles
northwest of downtown, introduced a measure Tuesday that would keep
the temporary blockades in place as long as police see fit, said
Rick Kunz, a Wachs aide.
   The council will consider Wachs' measure next week. Originally,
the blockades were allowed by a 30-day permit obtained from the Los
Angeles Department of Transportation because of police claims that
there was an unusual danger to the public and property in the area.
   Police barricades on streets plagued by crime were first used in
California three years ago on a three-block stretch of road in
Northridge. Roadblocks have also curtailed drug dealing in the
Pico-Union area near downtown.
   In Miami Shores, Fla., police last year permanently barricaded
several streets to limit access to the suburb. They since have
reported a noticeable reduction in the number of burglaries.
