<FIRST>u w AM-MediaSurvey 1stLd-Writethru a0667 11-15 0972</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Media Survey, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Believes Political Bias Growing in News Media</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 8 grafs for grafs 3-9 pvs, Among network ... 11 percent,
using only figures for top two categories of believability for sake of
clarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increasingly, the American public has come to
believe there is political bias in news coverage, a new survey
finds.
   Despite that _ and a belief by 63 percent of the American public
that news organizations fuel controversies _ a favorable view of
those organizations is expressed by 82 percent for network TV news,
80 percent for local television news and 77 percent for daily
newspapers, said the Times Mirror survey released Wednesday.
   Among network big names, ABC news anchor Peter Jennings ``is now
the most highly regarded of the television correspondents,''
according to the poll. While his believability rating topped his
network rivals, it dropped five points from its 1985 level. CBS'
Dan Rather lost 10 believability points, ABC's Ted Koppel 9 points,
and NBC's Tom Brokaw 7 points.
   At the other end of the believability scale was Geraldo Rivera
whose rating dropped 48 points between the two surveys.
   The survey, conducted among members of the public, media,
government, academia and business, is the first work of the
Washington-based Times Mirror Center for The People &amp; The Press.
   ``Believability is down, there's just no question about it,''
said Michael Robinson, an associate professor of government at
Georgetown University and associate director of the survey. ``On
the average, news organizations lost nine points on a sale of 100
in terms of believability,'' he said.
   The survey's rating scale includes four categories ranging from
the top (you can believe all or most of what the person says) to
the bottom (believe almost nothing).
   Counting the percentages of respondents ranking news people or
organizations in the top two categories, the top of the list reads:
Jennings 85 percent, Cable News Network 84 percent, The Wall Street
Journal 83 percent, Brokaw 81 percent and Rather and Koppel 79
percent. At the bottom is Rivera at 26 percent.
   Other names and organizations include ABC's Diane Sawyer at 75
percent, The Associated Press 74 percent, ABC's Sam Donaldson 71,
USA Today 70, and columnist George Will 59.
   By comparison, Pope John Paul II gets a rating of 70 percent,
President Bush 63 percent, former President Reagan 47, Johnny
Carson 33, Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev 29 and businessman
Donald Trump 25.
   ``The most interesting case, bar none for me, is CNN,'' Robinson
said. ``CNN is the only news organization that has sustained no
decrease in believability.''
   The reason, he said, is that CNN concentrates on hard news. ``It
doesn't do a lot of interpretation, doesn't do a lot of
watchdoggery, it just shows hard news, particularly the sort of
news the public is most interested in.''
   The Los Angeles-based Times Mirror Co.'s holdings include the
Los Angeles Times, New York Newsday and the Baltimore Sun. It also
includes a cable television division.
   Pollsters said that since Times Mirror began its research
program five years ago, there has been a ``significant erosion of
public confidence in the press as an objective reporter of the news
and as an impartial observer of the political and social scene.''
   In 1985, 53 percent of the American public believed news media
favored one side in dealing with social and political issues. That
percentage remained in the 50s in five subsequent surveys and rose
to 68 percent in the current one. Similarly those who believe news
organizations ``deal fairly with all sides'' dropped from 34
percent to 28 percent.
   When the press respondents were asked whether news organizations
merely report the news or fuel controversies by their coverage, 46
percent opted for the first and 49 percent for the second. ``Drive
controversy'' also got the nod from 75 percent of the academics, 80
percent of business leaders and 77 percent of government leaders.
   Not surprisingly, members of the news media _ 81 percent _ said
they cover stories about the personal and ethical behavior of
politicians very or fairly responsibly. Only 68 percent of the
general public and 60 percent of government leaders agreed.
   The percentage of people who think news organizations get their
facts straight rose to 54 percent from a low of 40 percent a year
ago. And there was a slight increase in the percentage of those who
believe the press respects people's privacy _ from 14 percent last
year to 23 percent.
   The survey found that the media consistently overstate interest
in news stories. In eight of nine stories cited, the media thought
the public was more interested than the public said it was.
   The greatest overstatements of public interest were on stories
about Pete Rose, the Mike Tyson-Robin Givens divorce and former
House Speaker Jim Wright, the survey said. News about the scandal
at the Department of Housing and Urban Development was the only
instance in which the press correctly gauged the very low level of
public interest.
   Sixty-four percent of the members of the public surveyed said
they read a newspaper nearly every day, while 67 percent said they
regularly watched a network news show.
   A total of 508 media telephone interviews were conducted Aug.
3-Sept. 29, while 275 interviews were conducted with leaders in
business, government and academia Aug. 3-Oct. 6.
   Nearly 100 interviews were conducted with government leaders,
including 38 members of Congress, 12 senaors, nine governors, 21
mayors and 16 senior Bush administration officials. There were 100
interviews with presidents and journalism deans at major colleges
and universities.
   The Gallup Organization conducted a telephone survey of 1,507
adult members of the public Aug. 9-28.
   The margin of error ranged from 3 percentage points for the
largest sample to 11 percentage points for the smallest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
