<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSFees     11-15 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Fees,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say UCLA Shouldn't Charge Candidates for Drug Testing Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS activists say UCLA Medical Center was
trying to profit from a government-subsidized research program by
charging patients for AIDS drug studies in which participation is
free around the country.
   ``What UCLA is doing is wrong,'' said Dr. Neil Schram, former
chairman of the Los Angeles City-County AIDS Task Force. ``They are
using this study as a way to make money and in my opinion that is
inappropriate.
   ``Experimental drug treatment programs are federally funded and
they are supposed to be free.''
   Critics claim the medical school, part of the University of
California, Los Angeles, charged patients a $260 consultation fee
to determine their eligibility for the study.
   UCLA's AIDS Clinical Trials unit is one of 46 research
facilities nationwide participating in the study conducted by the
National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases to examine
the effects of experimental AIDS drugs such as AZT and DDI.
   Federal health officials said research groups have the option of
charging fees, but believe that UCLA is the only program that does.
   ``I've never encountered it before,'' said Dr. Daniel Hoth,
director of the AIDS program for NIAID.
   Dr. David Hardy, co-investigator of the clinical trial group at
UCLA's AIDS Research Center, said the program charges fees because
the screenings are part of a larger evaluation designed to
determine options in treatment.
   ``The time that we spend with someone in the clinic is not
specifically for participation in the study,'' he said. ``We
discuss much, much more than just the study, such as why they might
want to continue taking AZT or why they can't, and we consider it a
medical consultation.''
   He added that after candidates are chosen, treatment is free.
   To be eligible for the program, a patient must test positive for
the AIDS virus and never have been treated with DDI. The program is
composed of three separate studies to determine the effectiveness
of DDI, in comparison to AZT.
   DDI, or dideoxyinosine, and AZT, now known formally as
zidovudine, both inhibit replication of the AIDS virus.
   AIDS activists claim the program should be free because patients
put their health at risk by taking an experimental drug. They also
claim the fee excludes poor patients who could benefit.
   ``There is already a problem with minorities and poor people
getting experimental drug treatments and this will make it that
more difficult to get access to those drugs,'' said Mark
Kostopoulos, a spokesman for AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
