<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessProtest     11-15 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Protest,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Protesters Arrested in Boston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homeless protesters who had taken over an ornate
room of the Statehouse were arrested Wednesday shortly after saying
they would not be moved until $700,000 in budget cuts were restored
to the winter shelter program.
   The vigil, held in memory of one of their own who died after
spending a night on Boston Common last winter, ended with the
arrest of 20 people about an hour after it began.
   Leroy Van Valkenburg and more than 100 others moved into Nurses
Hall promising, ``I will not move.''
   All of those arrested were charged with disorderly conduct, said
Capitol Police Officer Kathleen Stapleton.
   Rich Kramer, an organizer, said bail was set at $25, and a $500
bail fund had been established to benefit any homeless people who
were arrested.
   Van Valkenburg, 51, has lived on the streets for 10 years. He's
survived 35-below zero nights on Boston Common, even after
suffering three heart attacks and a stroke.
   The event was held in memory of Tim Flynn, 32, a friend of Van
Valkenburg's who died last winter.
   Organizers of the event said the state provided $2.2 million to
make sure the homeless were sheltered last winter. But because of
the state's worsening fiscal status, only $1.5 million is available
this year.
   ``If the state can't provide for rescue, than we'll have to take
the space and make it available,'' said Jim Stewart, an activist
from Cambridge.
   Joe Landolfi, a spokesman for the office of Human Services, said
that regardless of the budget crunch,``nobody's going to be out on
the streets due to a lack of beds.''
   Van Valkenburg said he worked as a cook at two hotels for 20
years until 10 years ago when he was disabled. In addition to two
heart attacks, he suffered a stroke that left him partially
disabled and he relies on a brace to walk.
   Van Valkenburg receives about $100 a week in disability payments
from the state, but he can't accumulate enough to pay advance rent
and security for a room and still buy food.
   He relies on shelters in the cold months.
   The state's winter care program is designed to provide emergency
shelter during the colder months, according to Madeline Carhart of
the Executive Office of Human Services.
   But with funding down $700,000 from last year, Stewart and
Harris predict 200 fewer people will be able to find housing.
</TEXT>
