<FIRST>u w AM-US-EasternEurope     11-15 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Eastern Europe,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Not Pushing Capitalism On Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said Wednesday the United
States regards captialism as the best formula for curing the
economic problems of Eastern Europe but said ``we have not tried to
dictate it for any of these countries.''
   The statement came after Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
said the reforms in Eastern Europe do not spell the demise of
socialism and denounced calls for ``exporting capitalism'' to the
Soviet bloc.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater noted that the United
States has joined other Western countries in providing aid to
Poland and Hungary as they try to reform their economies into a
free-market system. ``But we don't think that's a conflict with the
concerns raised by President Gorbachev,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said President Bush views the United States'
free-market system ``as the pride of the world and as a good way to
reform the economic problems that they are facing. We certainly are
proud of the capitalist system and the rewards that it has offered.
   ``We hold it up as an example to all, but we have not tried to
dictate it for any of these countries,'' Fitzwater said.
   He added, ``We have no apologies or concern with anything that
we've done at this point.''
   Bush and Gorbachev will meet for a summit Dec. 2-3 on ships in
the Mediterranean off the coast of Malta. Fitzwater confirmed that
Bush is considering a stop in Brussels, Belgium, on the way home to
brief NATO allies on the talks.
   Fitzwater said he expected Bush and Gorbachev to make a
commitment to progress on reducing strategic nuclear stockpiles and
conventional arms in Europe. He stressed, however, that there would
be no major agreements, saying, ``We will not be counting throw
weights.''
   The press secretary acknowledged that the United States and
Soviet Union are trying to manipulate public expectations of the
summit's outcome.
   ``The Soviets ... have a tendency in past summits ... to build
expectations before a summit, and we have a tendency to play them
down,'' he said. ``I suspect the reality is somewhere in the
middle. But I would urge you to discount theirs a little bit on the
top side.''
   Fitzwater also said that despite prodding from Democrats, there
is ``no real consideration'' being given to the idea of Bush going
to the Berlin Wall to salute its opening.
</TEXT>
