<FIRST>u w AM-Thornburgh-Security     11-15 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Security,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General's Office Gets Bullet-Proof Windows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New windows with thick bullet-proof glass were
installed in Attorney General Dick Thornburgh's office last week as
part of efforts to tighten his security, officials said Wednesday.
   The replacement of existing windows with bullet-proof glass,
completed last week, cost $73,000, the department said.
   Security for the attorney general has been noticeably tighter
since Colombia's crackdown on drug lords, which prompted threats
from cocaine traffickers to kill U.S. officials.
   The attorney general now travels in an armor-plated limousine
that cost more than $100,000.
   Thornburgh no longer uses the public entrance to his office at
the Justice Department, leaving instead by a variety of routes.
   The handful of FBI agents in Thornburgh's security detail have
recently been spotted carrying gun cases, indicated they are now
armed with high-powered weapons.
</TEXT>
