<FIRST>r i AM-NorthernIreland     11-15 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Bomb Blows Up Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb ripped through a car
traveling on a rural highway in County Tyrone Wednesday, killing
the driver, police said.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility in a statement
issued to local media and alleged that the victim, a businessman,
worked for the British province's security forces.
   Police denied he had any connection with the security forces.
   The man, whose name was not released, was driving on the highway
between Dungannon and Ballygawley, about 8 miles from the
province's border with the Irish Republic, when a 2-pound bomb
hidden under the car detonated, a police spokesman said.
   The explosion blew the roof off the car, which burst into
flames, the spokesman said. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The IRA is fighting to drive the British out of Northern Ireland
and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the overwhelmingly
Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
   Earlier, several hundred Protestant demonstrators marked the
fourth anniversary of the signing of the Anglo-Irish agreement by
linking hands along main roads in different parts of the province.
Organizers had predicted a turnout of 300,000 people.
   ``I recognize that the imaginative scheme did not capture the
imagination of the Ulster people,'' said an organizer, the Rev.
Martin Smyth, a legislator in the British Parliament.
   Organizers blamed the low turnout partly on the absence of two
Protestant leaders, the Rev. Ian Paisley who is visiting Australia
and James Molyneaux who was lobbying fellow British legislators in
London.
   The 1985 agreement between Britain and Ireland gave the Irish
government a consultative role in the affairs of Northern Ireland
for the first time.
   It set up a permanent secretariat of British and Irish civil
servants in Belfast to deal with the grievances the Catholic
minority claim they suffer under the Protestant majority.
   The agreement also pledged cooperation between the two countries
on security measures along their common border.
</TEXT>
