<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Iraq     11-15 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Iraq,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Ministers Meet on Egyptian Exodus from Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cabinet ministers made plans Wednesday for
bringing order to the return of about 3,000 Egyptian workers a day
from Iraq and an official said they leaving for economic reasons,
not because of maltreatment.
   In Baghdad, President Saddam Hussein of Iraq called a meeting of
Egyptian residents and complained about Cairo newspaper reports
that the workers were being mistreated.
   He promised to investigate any complaints, but discounted claims
that many Egyptians have been killed maliciously in Iraq. He said
they died naturally or from violence in numbers understandable in a
group of about 2 million people.
   Rumors circulated Wednesday among diplomats in Cairo that Nabil
Najm, the Iraqi ambassador, had received a death threat. Embassy
spokesman Daoud Farhan denied the reports and said the ambassador
was not in Egypt.
   Ahmed Radwan, secretary-general of President Hosni Mubarak's
cabinet, said the ministers were told the main reason Egyptians
were returning was that new fiscal rules in Iraq reduced the amount
of money alien workers could send home.
   He said Ibrahim Ouf, Egyptian ambassador in Baghdad, told the
ministers a manpower surplus had resulted from Iraq's
demobilization after the truce agreement of August 1988 in the
8-year-old war with Iran.
   Ouf said Iraqi employers were dismissing Egyptians and giving
their jobs to former Iraqi soldiers, according to Radwan.
   The Cabinet official did not address reports by the newspaper
Al-Akhbar that more than 100 Egyptian corpses were returned from
Iraq in October, compared to an average of two or three in other
months.
   He did say, however, that Ouf told the ministers Iraqi
authorities were prepared to present complete files on Egyptians
who die in Iraq.
   Al-Akhbar has reported that Iraqi death certificates attributed
most of the Egyptian deaths to violent causes.
   On Wednesday, it said five bodies of Egyptian men aged 23-40
arrived at the Cairo airport the day before with documents
indicating two died of skull fractures, one of burns and one of
heart failure. Al-Akhbar said the cause of the fifth death was not
determined.
   Radwan's comments were distributed by the official Middle East
News Agency. He said the ministerial group was headed by Prime
Minister Atef Sedki and including the foreign, finance, labor,
immigration, supplies and administrative affairs ministers, the
head of the Civil Aviation Authority and Ambassador Ouf.
   Tens of thousands of Egyptians are said to be awaiting
transportation from Iraq. The departures began soon after Iraq
issued new regulations Oct. 1 on sending money home.
   Sedki and Taha Yassin Ramadan, deputy prime minister, are to
discuss the situation Saturday in Cairo.
   Authorities at Cairo airport said 25,000-27,000 Egyptian workers
arrived past week on Egyptian and Iraqi airliners.
   They said both airlines had increased their number of flights to
handle the traffic.
</TEXT>
