<FIRST>r w AM-Archives-Morris     11-15 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Archives-Morris,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Congressmen Question Archives-Cigarette Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of Congress on Wednesday called
for investigation of an agreement between a cigarette manufacturer
and the National Archives to sponsor a campaign commemorating the
200th anniversary of the Bill of Rights.
   ``Philip Morris has bought the exclusive rights to the
Constitution which we entrusted to the National Archives, for the
modern equivalent of 30 pieces of silver or $600,000,'' said Rep.
Thomas A. Luken, in a statement announcing a congressional hearing
on Thursday.
   The Ohio Democrat heads the House subcommittee on transportation
and hazardous materials, which has jurisdictin over advertising and
the Federal Trade Commission.
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., asked the General Accounting Office,
the investigative arm of Congress, to look into the matter.
   The Health Research Group, a consumer organization, wrote Sen.
Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., last week asking Congress to revoke the
agreement. Bingaman has written Don Wilson, the archivist of the
United States, questioning how and why the agreement was made.
   The two-year agreement, signed in August, makes Philip Morris
Companies, Inc., the nation's largest cigarette maker, a part of
the official National Archives bicentennial celebration of the Bill
of Rights.
   In a ``memorandum of understanding'' Philip Morris agreed to
donate $600,000 to the Archives trust fund in exchange for being
allowed to publish or broadcast announcements and promotional
materials commemorating the bicentennial and referring to the
Archives.
   Critics have questioned whether the broadcast announcements
constitute cigarette advertisements on radio and television, which
was banned by the federal government in 1971.
   ``The Philip Morris ads are running on television and do not
contain any health warning and apparently are a fragrant violation
of the law prohibiting such video commercials,'' said Luken.
   Guy L. Smith, Philip Morris' vice president of corporate
affairs, said he didn't believe the company's announcements
violated the advertising ban since ``there is no cigarette called
Philip Morris.''
   ``In the same week that the Berlin Wall is being torn down that
people in this country are being criticized for celebrating the
Bill of Rights is very strange,'' Smith added in a reference to
recent events in East Germany.
   The company plans to continue the campaign and send a
representative to testify at Thursday's hearing, he said.
   Critics also have questioned corporate sponsorship of Archives
programs.
   Sidney Wolfe, director of the Health Research Group, criticized
the ``commercialization of space in the building which houses the
symbols of our nation.''
   Congress not only permitted the agency to accept tax-exempt
donations to its trust fund but also specifically ``encouraged it
to do so in order to enhance it's archival and outreach
activities,'' said Susan Cooper, spokeswoman for the Archives.
   While this the first large corporate donation to the Archives
trust fund, Cooper said, it is not the first cooperative effort
with private industry.
   In addition, she said Philip Morris' sponsorship of an exhibit
in the Archives building is no different than when other companies
underwrote receptions to celebrate the bicentenial of the
Constitution or when Philip Morris itself sponsored exhibits at the
National Art Gallery.
</TEXT>
