<FIRST>u a AM-NavyStand-down     11-15 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Stand-down,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantic Fleet Prepares for Two-day Safety Stand-down</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NK2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy's top safety officer on Wednesday
compared a two-day safety stand-down to a timeout in an athletic
contest called to ``review the game plan and get back to the
basics.''
   The exercise is a useful tool, said Capt. Ferguson Norton, chief
of the Naval Safety Center. The stand-down ordered Tuesday is the
most widespread in memory, he said.
   It was ordered after a rash of 10 accidents in the last three
weeks killed 10 people and injured 71.
   All Navy units will spend 48 of 72 hours this week reviewing
procedures and training, looking at the work environment, and
reminding all hands of safety measures, according to the stand-down
ordered by Secretary of the Navy H. Lawrence Garrett III and Adm.
Carlisle A.H. Trost, chief of naval operations.
   ``A timeout also can be called to halt the momentum of the
opponent, ... in this case, the string of mishaps,'' Norton said at
a news conference.
   The safety center analyzes all Navy accidents worldwide in an
attempt to prevent further problems.
   ``Safety is the product of sound operating procedures and good
training,'' Norton said.
   ``We want to leave no stone unturned to ensure that safety is
uppermost in the minds of all hands, at all times,'' said Lt. Cmdr.
Steve Burnett, a spokesman for the Atlantic Fleet.
   Norton said the Navy's record of safety has been steadily
improving over recent years.
   There were 118 major problems during operations in 1984. That
figure has dropped to 69 so far this year, according to Navy
figures.
   However, the number of fatalities for 1984 was 64; 102 sailors
have been killed so far this year, including 47 in the April 19th
gun turret explosion aboard the battleship USS Iowa.
   Norton said the center's analysis found no clear links between
accidents of the last three weeks. He also said there was no
indication that Pentagon budget cuts had any effect on accidents.
   ``We're got a tough business. ... We're expected to be able to
go tomorrow anywhere in the world and be an instrument of national
policy. That's what the government expects and that's what the
American people expect,'' Norton said.
   Meanwhile, personnel at the Norfolk Naval Station spent the day
preparing for the stand-down.
   ``Most of the units did not find out about the stand-down until
late yesterday. The 72-hour window gives them time to plan the
rotations and wind down any missions they are on,'' Burnett said.
   Burnett said Atlantic Fleet ships at sea will not be called home
for the safety drill.
   ``Ships at sea will stand-down at sea. Those on shore will do
their stand-down there.''
   The most serious of the recent accidents occurred Oct. 29 when a
jet pilot making his first landing on an aircraft carrier crashed
into the USS Lexington in the Gulf of Mexico. he pilot and four
others were killed.
   On Monday, the destroyer USS Kinkaid and a freighter collided in
the Malacca Strait killing one Navy crewman, injuring five, and
starting fires on both vessels.
   Last Thursday, a Navy reserve pilot flying an A-7E jet crashed
into an apartment complex in Smyrna, Ga., killing two civilians and
injuring two others, including himself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
