<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Soviets     11-15 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Soviets,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Passes 1st Joint US-Soviet `Peace and Security' Resolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly on Wednesday passed
an unprecedented joint U.S.-Soviet resolution urging nations to
settle conflicts peacefully and respect human rights.
   Although the resolution passed unanimously, Japan and Brazil
expressed unease over whether the superpowers might use their new
spirit of cooperation to stifle debate on issues not high on their
agenda.
   Japan's Ambassador Hideo Kagami said: ``Any part of this
resolution must not be interpreted to justify undue politicization
of issues of the United Nations under the name of peace and
security.''
   Brazil's Ambassador Paulo Nogueira-Batista pointed out that the
resolution stressed the role of the Security Council and General
Assembly, but failed to mention the Economic and Social Council,
which sets policy on social matters such as the environment, AIDS,
and the anti-drug fight.
   Brazil and Japan both joined in the consensus on the resolution,
however.
   The resolution urges all nations to obey the U.N. Charter and
use U.N. bodies to settle disputes, but offers no specific
proposals to end conflicts in Central America, Afghanistan,
Cambodia or elsewhere.
   It calls on all nations to ``respect the principles of sovereign
equality, political independence and territorial integrity of
states, and non-intervention in foreign affairs.''
   It also calls on nations to ``refrain from the threat or use of
force inconsistent with the charter,'' which permits only
self-defense, and to ``peacefully settle disputes.''
   Nations should ``adhere to the principles of equal rights and
self-determination of peoples, respect for human rights and
fundamental freedoms, cooperation among states.''
   General Assembly resolutions have no binding effect on nations,
but the superpowers have the ability to persuade their allies to
resolve disputes peacefully when they wish.
   Earlier this month, at a joint U.S.-Soviet news conference,
Assistant Secretary of State John Bolton stressed that the
resolution puts an end to the superpower rivalry that prevailed
during the Cold War years.
   ``Today, it is an end to confrontation,'' said his Soviet
counterpart, Vladimir Petrovsky.
</TEXT>
