<DOCNO> AP891115-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Pay-Ethics-Glance     11-15 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pay-Ethics-Glance,640</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of major provisions in the
pay raise and ethics reform package announced by House leaders on
Wednesday. The provision generally would apply to all branches of
government except the Senate, which is expected to consider a
separate version for itself before Congress adjourns for
Thanksgiving.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PAY</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The plan envisions top government pay scales increasing at least
35 percent in the next 13{ months.
   House members, federal judges and top executive branch officials
would receive an initial 7.9 percent pay raise by Jan. 1, a ``catch
up'' for two years without a cost-of-living adjustment or COLA.
   On Jan. 1, 1991, the same officials would receive a 25 percent
increase in pay, on top of whatever government-wide COLA takes
effect at that time. At a minimum, assuming no COLA in 1991, the
salary of rank-and-file House members would go to $120,700.
Assuming a COLA of about 3 percent, salaries would be about
$124,400 _ 39 percent above current levels.
   After that, annual pay adjustments of up to 5 percent would be
made automatically based on the government's index of
private-sector wages and salaries.
   The package would abolish the current federal pay commission
which recommends top government salaries and replace it with a new
11-member Citizens Commission.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>OUTSIDE INCOME</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   House members, officers and employees, and other top executive
and judicial officials would be barred from accepting honoraria, or
speaking fees, beginning in 1991. For House members, current rules
limit such fees to 30 percent of salary; for 1990, total
permissible outside income for House members would be frozen at the
1989 level.
   Once the ban takes effect, payments for speeches which may be
given to charity would have to be made directly to the charity and
could not exceed $2,000, and could not go to any charity from which
the official or a relative receives a financial benefit. However,
the House would not make public the name of the charity, as it does
now; only the name of the donor.
   Income earned outside the House by members and top staff would
be limited to 15 percent of congressional salary beginning in 1991.
Officials could not receive directors fees, legal fees or other
income for professional services. Book royalties would be exempt
from the limits, but only if they are from established publishers
and are ``usual and customary.''
   Both the limit on outside income and the honoraria ban would be
lifted if the pay raise is repealed.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>GIFTS AND TRAVEL</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Members and staff could not receive gifts from any person,
outside of family, totaling more than $200 a year beginning Jan. 1,
1990. Most meals and gifts under $75 would not be counted in the
total. Currently, members are barred from receiving more than $100
a year in gifts from anyone with a ``direct interest in
legislation.'' Privately paid speaking trips would be limited to
four days for domestic travel and seven days for foreign travel.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>ETHICS COMMITTEE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The bipartisan House panel would be expanded from 12 to 14
members and would separate its investigative and trial functions.
If a House member is being investigated, the panel would divide
into two groups. One would serve in effect as a grand jury and the
other as the trial jury.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>EXCESS CAMPAIGN FUNDS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   House members who were in office in 1980 and now are allowed to
keep leftover campaign contributions when they retire would see
that privilege abolished in 1993.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More detail would be required in the reporting of privately
funded travel for lawmakers, and new categories of value would be
created on the upper end of the scale for reporting of assets,
liabilities and transactions. Currently, members can report their
most valuable assets in the category of ``$250,000 and above.''
Three new categories would be created for amounts up to $1 million.
The value of assets in blind trusts would have to be reported for
the first time, and tighter restrictions would be placed on who can
be trustee.
</TEXT>
