<SECOND>AM-Bush-Suits,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Shops For Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush went shopping Wednesday night,
stopping traffic on a busy downtown street while he bought two
suits at a men's store.
   The half-hour shopping expedition at the tail end of the evening
rush hour blocked traffic on L Street, one of the capital's main
thoroughfares, as Bush browsed in private at the Arthur A. Adler
shop.
   He emerged after the fitting with a wave for a crowd of 200
people who had gathered at a nearby street corner. He told
reporters later that he had purchased two suits but offered no
description.
   Bush has shopped before at Adler's, but not as president and not
at this particular store, a new location that opened in April.
   John Adler, the owner and president, said, ``We're primarily a
gentlemen's clothing store,'' with suits in ``very classic,
traditional'' style selling from $400 to $1,000.
   Bush shopped at Adler's old location on Connecticut Avenue as
vice president and also bought a tuxedo there that he wore to his
inaugural balls last Jan. 20.
   The president apparently wanted to visit the store in person.
Asked why he had not simply taken some suits to the White House for
Bush to try on, Adler said he has done that before.
</TEXT>
