<FIRST>r w AM-MarketReform-Breeden     11-15 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Market Reform-Breeden,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Chief Pushing Market Reform Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A longer version is running on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman
Richard C. Breeden said Wednesday that he supports pending new
market regulation legislation even though it doesn't ban program
trading.
   Breeden told a group of reporters at SEC headquarters that the
controversial, computer-driven trading strategy is only a symptom
of bigger market problems.
   ``I think we need a close look at the whole issue of volatility
and the factors that help produce it and the elements that may be
at work. I'd like to make sure that before we treat only the
symptom that we also are aware of what the disease is,'' he said.
   Critics of program trading, in which enormous blocks of stocks
are bought or sold in a wink of an eye through computer-driven
entry of buy and sell orders, say it can lead to excessive
volatility _ sharp price rises and drops _ which in turn, scares
small investors out of the market.
   And that, say the critics, makes it hard for U.S. companies to
sell securities and raise capital.
   Breeden said he supported recently amended legislation pending
before the House Energy and Commerce Committee that would allow the
SEC to curtail trading practices found to be ``manipulative or
abusive.''
   ``I don't think it gives us the authority to ban program trading
per se,'' Breeden said of the Securities Markets Stabilization Act
of 1989. ``The thrust of this section is not to ban program trading
as one practice in the marketplace. But what it does allow us to do
is to specify specific harmful practices, including those
associated with program trading.''
   If the bill was passed, said Breeden, the SEC could then
``define rules that would bar specific practices that we deem to be
harmful and contributing to excessive volatility and those
practices could include program trading.''
   Originally the bill would have allowed the SEC to intervene when
it considered trading practices to be ``disruptive,'' but members
of the telecommunications and finance subcomitee argued that the
word was too vague.
   In a letter to the subcommittee, Robert R. Glauber, an
undersecretary of the Treasury argued the word ``is itself
disruptive.''
   Glauber wrote that it could ``derail the chances for final
passage of other important provisions included in this
legislation.''
   The bill must be passed by the Energy and Commerce Committee
before going to the House floor. Congressional leaders have said
they want to adjourn for the holidays next week.
   A similar bill is slated to be considered by the Seanate Banking
Committee Thursday.
</TEXT>
