<HEAD>Vice Principal Shot, Student Taken Into Custody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vice principal of a junior high
school was shot once in the back in a school parking lot Wednesday
and a 13-year-old boy was taken into custody, police said.
   Andy Chambers, 44, was in surgery at Arlington Memorial Hospital
to remove a bullet lodged in his abdomen, said hospital spokeswoman
Carlene Ness.
   ``He is alert and it doesn't appear to be life-threatening,''
Ms. Ness said. ``They're going in to do exploratory surgery now and
probably remove the bullet.''
   Chambers was shot once in the back at a Workman Junior High
School parking lot at about 3:45 p.m. as students and teachers were
leaving for the day, said Dee Anderson, spokesman for the Arlington
Police Department.
   Several teachers and students witnessed the shooting, he said.
   The 13-year-old boy, who was not identified because of his age,
was taken to the Tarrant County Juvenile Detention Center for
arraignment.
   A .22 caliber pistol was found in a ditch near the school
parking lot, where the shooting took place, Anderson said.
   Chambers did not see who shot him, but said he had not been
involved in any recent confrontations with students, Anderson said.
