<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--ShipRescue     11-15 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Ship Rescue,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crew Rescued From Container Ship That Aground in Bering Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a Greek container ship that
ran aground on St. Matthew Island was rescued Wednesday, and the
accident left a 12-mile long slick of fuel oil in the Bering Sea,
the Coast Guard reported.
   The ship's tanks held 294,000 gallons of a diesel fuel-oil
mixture, but officials were unsure how much of that had leaked,
Coast Guard spokesman Greg Robinson said from Juneau.
   Coast Guard investigators planned to fly over the slick at dawn
Thursday to assess what cleanup measures, if any, are needed.
   The 27 crew members were transferred from the grounded Milos
Reefer to a nearby Polish ship, Robinson said.
   The 485-foot refrigerated fish-carrier ran aground Tuesday night
and was taking on water. No injuries were reported and the ship had
no cargo.
