<FIRST>r a AM-PesticidePoisoning     11-15 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pesticide Poisoning,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Migrant Workers Fall Ill From Pesticide Exposure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUSKIN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 migrant farmworkers were
treated for vomiting, dizziness and heart and breathing problems
Wednesday after they were exposed to a toxic pesticide in a
cauliflower field, officials said.
   Morning workers at Goodson Farms began falling ill as soon as
they entered a 16-acre field which had been sprayed the previous
afternoon with the pesticide phosdrin, farm employees said.
   ``This is a pesticide we use all the time. As soon as it's dry,
it's safe to go in there,'' said farm manager Henry Almond. ``But
this morning, one got sick and pretty soon they all started getting
sick.''
   Phosdrin is a common, though highly toxic, pesticide sprayed on
a wide variety of agricultural crops to control worms. The label
warns that fields sprayed with it should not be entered without
protective clothing for at least 48 hours, said Tasha Brew, a
pesticide education specialist at the University of Florida's
cooperative extension service.
   ``Sometimes we go in about an hour after spraying, so long as
it's dry,'' Almond said. ``This didn't stop us. We got people back
out there now.''
   The workers wore protective boots and gloves to protect them
from any pesticide residue, he said.
   Crew managers at the farm began taking the first workers to a
rural clinic, and later ambulances were dispatched to bring in more.
   ``The pesticide enters through the skin, so we first had to
strip their clothes off, shower them and wrap them in sheets,''
said Judy Brown, administrator at the Ruskin Migrant Health Center.
``They were covered with it.''
   Most of the workers suffered from vomiting, dizziness and
blurred vision, with a handful showing breathing and heartbeat
problems, said Ms. Brown, adding that a total of 77 had come
through the clinic by late afternoon.
   Four patients were admitted to South Bay Hospital in nearby Sun
City with depressed heartbeats and breathing problems, said
hospital spokeswoman Oona Lewis.
   About 25 others were treated and released at Tampa General
Hospital, with the rest treated at the clinic, officials said.
   Almond said the workers were in the fields tying leaves around
the cauliflower to keep the fleshy part of the plants from
yellowing. The plants were scheduled to be harvested in about eight
days.
</TEXT>
