<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages 3rdLd-Writethru a0795 11-15 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0795,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says It Kidnapped American Woman, Two West Germans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-12, `Ms. Fahrend's...' with 7 grafs to UPDATE with
mother's comments. Pick up 13th pvs, ``She traveled...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously unknown group said Wednesday
it had kidnapped an American woman and two naturalized West Germans
_ a man born in Lebanon and his 7-year-old son.
   The claim was made in a typewritten statement, in Arabic, for a
group calling itself The Organization of Just Revenge. The
statement was delivered to a Western news agency with photocopies
of the passports and visas of the three people.
   It identified the American as Deborah Fahrend, 54, of San
Francisco, and described her as a publisher-journalist. The two
others were identified as Mounir Shamseddin Sami, 39, born in
Lebanon, and his son, Danjel, born in Berlin.
   ``The Organization of Just Revenge announces its responsibility
for kidnapping the West German Mounir Sami (born in Lebanon) and
his son Danjel Sami and American publisher-journalist Deborah
Fahrend in Beirut for their activities in Lebanon,'' it said.
   No demands were made in the poorly typed statement, which gave
no details and did not say when the abduction occurred. The
kidnapping could not be confirmed.
   Ms. Fahrend would be the first American woman abducted in
Lebanon, and one of only a few women of any nationality.
   Ms. Fahrend's mother, Margaret Brooks of Davis, Calif., said
that in a letter she received last week her daughter said she was
going to Beirut with someone named Mounir and wrote: ``I'm going to
use Mounir's connections to the hilt,'' referring to diplomatic
friends he had in Lebanon. ``It seems to me to me a chance in a
lifetime.''
   Ms. Brooks said her daughter referred to Mounir as her
``therapist and really good friend.''
   Ms. Fahrend's sister, Emily Rowe, 59, also of Davis, said in an
interview that her sister chose the name Fahrend, which means
traveling or itinerant in German, as a pen name while living in
India several years ago.
   ``She tackles life pretty much head-on,'' Ms. Rowe said. ``She
would be unaware of danger in thinking of going to Lebanon, instead
thinking of the opportunities for professional advancement.''
   She described the family's reaction as ``a state of shock.''
   Jane McCullough, a friend of Ms. Fahrend in San Geronimo, a town
20 miles north of San Francisco where she is said to have lived
until 1987, said they last met when her friend visited in June.
   She said the description ``publisher-journalist'' surprised her.
She said Ms. Fahrend, who she indicated was divorced and had two
daughters, was a registered nurse and sometime poet.
   ``She traveled extensively and was a poet _ wrote poetry about
the places she visited,'' Ms. McCullough said.
   A State Department official in Washington, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said the department had no information on Ms. Fahrend
and ``we're trying to find out if she had a waiver on her
passport.''
   Americans are prohibited from traveling to Lebanon without such
a waiver of the rules.
   The documents showed one-entry visas issued for Ms. Fahrend and
the two Germans by Consul Michelene Baz at the Lebanese Embassy in
Nicosia, Cyprus, on Nov. 1.
   Attempts to reach Ms. Baz on Wednesday night were unsuccessful.
Other Lebanese diplomatic sources in Nicosia said further details
about the visa applications would be available Thursday morning.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman in Cyprus said he had no information on
the kidnappings. The American Embassy in Beirut has been closed
since Sept. 22.
   The documents also showed entry stamps by the Lebanese security
department at the Christian port of Jounieh north of Beirut, dated
Nov. 3, an indication the three traveled from Cyprus to Lebanon
together by sea.
   No information was available on whether they remained in the
Christian sector or crossed to Moslem west Beirut before their
abduction.
   The West German Embassy in Beirut said it had no knowledge of
the abduction until the statement was released after nightfall.
   If the kidnapping is confirmed, Ms. Fahrend would be the only
Western woman now held captive in Lebanon, where women have been
kidnapped only rarely.
   One was Danielle Perez, daughter of French hostage Marcel
Carton, who was kidnapped with her father in 1985 by Islamic Jihad,
a Shiite Moslem group loyal to Iran, and released 12 hours later.
Carton was held more than three years later.
   Ms. Fahrend's father was identified in the visa photocopy as
Frederick Brooks and her mother as Margaret Brooks. Her passport
was issued in San Francisco Oct. 15, 1984.
   Eighteen other foreigners are held in Lebanon, including eight
Americans. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, 42, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Most of the hostages are believed held by pro-Iranian factions.
</TEXT>
