<FIRST>r a AM-OperationPunchout     11-15 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Operation Punchout,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Air Force Cop Pleads Guilty In Military Thefts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILL AIR FORCE BASE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force security policeman
pleaded guilty Wednesday to stealing more than $3,900 in military
supplies from a base where two other security men pilfered F-16 jet
engines.
   Hill Air Force Base Staff Sgt. Timothy M. Eastabrook was to
begin his court-martial Wednesday, but instead entered the plea as
part of an apparent plea-bargain.
   Eastabrook was to have been the first man to face general
court-martial as a result of ``Operation Punchout,'' a 2{-year
undercover investigation of military thefts from bases in the West
and Southwest.
   Fourteen Hill personnel have been charged to date, with seven
facing military courts-martial and seven indicted by a federal
grand jury.
   Two other Hill security policemen have pleaded guilty to
stealing three F-16 jet engines and selling them to undercover
agents. They await sentencing in U.S. District Court.
   The two charges against Eastabrook, 28, alleged that between
October 1986 and April he stole almost 100 items and illegally sold
them to Military Surplus Brokers, an FBI front in Roy.
   In the plea-bargain, Eastabrook pleaded guilty to both charges,
but to stealing slightly more than $3,900 rather than the $5,304 he
originally had been charged with. The remaining goods were
apparently items he had been issued, officials said.
   Lawyers on both sides said military justice rules prevented them
from discussing the plea-bargain.
   Three other Hill enlisted men have gone through special
courts-martial on charges they illegally sold military supplies.
Two were acquitted and one was found guilty, demoted and sentenced
to a month in jail.
   On Tuesday, another Hill security policeman pleaded guilty to
three counts of theft of government property. Airman 1st Class
Patrick John Oltmanns, 21, from Moose Lake, Minn., is scheduled to
stand trial Jan. 8.
   Oltmanns is charged with stealing aircraft aviation instruments,
military gear and miscellaneous clothing items between July 1988
and February 1989.
</TEXT>
