<FIRST>r a AM-UnionvsUnion     11-15 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Union vs Union,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>AFSCME Is Target of Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's largest public employee
union was picketed Wednesday by its own field organizers, who went
on strike after contract negotiations broke down late Tuesday.
   The 10-member United Staff Union of Iowa called the strike
against Council 61 of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees after mediation failed to produce a new
contract.
   ``We feel it's in the best interests of both parties to resolve
it as soon as possible,'' said Dan Varner, an AFSCME field worker
on the picket line.
   United Staff Union is seven AFSCME field workers and three
AFSCME clerical workers. On Wednesday, they carried signs outside
Council 61 headquarters in Des Moines while negotiations continued
inside.
   Lynda Coleman, president of United Staff Union, said the union
and AFSCME officials have agreed on a 2.5 percent wage increase,
but that AFSCME wants the raise to take effect Jan. 1.
   United Staff wants the increase retroactive to Oct. 1, with back
wages paid by Dec. 31.
   AFSCME officials did not return phone calls Wednesday.
</TEXT>
