<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0822EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Aumont Adv16   11-15 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Aumont, Adv 16,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs, Nov. 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jean-Pierre Aumont Stars in PBS' `A Tale of Two Cities'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean-Pierre Aumont confesses he had never
read Charles Dickens' ``A Tale of Two Cities'' until he was asked
to star in a new four-part miniseries for television.
   In the story of the French Revolution, Aumont stars as the
ill-fated Dr. Manette, who was confined for 18 years in the
Bastille. He was imprisoned for denouncing two aristocrats who had
fatally wounded a young couple he had treated.
   The Anglo-French production of ``A Tale of Two Cities'' begins
Sunday on Mobil's ``Masterpiece Theatre'' on PBS.
   It also stars James Wilby as Sidney Carton, Serena Gordon as
Lucie Manette, Xavier DeLuc as Charles Darnay, John Mills as Jarvis
Lorry, Anna Massey as Miss Pross, Kathie Kriegel as Madame Defarge,
Gerald Klein as her husband and Jean-Marc Bory as the Marquis de
St. Evremonde. Philippe Monnier directed.
   ``It is a huge book and I had never read it,'' said Aumont. ``It
took me many days to get through it, but it was worth it.''
   Dr. Manette is in poor health when he is released from the
Bastille. His daughter, Lucie, takes him to England to recover his
health.
   Later, Manette's son-in-law, Charles Darnay, is arrested and,
Aumont explained, ``He returns to France to save his life, which he
does.''
   The series was filmed in Manchester, England, and Bordeaux,
France, which stood in for Paris.
   ``I don't think they could have done it in Paris,'' he said.
``They had to find a place where the streets had not changed.''
   The French-born Aumont began his career on the stage in San
Francisco at the age of 17. He co-starred with Katherine Cornell in
``Roseberg.'' At the start of World War II he returned to France.
   ``I fought in Tunisia, Italy and landed in Southern France,'' he
said. ``I landed with the Americans and for one whole day I was the
only French soldier in France. After the war, I returned to the
United States and made more films.''
   He co-starred with Leslie Caron and Mel Ferrer in ``Lili,'' and
on Broadway he co-starred with Vivien Leigh in ``Tovarich'' and Al
Pacino in ``Camino Real.''
   Aumont talked about the miniseries on a brief visit from Paris,
where he lives with his wife, Marisa Pavan. They have three
children, all of whom are American citizens. One son lives here and
a son and daughter live in Paris.
   He recently completed a movie filmed in Aix-en-Provence called
``The Fighting Frenchman.''
   ``It's about the war and the Resistance and the collaboration,''
he said. ``I play a man who is beginning to believe in Marshal
Petain and think the Germans aren't so bad. Then he has a change of
heart and becomes a follower of Charles de Gaulle.
   ``When I met with the director he told me it would be the story
of a man who enlists in the Free French Forces. I said, `Oh, that's
easy. That's what I did in real life.' There was a long silence and
he said, `Yes, but you play the father.' I had simply forgotten
about my age.''
   Another completed film due for release soon is ``Les Grandes
Familles.''
   In recent years, Aumont has appeared on French television
regularly and on American TV in such shows as ``Hart to Hart'' and
``The Love Boat.''
   ``I did `Gigi' on the stage in London for a year,'' he said.
``That was great fun. I had seven songs and I'm not really a
singer. I told my agent, `I'm not a singer.' He said, `What about
Rex Harrison? What about Maurice Chevalier?' I let myself be easily
convinced.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in Television:
   GEOGRAPHIC SPECIALS _ To help mark National Geography Awareness
Week, National Geographic Television announced plans for four PBS
specials starting in January. The first explores the endangered
Amazon rain forest, the second the Indonesian island of Bali, the
third the Linyanti region of Botswana, and the final program in
April the Soviet city Leningrad. The programs mark the 25th
anniversary of the National Geographic Specials.
   NASTY BOYS _ NBC has ordered 12 episodes of ``Nasty Boys'' from
Universal Television for the midseason. It's based on the North Las
Vegas Police Department's special drug enforcement team, which is
noted for its unorthodox tactics. The two-hour pilot movie on Sept.
22 beat the season premiere of CBS' ``Dallas.'' It was NBC's
highest Friday-night rating in two years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, Nov. 16</NOTE>
