<FIRST>a a AM-Cash-Welfare Adv20   11-15 0961</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cash-Welfare, Adv 20,0988</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Nov. 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Welfare Recipients Earn Cash To Attend Job-Training Classes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An accompanying story is BC-Cash-No Pregnancies, b0340.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kathy Thorpe wants a job. She wants a
place to live in a drug-free neighborhood where she and her two
toddlers will feel safe. And she wants to get off welfare.
   ``Ever since I've had these kids, I've had this fear _ that I'd
always be financially dependent,'' said Thorpe, 28. ``These kids
are depending on me, and I don't want to let them down.''
   Despite a failed marriage, the lack of a job and no day care for
her 2{-year-old daughter and 1-year-old son, she has a better
chance to fulfill that goal now, thanks to an experimental job
training effort that rewards determination with cash bonuses.
   ``I would love to get into computers,'' Thorpe said. ``I'd like
to try to be a word processor.''
   Officials here in Montgomery County, frustrated by the lack of
participation in job-training programs, started a three-year pilot
program in July offering cash incentives of up to $1,000 to
motivate welfare recipients to go to school and get jobs.
   ``It's no longer good enough to just give people a (welfare)
check,'' said Robert S. Caulk, director of the Department of Social
Services for the county, which borders Washington, D.C. ``We've got
to do more to provide them with the wherewithal to get off of
welfare, to break that cycle of dependence.''
   The program, which targets those who have been receiving Aid to
Families with Dependent Children for at least three years and
low-income teen-age parents, is the first in the nation to offer
cash incentives for job training, Caulk said.
   Participants who complete a goal, such as consistently attending
a training class or earning a high school equivalency diploma,
receive payments ranging from $25 to $200, with a limit of $1,000
per person per year. The U.S. Departments of Agriculture and Health
and Human Services agreed to waive requirements that would have
deducted the incentive payments from welfare or food stamp payments.
   The program will cost nearly $1 million in federal, state and
county funds, Caulk said. But the annual savings in welfare
benefits alone would be about $5,000 for each three-member family
that becomes economically self-sufficient, he said.
   Social workers set up goals and payments, taking into
consideration each person's abilities and motivation level.
   ``We're trying to empower case managers to have the flexibility
to say, `For this client, just showing up five days in a row is an
accomplishment,''' he said. ``That person would be rewarded at the
end of five days. Somebody else may have a totally different kind
of package. They may have to score well in word processing or
assembly or retail training. Others may get one payment to complete
the class.''
   About 600 people will participate in the experimental program,
with half receiving cash incentives and the other half acting as a
control group.
   ``The federal government suggested we keep payments quiet'' so
the control group wouldn't know others were receiving payments for
completing the same tasks they did without pay, Caulk said. ``But
that is impossible because they're all in the same classes, and we
want them to discuss their progress and encourage each other.''
   Wealthy Montgomery County has tried other projects in the past.
Three years ago, it gave welfare recipients vouchers worth up to
$250 to pay for food, utilities or other bills in exchange for
their participation in job-training programs. The dropout rate was
more than 50 percent.
   The federal government's approach to the problem is to require
certain welfare recipients to attend job-training classes to keep
their public assistance checks coming.
   But Caulk said even the threat of losing payments they now
receive has not helped motivate some welfare recipients to seek
advancement.
   Last year, Congress passed the Family Support Act, requiring
states to set up large-scale education, job-training and work
programs to make welfare recipients self-sufficient.
   Maryland was the first state to implement the act in all
counties, said J.C. Shay, spokesman for the state Department of
Human Resources, who added that state officials are optimistic
about Montgomery County's program.
   ``We're anxious to see how the cash incentives will impact on
the welfare recipients' participation, motivation and continuation
in the program,'' he said.
   Federal officials are taking a wait-and-see attitude.
   ``We're not in favor of the program or against it, but if it is
successful we'd like to see it tried in other areas,'' said Peter
Germanis of the federal Low-Income Opportunity Board, which
includes officials from several federal agencies who are working to
improve the nation's welfare system. ``And if it were to succeed in
several areas, it could be used for reforming the national wefare
system.''
   Already, the program has surpassed Caulk's expectations.
   ``Our goal was to have 40 people in the first (job-training)
class. So far, 61 people have enrolled,'' he said. ``Going on past
experience, we could lose half in the next month.''
   If the program works, however, the cash incentives would
encourage them to stay, he said.
   ``This has never been tried before, so if we find that the
payments make no difference, even that is worth knowing,'' Caulk
said. ``Then we can sit down and think of something else to try.''
   Thorpe said she is confident the program will work.
   ``When people ask me, `What have you been up to?' I don't say,
`Oh, nothin', just hangin' around.' I say: `I've been busy. I'm
going to school. I'm going to get a job.'''
   And although she'd seek training even without being paid, she
said, ``The money really comes in handy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Nov. 20</NOTE>
