<FIRST>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv25-26   11-15 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 25-26,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 25-26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>1990 Hyundai Sonata GLS: Surprising Room, Performance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Forget what you know about Hyundais. Just get inside the
carmaker's 1990 Sonata.
   Otherwise, you'll spend 5 minutes walking around this roomy,
mid-size car, convinced someone stuck the wrong nameplate on the
door.
   The test car, a Hyundai Sonata GLS with leather interior and V-6
engine, showed the South Korean carmaker has considerable talents
beyond the little low-end subcompact Excel it has been selling in
the United States since 1986.
   The Sonata felt big inside and acted big, with a 3-liter,
multi-port, fuel-injected six-cylinder engine teamed with
four-speed automatic overdrive transmission that delivered up to
142 horsepower on demand rather smoothly. I even made the tires
squeal a few times when I really tried to gun it.
   Front seats were roomy, and back seat space was impressive. With
the front seats moved up a bit, I could even stretch out my legs in
the back seat. With the front seats back a bit, I still had decent
legroom. Headroom and shoulder space in back also were commendable.
   In fact, the Sonata's 99.7 cubic feet of passenger space is
bigger than that of some other sedans such as the Toyota Camry.
   Exterior styling on the Sonata was subdued, not exactly
expressive, but certainly the car has a nice look.
   Suspension and handling is capable. The car does a good job of
cushioning harsh bumps with its rather spongy ride.
   Inside, the rear-seat armrests offered storage space, big side
windows added to the roomy feel and the ventilation system was
powerful. The button to pop open the trunk was neatly tucked on the
underside of the driver's armrest, so you don't have to hunt for it
in the glovebox as in some domestic cars.
   Best of all, the base price for a 1990 Sonata with manual
transmission is $9,999, making it a potent price competitor in the
mid-size sedan segment.
   In contrast, the Mitsubishi Galant sedan with manual
transmission starts at $10,989 and the Toyota Camry sedan with
manual transmission starts at $11,588.
   At that Toyota price, you're close to the upscale Sonata GLS
with manual transmission, which starts at $12,349. And the GLS
model includes tilt steering, cruise control, power door locks and
windows and illuminated vanity mirror as standard equipment.
   The GLS test car, with options that included leather interior,
air conditioning and premium radio, topped out at $15,849.
   Not bad for a roomy, V-6-powered car that can comfortably and
sensibly be used for family jaunts around town, vacation travel or
trips to work.
   That should appeal to likely buyers of the Sonata, most of whom
will be men (55 percent of buyers), with a median age of 40, and
married (70 percent of buyers), according to the company.
   Thirty-three percent of buyers are likely to be college-educated
and median income is expected to be $32,000.
   I did find a couple of annoyances in the test car. The power
antenna made five or six loud, thumping sounds whenever it went up
or down. And, as a passenger pointed out, the open-close
adjustments for the inside vents at each end of the dashboard
didn't work properly; the vents actually released more air when the
levers were in the closed position.
   But overall, the Sonata was a surprising car.
   Unfortunately, sales have been surprising, too _ surprisingly
low since the Sonata's introduction early in 1989. Hyundai had
looked to sell 80,000 of the cars this year. But sales totaled
26,150 through October as U.S. car sales turned sluggish.
   Because the Sonata is a new vehicle, there is no owner report of
trouble from Consumer Reports magazine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 25-26</NOTE>
