<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--O'Keeffe Adv24-26   11-15 0893</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--O'Keeffe, Adv 24-26,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: The Passion of Georgia O'Keeffe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passion and commitment to her art drove Georgia
O'Keeffe's painting, which both illuminates her appeal and adds a
compassionate dimension to the O'Keeffe legend, according to a
recent biographer.
   Roxana Robinson, author of ``Georgia O'Keeffe: A Life,'' said
the artist endures because she painted emotion in the 20th century.
   ``From the start of this century, painting in this country has
been done in the masculine tradition, (which) has been either cold
or angry. O'Keeffe's paintings are passionate, tender and full of
joy. And specifically they refer to the female experience,'' she
said in a recent interview.
   The findings by Robinson, aided in her study by cooperation from
O'Keeffe's family, come in contrast to popular notions that
O'Keeffe was detached, even cool about her work and relationships.
   She draws from O'Keeffe's letters and interviews with her
associates and relatives to trace the artist's life from childhood
on the Wisconsin prairie in the early 1900s through her tumultuous
marriage to New York photographer and art impresario Alfred
Stieglitz.
   ``Georgia O'Keeffe: A Life'' (Harper and Row, $25) also examines
O'Keeffe's complicated relationship with Juan Hamilton, a
23-year-old drifter who appeared on her doorstep looking for work
in 1973 and stayed until her death. The letters discount the
persistent sexual interpretations of O'Keeffe's work.
   ``She was much warmer and more vulnerable than I expected,''
said Robinson, a novelist and art historian. ``She was also
probably colder and more difficult, too. But doing the research I
began to understand why.''
   O'Keeffe's life on the prairie as the eldest daughter of a
farming family with six siblings taught her the importance of
self-sufficiency; her independence was established early in life.
   ``I am going to live a different life from the rest of you
girls,'' she said upon graduating from high school. ``I am going to
give up everything for my art.''
   Her love for Stieglitz, who was nearly two decades her senior,
was strong, and he not only was enamored with her, but as a leading
figure in New York's art world he was also her greatest booster.
   ``If you were a woman and a painter, you were a woman painter.
And that was very different from being a painter,'' Robinson said.
``It was important that she had somebody that was at least trying
to get her work perceived as equal to men. But he didn't promote
her work as any better than it actually was.''
   Stieglitz, however, was also O'Keeffe's greatest source of pain,
but she never confronted him with his appetite for other young
women. Again, her family ethic of self-sufficiency allowed her to
cope.
   She demanded her solitude to work and began to spend about half
the year apart from her husband, painting in New Mexico. The
O'Keeffe legend portrays her as a woman who just decided she was
leaving one morning, but O'Keeffe's pain was deep.
   ``At that period of her deepest grief and unhappiness she turned
her energies toward her art instead of her anguish,'' Robinson
said. ``If Stieglitz chose to make her unhappy, her job was to see
that she was not unhappy. It was not to change his behavior.''
   O'Keeffe died in 1986 at the age of 98.
   The research alone makes Robinson's book worth reading, although
her prose is sometimes redundant and her own pronouncements on
feminism often blunt the message O'Keeffe's life so clearly
illustrated.
   The book does not raise the issue of O'Keeffe's supposed
bisexuality because, Robinson said, she could not produce any
corroborating evidence.
   The sexual content of much of O'Keeffe's bright and flowing
flowers has long been debated, most vehemently by the artist
herself.
   ``When you took time to really notice my flower, you hung all
your own associations with flowers on my flower,'' O'Keeffe wrote
to one critic. ``And you write about my flower as if I think and
see what you think and see of the flower _ and I don't.''
   For O'Keeffe, the flowers were demonstrations of passion, but
not specifically representing genitalia or sexual objects, Robinson
says.
   ``O'Keeffe's flowers were images drawn from a female
perspective, which made them both new and suspect,'' Robinson wrote.
   Similarly, O'Keeffe's later stark depictions of cattle skulls
and bones she found on the desert of New Mexico were often
misinterpreted to symbolize death.
   ``I have wanted to paint the desert and I haven't known how,''
she wrote in an exhibition catalog. ``So I brought home the
bleached bones as my symbols of the desert. To me they are as
beautiful as anything I know. ... The bones seem to cut sharply to
the center of something that is keenly alive in the desert even
tho' it is vast and empty and untouchable _ and knows no kindness
with all its beauty.''
   Robinson portays O'Keeffe as a leading example of the changing
roles of women throughout the 20th century.
   ``Georgia O'Keeffe, by her example, gave permission to the
following generations of women to give work priority in their
lives, to consider it crucial,'' Robinson writes.
   ``Her paintings ... were about something that had never been
before so clearly revealed: the female experience.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26</NOTE>
</DOC>
