<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Byrne Adv24-26   11-15 1205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Byrne, Adv 24-26,1234</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Burning Down the House With a New Latin Beat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forsaking African rhythms, jazz arrangements
and avant-garde electronics of previous Talking Heads and solo
efforts, David Byrne's latest musical safari has brought him to the
seductive beats of Latin America.
   ``It's a little different, maybe,'' Byrne said from the stage of
the Pantages theater to the bobbing concertgoers below. ``But maybe
not,'' he quickly added, springing into another conga-laced tune.
   Those familiar with the hybrid tastes of Byrne, the lead singer
of Talking Heads, knew just what he meant. Although his new album,
``Rei Momo,'' is infused with merengues and sambas, it's about as
traditional a record as any he's made.
   ``I'm not trying to convert people, or educate people or do any
of that kind of stuff,'' Byrne said in an interview while stopping
in Los Angeles during a national tour this fall. ``For me, it's
purely something I'm getting a lot of enjoyment out of _ music that
I think is deep and fun. It's what I want to do. It's not as though
I'm saying: `Now, I want to tell you about this! You must sit down
and listen!'''
   Unlike the contemplative, occasionally downcast themes cascading
through Byrne's prior work, ``Rei Momo'' carries both invigorating
lyrics and beats. In ``Don't Want to Be Part of Your World,'' for
example, he sings of children escaping an imperfect life to a place
``free from greed and hunger, free from hate and war.''
   ``I think it is somewhat inherent in the culture _ the music,
the melodies and rhythms _ that it can give you a kind of tinge of
something uplifting, spiritual or whatever,'' the 37-year-old Byrne
said.
   ``In Brazil, there's a vast difference between the rich and the
poor. The economy is in pretty bad shape. And yet they have these
incredible cultural resources. The spirit of the people is very
rich.
   ``Not only in Brazil but also in a lot of Latin culture, in the
barrios in New York and Los Angeles and Texas ... music is filled
with the spirit of life. And you feel, `This is what is allowing
people to go on.'
   ``The music seems to reflect their lives and add something to
their lives, rather than being the latest record that's foisted on
them.''
   Byrne is the latest American artist to use Latin sounds in pop
music in the 1980s. Others have included Paul Simon, who has worked
with Brazilian star Milton Nascimento, Quincy Jones and the
Manhattan Transfer. Madonna recorded a song, ``La Isla Bonita,''
which had a Latin flavor, and Linda Ronstadt put out an album of
Mexican favorites taught to her by her father.
   Twenty-five years after Brazilian music first caught American
ears with the quiet strains of bossa nova, a second Brazilian
invasion is occurring. Brazilian superstars such as Djavan, Simone,
Caetano Veloso and Nascimento have been signed to American labels
and are touring the United States.
   Latin music has likewise grown in popularity, with the arrival
of crossover artists such as Miami Sound Machine and Reuben Blades.
   The co-founder of the 14-year-old but now idle Talking Heads,
Byrne has directed the film ``True Stories,'' acted in public
television's ``Trying Times,'' and composed the scores for the
Twyla Tharp dance ``The Catherine Wheel,'' Robert Wilson's opera
``The Forest'' and the movies ``The Last Emperor'' and ``Married to
the Mob.''
   For the 1986 movie ``Something Wild,'' he composed his first
Afro-Latin single, ``Loco de Amor,'' sung by Celia Cruz, the queen
of Latin music.
   It was scarcely a radical departure. In some of the 10 albums
Byrne has recorded with Talking Heads, especially 1980's ``Remain
in Light'' and last year's ``Naked,'' his music has been laced with
African sounds.
   Byrne refined his appreciation for Afro-Latin compositions while
spending six weeks in Brazil last year making a documentary about
native dance-music rituals for public television's ``Alive From Off
Center.'' In addition to ``Rei Momo,'' he has assembled two
compilations of Brazilian hits, ``Beleza Tropical: Brazil Classics,
Volume 1,'' which reached the No. 1 position on Cashbox's Latin
charts, and the new ``O Samba: Brazil Classics, Volume 2.''
   Because Byrne enjoys a loyal following, his current tour is
attracting mostly capacity audiences. ``Rei Momo'' debuted at No.
30 on the compact disc charts while the album was No. 109 after two
weeks.
   Yet the people attending the concerts given by Byrne and his
16-piece band are largely white Americans _ not the kind of
audience usually seen at a concert where vocals aren't always in
English and the bandstand is filled with such instruments as the
coro and sencerro _ Cuban drums _ and guiro, a percussion device.
   ``What we're doing will help the Latin scene ... a lot,'' said
Milton Cardona, a percussionist who appears on Byrne's album and
tour.
   Angel Fernandez, who plays trumpet and arranged several of the
album's songs, said: ``That's part of the excitement. To us, it's
great to be bringing this music to a bigger audience. And I think
the public is ready for something new.''
   Said Byrne: ``You don't have to understand it to enjoy it.
   ``I'm encouraged by the audience (but) I'm still afraid about
radio,'' he said. ``When (radio stations) hear that it's a Latin
record, they say, `Whoa! We don't play Latin music, we play the
hits.'''
   For both the album and the 20-city tour that started in
Poughkeepsie, N.Y., in mid-September with plans for a South
American and Europe swing, Byrne gathered some of the nation's
leading Latin musicians _ veterans of bands for Ruben Blades, Tito
Puente and Cruz.
   In assembling the record, Byrne attempted to build songs that
satisfied both his perfectionist personality and the music's latent
disregard for formality.
   ``On the cumbia (`Independence Day'), for instance, I had a drum
set up for the recording session,'' Byrne said. ``And the drummer
came in, and he hardly ever touched the drums. He usually would
play the side of one of the tom toms. He didn't hit the snare drum
once. So it was ... everything exactly the opposite of what a rock
drummer would do.
   ``This was really different than recording with Talking Heads.
For each song, we'd kind of cast the players in a way. ... If
something was, say, a merengue, there are musicians who specialize
in that kind of rhythm and those kind of bass parts, and we'd get
those musicians in.''
   While a few critics have accused the shy musician of
international cultural vandalism, Byrne says he's only creating new
music out of old, as has been done for years.
   ``If everybody plays the same stuff, then nobody will listen to
any of it,'' he said.
   ``I want to be free to do whatever I want to do. ... I get
accused a little bit of flirting around with different styles, but
I think a lot of them have an awful lot in common, and that I'm not
jumping around as much as it may appear on the surface.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26</NOTE>
