<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Jones Adv24-26   11-15 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Jones, Adv 24-26,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Shirley Jones Records First Solo Album</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a show business career of more
than 30 years, including singing in movie classics such as
``Oklahoma!'' and ``The Music Man,'' Shirley Jones has released her
first solo album.
   The Diadem Music LP ``Silent Strength'' is a collection of
gospel songs.
   ``I grew up singing Christian music,'' Jones, 55, said in a
telephone interview from her home in Beverly Hills, Calif. ``I was
the youngest member of my church choir at age 6.
   ``It has been synonymous with my singing. It's beautiful music
and this (project) was a wonderful experience.
   ``I've never really done a solo album. I've done the movie
albums and did some things for Columbia with my husband, Jack, and
of course `The Partridge Family.'''
   In 1970-74, Jones was Shirley Partridge in the popular TV comedy
about a family that became successful in show business. She
portrayed a widowed suburban mother and David Cassidy, her real
life stepson, was Keith Partridge.
   ``I did 23 motion pictures and nobody knew me until `The
Partridge Family,''' she said. ``But that's TV. The power of TV is
the strongest power we have now. You become a friend to people.
You're really not larger than life, but part of their family.
   ``The show had a combination of things. It had music for the
time. We were a family in show business, an everyday family. Plus
we had good actors. David was a teen hero and little Danny Bonaduce
was a wonderful young comedian. The chemistry worked.''
   Her movie credits, besides ``Oklahoma!'' and ``The Music Man,''
include ``Carousel,'' ``Elmer Gantry'' (Academy Award for
supporting actress in 1961), ``April Love'' and ``Beyond the
Poseidon Adventure.'' Her most recent film was ``Tank'' with James
Garner three years ago.
   The Oscar, she said, changed her career. ``I was considered a
pretty young thing who could sing until then. After that, they said
that maybe this kid can act. It opened doors for me, no doubt.''
   She also has appeared in several TV movies, including ``The
Family Nobody Wanted,'' ``Winner Take All,'' ``The Orchard
Children,'' ``Last Cry for Help'' and ``Silent Night, Lonely
Night.'' Most dealt with topical issues such as gambling addiction,
unjust adoption procedures and teen suicide.
   ``Those kind of roles are wonderful to play,'' Miss Jones said.
   She recently taped a two-hour tribute show to composer Richard
Rodgers, to be broadcast on the Public Broadcasting Service next
March.
   Jones also sings frequently with symphony orchestras across the
country. One of her traditional songs is ``You'll Never Walk
Alone'' from ``Carousel.'' The song is also on her solo album.
   ``It conveys a message to audiences of all types, whether
Christian or Jewish or whatever,'' she said. ``Those words touch
people. I've been singing it even before `Carousel.' It's been part
of my repertoire for 30 years now. When I think of the words during
a distressing time, it helps me through.''
   Among other cuts on the album, ``The Music's Gotta Stop
Someday'' describes the emptiness of entertainment without content.
The title cut ``Silent Strength'' is about trusting one's savior.
   ``We spent five hours in my living room one Sunday afternoon
going through the music,'' Jones said. ``We pored through music and
talked about words and what was right for me. I wanted to do
beautiful ballads with beautiful lyrics and no rock 'n' roll
stuff.''
   She said she's at a point in her career where she accepts only
projects that intrigue her. ``I'm at a marvelous place in my life.
I'm not driven by my career, but I never have been really. I can
pick and choose. I'm able to do what I want to do which is sing,
basically.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26</NOTE>
