<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-15 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0879</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales fell a full 1 percent in October,
driven down by a slumping auto market, and industrial production
dropped 0.7 percent in its steepest fall in more than three years,
the government said.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that retail sales
dropped to a seasonally adjusted $144.5 billion, the first decline
since a 0.4 percent drop last February. Sales had rise 0.7 percent
in September and 0.9 percent in August.
   The decline in industrial production was the steepest since a
1.3 percent drop in March 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically made cars and light trucks
continued a skid that started last month, falling 20.2 percent in
early November compared with a year ago, the automakers reported.
   The eight major companies that make cars in the United States
said Tuesday they sold cars and light trucks at an average daily
rate of 26,194 during the Nov. 1-10 period this year compared with
a daily rate of 32,833 during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savings and loan regulators undermined a
securities investigation linked to the nation's largest savings and
loan failure, the head of the Securities and Exchange Commission
said at a hearing where tearful, elderly witnesses told of losing
their life savings.
   SEC Chairman Richard C. Breeden told the House Banking Committee
on Tuesday that a ``memorandum of understanding'' between the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board and Lincoln Savings and Loan
Association gave Lincoln's parent company a powerful legal tool to
resist the SEC's probe.
   The SEC was trying to determine if the parent company, American
Continental Corp., headed by Phoenix, Ariz., millionaire Charles H.
Keating Jr., had filed false financial statements.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southland Corp. said it may be unable to make
payments due in 1991 on debt it incurred in its $4.9 billion
leveraged buyout and is considering a recapitalization or other
restructuring.
   Southland, which was acquired by its founding Thompson family in
the 1987 buyout, until now had maintained that it could meet its
debt obligations. But the company said Tuesday that sales
projections at its 7-Eleven convenience stores had not been met.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel has approved a bill that gives
the Securities and Exchange Commission limited authority to control
program trading in market emergencies.
   The telecommunications and finance subcommittee, after a
sometimes heated debate over whether it was moving too fast, voted
Tuesday to send the bill to the full Energy and Commerce Committee
for consideration, possibly as soon as Thursday.
   The bill, known as the Securities Markets Stabilization Act of
1989, would give the Securities and Exchange Commission new
authority to suspend or constrain practices that could cause market
volatility _ sharp price rises and drops.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc. said it is introducing an
interactive 900-number telephone service that will enable callers
to get stock quotes, business and financial news, sports reports
and weather conditions.
   Dow Jones, publisher of The Wall Street Journal, said Tuesday it
plans to charge 85 cents for the first minute and 75 cents for each
additional minute for calls to its service, called JournalPhone.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. has reported a net
loss of $447 million for the third quarter as income from its
domestic cigarette business declined.
   The loss, reported Tuesday, compared with a net profit of $355
million, or $1.55 a share, in the third quarter of last year.
   The consumer products giant was taken private in October 1988 in
a $24.53 billion leveraged buyout by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
Therefore, there are no per-share figures for the latest results.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines said it plans to buy $10 billion
worth of new jets, including 160 of McDonnell Douglas Corp.'s new
MD-90 aircraft.
   The orders and options announced Tuesday are in addition to $13
billion in plane orders announced earlier by the Atlanta-based
carrier. Delta has orders and options now on a total of 519 new
jets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Wall Street stock speculator Ivan F.
Boesky has been granted a temporary release from his three-year
term at a California prison camp, authorities said.
   Boesky is due back at the minimum-security prison in Lompoc,
Calif., around the end of the month, said Ed Wolahan, the prison's
supervisor of education. The furlough began Thursday.
   Tuesday marked three years since Boesky paid $100 million and
agreed to plead guilty to one felony to settle charges in Wall
Street's biggest insider trading scandal.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices retreated in sluggish trading Tuesday amid
uneasiness about the economy's weakness and pessimism about the
chances for lower interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial average
fell 16.18 to 2,610.25.
   The dollar fell sharply against all key currencies.
   Bond prices finished mixed.
   Platinum futures prices climbed to six-month highs; gold and
silver also advanced; cocoa futures plunged; energy, livestock and
meat futures were lower; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
