<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryAuction     11-15 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Auction,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Yields Fall As Government Completes Quarterly Refunding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds fell in
Tuesday's auction to the lowest level in nearly three years as the
government completed its quarterly refunding.
   The average yield was 7.87 percent, down from 8.14 percent at
the last auction on Aug. 10.
   It was the lowest rate since 30-year bonds averaged 7.49 percent
on Feb. 5, 1987. The bonds will carry a coupon interest rate of 8[
percent with each $10,000 in face value selling for $10,287.50.
   A total of $10 billion in bonds were sold out of bids totaling
$20.4 billion.
   In addition to Tuesday's bond auction, the refunding involved
sales of $10 billion of three-year notes last Thursday, $10 billion
of 36-day cash management bills last Friday and $10 billion of
10-year notes on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MotorizedAd     11-15 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Motorized Ad,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Marnier Liqueur Plans Motorized Magazine Ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The importers of Absolut vodka were nosed out
recently by Texas Instruments Inc. in getting the first ``talking''
magazine ad to market.
   But Carillon Importers Ltd. is back, claiming a first for
another of its brands _ a ``motorized'' magazine ad for Grand
Marnier liqueur.
   When the center spread of the four-page ad is opened, a
cardboard cutout that shows two fanciful birds with oranges on
their bodies gently swinging a bottle of Grand Marnier between them
as if it were a bell.
   The cutout is powered by a tiny battery embedded out of sight
beneath the cutout.
   The Teaneck, N.J.-based importer said Tuesday it had spent more
than $1 million on the four-page holiday ad that is to appear in
selected copies of the Dec. 11 issue of the New Yorker. The ad will
be included in the 200,000 issues of the magazine that are sent to
subscribers in California and New York state.
   The ad is the latest example of the extra effort some liquor
advertisiers take to make their ads stand out at Christmastime.
   Absolut vodka's talking ad in selected copies of the December
issue of Vanity Fair magazine delivered tinny holiday greetings in
Italian, English and Spanish.
   But Texas Instruments ran an ad with a talking computer chip
about two weeks earlier in Business Week magazine.
   Other holiday magazine ad spectaculars this year include a
hologram from Finlandia vodka, an ad with pull-up tabs from Chivas
Regal Scotch whisky and peel-off stickers from Crown Royal Canadian
whisky.
   Some advertising executives have criticized the ad spectaculars,
saying it detracts from the environment for their clients' ads. But
others argue the unusual ads attract attention to a magazine and
make consumers more aware of other magazines.
   ``Most people love to see this sort of thing in their
magazines,'' said Steven Florio, president and chief executive of
The New Yorker Magazine Inc. ``We thought this was innovative and
creative and our readers would enjoy seeing it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
