<DOCNO> AP891115-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Wendy'sAnniversary Bjt   11-15 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wendy's Anniversary, Bjt,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hamburger Chain Founded By High School Dropout Celebrates 20 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CO3</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to correct LaserPhoto number.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Wendy's International Inc. celebrates
its 20th anniversary today, its founder pledges to renew a
dedication to customers that he believes the fast-food chain lost
somewhere along the way.
   ``We forgot who the customer was,'' founder and former Chairman
R. David Thomas said in an interview this week. ``But in 1989,
we're working hard on customer satisfaction and clean restaurants.
   The high school dropout opened the first Wendy's in downtown
Columbus on Nov. 15, 1969, naming it after his daughter. He stuck
to a limited menu of hamburgers and chili that he believed was the
only way to maintain quality.
   Today, the chain has grown to the nation's third- or
fourth-largest, depending upon the criteria used, behind No. 1
McDonald's and No. 2 Burger King, and possibly behind Hardee's. It
rakes in $3 billion in annual sales with a menu that has mushroomed
to include pizza, salad, pasta, two types of chicken sandwiches,
burritos, baked potatoes and chocolate chip cookies.
   Thomas, who owns 8 percent, or $40 million, of Wendy's stock,
said in a 1978 interview that he wanted Wendy's to be bigger than
McDonald's Corp.
   Asked about that on Monday, he said: ``We still just want to be
the best, the cleanest restaurant, the best prices, the best food.
We'll be as big as we want to be.''
   Thomas, who retired as chairman in 1982, now stars in his own
folksy television ads for Wendy's, which is based in nearby Dublin.
   Industry analysts say Wendy's started on the fast track and grew
quickly, establishing 1,000 stores in nine years and becoming the
No. 3 fast-food chain before its recent slide.
   ``They developed a unique niche targeting the adult fast-food
segment of the hamburger industry with a tightly-focused menu,''
said analyst Jeff Stein of McDonald &amp; Co. in Cleveland.
   ``But Wendy's seems to have lost some of its focus as it tried
to expand its menu and diversify into breakfast, which was not
successful, and spent a lot of money upgrading its restaurants,''
he said. ``They've seen their market share erode along the way.''
   Thomas said the diversification was necessary.
   ``In 1979, we had a real problem with beef, and the price went
way up, and the word `nutrition' started appearing, so we put in
the salad bar. Competition was getting keener, so we added a lot of
things. I don't think we could have the same menu as we did in '69
and be successful,'' he said.
   Average sales at Wendy's 3,762 restaurants rose 2.4 percent to
$759,000 per store last year, breaking a three-year decline.
Hardee's Food Systems Inc. reported average sales of $920,000 at
its 3,200 stores last year.
   Per-unit sales at Wendy's were highest in 1984, at $871,000.
That was the year of Clara Peller's commanding performance in the
``Where's the Beef?'' commercials.
   ``Advertising is an important part of the business, but it's not
a cure-all,'' said analyst Howard Hansen of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.
in New York.
   ``It may raise levels of awareness and bring customers in. But
unless you're giving a hot hamburger to a customer in a clean place
and quickly, all the advertising in the world isn't going to amount
to a hill of beans,'' he said.
   Hansen pegged Wendy's share of the fast-food market at about 4.8
percent, trailing 5.5 percent for Hardee's. McDonald's has about
18.9 percent, Hansen said.
   To help boost sales, Wendy's last November started installing a
system allowing customers to pay for food with a Visa card. Tests
show people spend more when they use credit cards, the company said.
   Earnings for the third quarter totaled $8.7 million, or 9 cents
a share, on revenue of $296.2 million, compared with the same
profit on revenue of $275.2 million for the same period last year.
   Thomas said that, for now, the company will continue a strategy
of making existing stores more profitable and opening new units at
a slower pace _ about 100 a year.
   ``We've got to take business from competition, business from
anyone,'' Thomas said. ``We've got to take care of the customers,
just like we did 20 years ago.''
</TEXT>
