<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales     11-15 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car and Truck Sales Continue Slump</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sales slump in domestically made cars and
light trucks continued in early November, prompting speculation
that automakers will bring back incentives to attract buyers.
   ``The hard thing to read is which of the Big Three is going to
move quickly next to reinvigorate sales with new incentive
programs,'' analyst Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
said Tuesday after sales figures were released.
   The eight major automakers with U.S. plants said they sold cars
and light trucks at an average daily rate of 26,194 during the Nov.
1-10 period compared with a 32,833-a-day pace during the same time
last year.
   Car sales dropped 23.1 percent, while sales of light trucks fell
15.3 percent during the period, compared with early November last
year. In October, domestic car and truck sales tumbled 11.6 percent
from the rate of October 1988.
   The drop in U.S. car and truck sales last month pushed down
October retail sales by 1 percent, the first decline in eight
months.
   ``We are in the midst of an automotive recession,'' said analyst
Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York. ``For anybody in
this economy, these types of numbers today are not funny.
   ``It's scary,'' he said. ``I don't think they are going to
continue. I hope they won't continue.''
   One of the ways automakers have accelerated auto sales recently
is through cash rebates or cut-rate financing. The companies had
incentive programs on a wide variety of 1989 models but have less
extensive programs now.
   Merlis and Phillippi said that could change.
   ``Any one of them (the Big Three) has a good reason to increase
them,'' Phillippi said. Merlis said he expected bigger incentive
packages to be combined with production cuts, a move analysts have
been expecting for months.
   ``You need more than just incentives to get inventories in
line,'' he said. ``This is an old-fashioned cyclical downturn with
a very sad effect on the general economy.''
   Sluggish car and light-truck sales during October and early
November have pushed the year-to-date sales rate down 2.6 percent
compared with the same time last year. Car sales are down 3.6
percent and truck sales are off 0.8 percent.
   General Motors Corp. said its early November combined domestic
car and truck sales were down 26.3 percent compared with last year,
with car sales dropping 29.1 percent and truck sales falling 20.9
percent.
   Sales of vehicles made in North America by Ford Motor Co. were
off 19.9 percent in early November, as car sales fell 23.5 percent
and truck sales dropped 14.3 percent.
   At Chrysler Corp., car sales during the period were down 22.5
percent and truck sales were down 9.9 percent, combining for a 16.6
percent drop in the early November vehicle sales pace.
</TEXT>
