<FIRST>r f PM-MarketReforms     11-15 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market Reforms,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Market Reform Bill Clears First Hurdle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill giving the Securities and Exchange
Commission limited authority to control program trading in market
emergencies has cleared its first hurdle.
   The House telecommunications and finance subcommittee, after a
sometimes heated debate over whether it was too much too soon,
voted Tuesday to send the bill to the full Energy and Commerce
Committee for consideration, possibly as soon as Thursday.
   Congressional leaders have said they want to end the current
session before Thanksgiving.
   ``I'm not convinced it's something we should have such a rush to
judgment,'' said Rep. Thomas Tauke, R-Iowa. ``We all know we're not
going to get this through Congress and down to the White House
before the end of the year anyway,'' he added.
   But Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said ``I think it would be
unconscionable to leave this congressional session without sending
a message to the markets.''
   The bill, known as the Securities Markets Stabilization Act of
1989, would give the Securities and Exchange Commission new
authority to suspend or constrain practices that could cause market
volatility _ sharp price rises and drops.
   Chief among those controversial practices is program trading,
the almost instantaneous, computer-driven transactions involving
huge blocks of stock.
   The proposed legislation also:
   _Would give the SEC authority, after consulting with the
president, to halt all trading in the securities markets in the
event of an emergency like the 1987 stock market crash.
   _Require large securities transactions to be reported.
   _Require the parent and affiliated companies of securities and
investment firms to verify their financial stability with the SEC.
   Another provision that calls for coordinated clearing and
settlement of transactions among the SEC and other government
agencies was moved into a separate bill, the Coordinated Clearance
and Settlement Act, which also passed the subcommittee.
   A similar bill is pending in the Senate but Senate leaders have
expressed doubts that they can add a program trading provision and
still get it passed before the holiday break.
   The provision giving the SEC modified authority to halt program
trading was approved only after the panel agreed to an amendment by
Rep. Matthew Rinaldo of New Jersey, the subcommittee's ranking
Republican, limiting the description of practices the SEC could
halt or prohibit.
   ``This language does not ban program trading and it does not
direct the SEC to ban program trading,'' said Rinaldo. ``It allows
the SEC to use its discretion in limiting or curtailing disruptive
trading strategies.''
   Opponents of program trading are particularly critical of one
form, index arbitrage, in which speculators try to take advantage
of inconsistencies between the stock and futures markets by
simultaneously buying in one while selling in the other.
   Critics claim index arbitrage leads to wild price swings which
drives small investors out of the market. And that makes it harder
for U.S. companies to raise capital through the sale of securities,
they claim.
   Originally, the bill sought to prohibit ``manipulative, abusive
or disruptive practices'' but several panel members complained that
language was too vague.
   When Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., the subcommittee chairman,
offered his assurance that he would hammer out suitable compromise
language before the bill went to the full committee, Rep. W.J.
Tauzin, D-La., said, ``What I don't think what we ought to do is
move on language we can't agree upon.''
   Other members complained that they needed more time to review
the most recent changes in the bill, some of which were added just
the night before.
   ``In the waning days of the session,'' said Rep. Thomas Manton,
D-N.Y., ``I think we're moving rather fast.''
   That sparked an outburst from Markey: ``We have had hearing
after hearing after hearing,'' he said, noting that several big
Wall Street securities firms that oppose program trading were
repeatedly invited to testify at those hearings but ``they turned
us down every time.''
   Rinaldo's amendment deleted the word ``disruptive'' from the
bill, which seemed to satisfy opponents pending further
negotiations on appropriate language.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TaxExtensions     11-15 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Extensions,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Extends Tax Breaks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has voted to extend through June 30
a dozen targeted tax breaks that are expiring, including
employer-financed education assistance.
   The extensions, most of them for six months, were approved by
voice vote Tuesday without debate and added to a bill authorizing
aid to Poland and Hungary. That measure is subject to further
consideration by the House.
   Each of the extensions had been approved by the House as part of
other legislation.
   Among the extended provisions are those offering tax reductions
for up to $5,250 per year of employer-paid education aid received
by a worker; a limited amount of employer-financed group legal aid;
businesses that increase spending for research and experimentation;
investment in rental housing for low-income families; self-employed
people to help cover the cost of health insurance; employers who
hire low-income people, and investors in bonds targeted to help
lower-income families buy a first home.
   Most of the tax breaks are due to expire Dec. 31. The deduction
for employer-financed education assistance expired last Dec. 31.
   The amendment adding the provisions to the Poland-Hungary bill
was written by Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo.
   ``If we allow them to expire, real damage can be caused,''
Danforth said. He cited, for example, the low-income housing credit
as about the only federal aid now available for that sector. ``If
we decide it is just going to go away for however long it takes
until we can re-enact it, there can be some real damage to
low-income housing,'' he said.
   The cost of the extensions, an estimated $1.2 billion, would be
made up by accelerating the rate at which large corporations must
turn over to the government the taxes they withhold from workers'
paychecks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 0240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-LincolnS&amp;L Bjt   11-15 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L, Bjt,0882</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Lost Savings in Lincoln S&amp;L Failure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of mostly elderly victims lost their
savings through Lincoln Savings and Loan after federal thrift
regulators undercut a Securities and Exchange Commission case
against its owner, say witnesses before a House committee.
   Four of the victims, some in tears, told the House Banking
Committee on Tuesday how Lincoln officials led them to believe junk
bonds in the thrift's holding company, American Continental Corp.,
purchased with their converted savings were federally insured and
safe.
   All of them blamed American Continental's chairman, Charles H.
Keating Jr., and five senators they tagged the ``Keating Five'' who
accepted a total of $1.3 million in political contributions from
the Phoenix millionaire.
   ``Up against the likes of Charles Keating and the influence he
was able to buy from elected officials and others in high office,
we didn't stand a chance,'' said Shirley Lampel, a partially blind
widow from Tustin, Calif., who lost $30,000.
   The five senators _ Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Donald Riegle,
D-Mich.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; John McCain, R-Ariz., and John
Glenn, D-Ohio _ are subjects of inquiries by the Senate Ethics
Committee and the FBI.
   Officials are investigating whether the senators improperly
intervened on behalf of Keating in April 1987 with thrift
regulators who were considering seizing Lincoln on grounds it was
unsound. Despite a formal recommendation a month later recommending
just that, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board waited until April 1989
to seize Lincoln.
   All of the senators have denied any wrongdoing in the Lincoln
fiasco, which is expected to cost taxpayers up to $2.5 billion and
22,000 bondholders like Mrs. Lampel, a majority of them retirees,
another $250 million.
   SEC Chairman Richard Breeden, who as a White House aide to
President Bush designed the $200 billion-plus taxpayer bailout of
the S&amp;L industry, said the experiences of Mrs. Lampel and others
has convinced him the banking laws need to be rewritten again.
   ``To be allowed to sell junk bonds of your parent (company) in
the lobby of a financial institution with the sinecure of federal
protection is something that Congress perhaps ought to prohibit,''
Breeden said. ``It's a little bit like having the requirement you
can't sell liquor within so many yards of a polling place.''
   While Mrs. Lampel and the others were being encouraged by
Lincoln officials to move their money out of federally insured
deposits into the high-risk, uninsured bonds, the SEC was trying to
determine if the holding company had filed false financial
statements.
   Breeden said a May 20, 1988, ``memorandum of understanding''
between the Federal Home Loan Bank Board and Lincoln accepting the
thrift's accounting on $135 million in disputed transactions gave
the parent company a powerful legal tool to resist the SEC's probe.
   ``The regulator of the subsidiary institution said, in essence,
that financial statements were all right,'' he said.
   Karl Hoyle, a spokesman for the bank board, now called the
Office of Thrift Supervision, said the memorandum ``in no way could
have impeded'' the SEC investigation. ``They're independent. ...
There's nothing we can do to get in the way,'' he said.
   Breeden also said the SEC has turned over some of the evidence
in its probe to a federal grand jury in Los Angeles considering
possible criminal charges against Keating and his associates.
   Keating and M. Danny Wall, the bank board's chairman and now
head of the Office of Thrift Supervision, have been subpoenaed to
testify before the House committee next week.
   While the committee has focused on Wall, the victims directed
much of their anger at Cranston, who raised more than $970 million
from Keating for his own and other Democratic political causes.
   Connie Wickman, 78, of West Hills., Calif., said she and her
husband were heartbroken when they learned their $25,000 in
retirement funds had been lost.
   ``I had no idea this man could be so corrupted,'' said Mrs.
Lampel. ``What Alan Cranston did here was not only foolish; it was
cruel, it was dishonest. It has devastated people and it has
devastated me.''
   Murray Flander, a spokesman for Cranston, said the senator has
``nothing but compassion for these people.''
   Among other Lincoln developments Tuesday:
   _The House committee's chairman, Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez,
D-Texas, said he intends to investigate other failed thrifts
``beyond Lincoln,'' including Silverado Savings in Colorado, on
whose board Neal Bush, the president's son, once served.
   _Riegle, the Senate Banking Committee's chairman, acknowledged
through a spokeswoman that in March 1987 he visited a lavish resort
Keating was building in Arizona with Lincoln funds to give a speech
to American Continental employees.
   _Breeden said former SEC Commissioner Barbara Thomas, an
appointee of former President Carter, had called the agency's top
enforcement official as a character witness for Keating.
   A former top Bank Board official testified last week that Ms.
Thomas had approached her about obtaining for Keating an early
examination audit of Lincoln by regional thrift regulators.
Documents obtained by the House panel show that Ms. Thomas, as of
early this year, had an outstanding unsecured loan of $250,000 from
Lincoln.
</TEXT>
