<FIRST>r f PM-Southmark-Integon     11-15 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Southmark-Integon,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southmark Approves Sale of Integon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southmark Corp. said it has reached an agreement
to sell its 89 percent stake in Integon Corp., its insurance unit,
for cash and securities to a new company formed by Jupiter
Industries Inc. and Head Insurance Investors L.P.
   Under terms of the sale, approved Tuesday by Southmark's board,
the two companies will pay $189 million in cash, debt and new stock
for Integon and repay or assume $120 million in Integon debt,
Southmark said.
   Jupiter, based in Chicago, and Head, based in New York, had
withdrawn an earlier offer of $135 million for Integon.
   Integon shareholders, including Southmark, will receive about
$94 million, or $3.04 a share. The remainder will be placed in
escrow against potential losses, Southmark said. The unused
escrowed funds eventually will be returned to shareholders, the
company said.
   Previous agreements to sell Integon called for shareholders to
receive as much as $7.45 a share, but those efforts fell through
for lack of financing or inability to reach a final accord.
   Southmark, the Dallas-based real estate and financial services
concern which is seeking to reorganize under the protection of
federal bankruptcy court, could receive up to $43 million in
much-needed cash for its 89 percent stake in the life insurance
company if the sale is approved.
   The sale must be approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Dallas and
by Integon's board and its outside shareholders. Southmark said it
anticipates completing the transaction by April 30, 1990, and
either party can end the agreement if the sale isn't closed by then.
   Southmark reported a $109.2 million loss for its insurance group
for the third quarter ended March 30. The loss includes a $90
million expected deficit from the sale of the group and contributed
to the company's $1.04 billion third-quarter loss.
   Jupiter is controlled by Chicago real estate investor Jerry
Wexler, and Head, an investment partnership, is managed by New York
merchant banking firm John Head &amp; Partners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
