<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-NewsCorp     11-15 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-News Corp,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>News Corp. Reports Sharp Profit Slump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News Corp., Rupert Murdoch's
Australia-based international media company, reported Wednesday its
first quarter earnings dropped 78 percent, partly because of
revenue lost during a labor dispute.
   News Corp. said it earned $28.7 million, or 23 cents per
American depository receipt (ADR), in the three months ended Sept.
30, down from $133.1 million, or 83 cents per ADR, in the same
period a year earlier, when the company had a $61.2 million
after-tax gain from asset sales.
   Each ADR is equivalent to two News Corp. common shares. They are
traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
   News Corp. said its revenue rose to $1.51 billion from $1.27
billion a year earlier, but that its results were affected by a
14-week dispute by pilots that eroded earnings at Ansett Airlines,
which News Corp. jointly owns with TNT Ltd.
   It did not say what the dispute had cost in terms of lost
revenue.
   The company said its earnings also were affected by inclusion
from Sept. 1 of operating results for its Sky Television operations
in Britain, and an increase in interest payments.
   News Corp.'s U.S. holdings, which include the Twentieth Century
Fox film studio, the Fox television network and publications
including TV Guide and the Daily Racing Form, provided the bulk of
sales and earnings for the company.
   Murdoch had prepared shareholders for a lean profit year at the
company's annual meeting Oct. 10, warning then that annual earnings
may ``not have their customary increase.''
</TEXT>
