<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CBOEInvestigation     11-15 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CBOE Investigation,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Probes Possible Manipulation of Stock-Options Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange is
investigating the possibility that stock-index options were
manipulated as part of program-trading activity, a published report
says.
   The exchange is looking at trading in Standard &amp; Poor's 100
stock index options during the Oct. 13 stock market plunge as well
as other volatile trading days, the Wall Street Journal reported in
today's editions.
   The CBOE is the fourth exchange to search for program-trading
abuses. The New York Stock Exchange and two other Chicago exchanges
are conducting a separate probe of computer-assisted program
trading in stocks and stock-index futures.
   CBOE President Charles Henry told the Journal that the exchange
is looking at ``sources of volatility,'' including trades, programs
or otherwise, that may have involved manipulation or other forms of
rule-breaking.
   ``We are looking at all volatile days,'' Henry said. ``We have
been in touch with the SEC frequently about the events, and they
are well aware of the review that is being conducted.''
   Exchange officials did not immediately return telephone calls
seeking comment.
   For years, the CBOE has been a source of rumors and suspicions
about program-trading abuses, the Journal said. Those suspicions
partially result from the complexity of options-related
program-trading strategies that are only understood by the most
sophisticated traders.
   Additionally, traders say program trades in S&amp;P 100 stock index
options have moved the market in the past, the newspaper said.
   Program trading is the rapid buying and selling of stocks by
computer to take advantage of temporary price differences. A stock
option is the right to buy or sell the underlying value of a stock
index, such as the S&amp;P 100, at a specified price within a specified
time.
   The unique feature of stock-index options is that they are
settled by payment in cash, not with delivery or receipt or stocks.
Also, S&amp;P 100 options can be exercised at any time before their
expiration date.
   The SEC reported that the S&amp;P 100 options market re-emerged as a
popular program-trading vehicle after the 1987 crash.
   A June 30 SEC memo said ``S&amp;P 100 stock index options were often
the second-most heavily used derivative product for index arbitrage
from November 1988 to April 1989.''
   Program trades involving the S&amp;P 100 options accounted for 8
percent to 19 percent of total index arbitrage volume for the
six-month period, the commission said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
