<DOCNO> AP891115-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-OntheMoney Adv16   11-15 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 16,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Nov 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Year-End Trap in Mutual Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the end of the year approaches, financial
advisers are issuing warnings about a trap that can spring on
anybody who buys shares of mutual funds.
   If you are thinking about getting into a fund or making a
substantial addition to an existing fund holding before year-end,
they say, you should do a little extra research.
   The subject of that inquiry: Is the fund about to declare its
annual distributions of dividends and capital gains?
   If the answer is yes, the experts say, you might seriously
consider waiting to invest your money until after the record, or
ex-dividend, date for those distributions, and thus miss sticking
yourself with an unnecessary tax obligation.
   The trap works this way:
   To qualify for status as investment companies that don't
themselves have to pay taxes, most mutual funds must pass through
substantially all of their investment income to their shareholders
each year.
   These distributions then become taxable, as dividends or capital
gains, to the shareholders.
   The typical money-market fund or income fund investing in bonds
declares its dividends daily, or at least monthly. So it doesn't
matter much what time of year you choose to invest in these.
   By contrast, many stock funds or others that might earn capital
gains _ for example, a fund investing in high-yield ``junk'' bonds
that can fluctuate a great deal in price _ make all or a big chunk
of their distributions once a year.
   The effective date of the distribution is often set between
mid-December and the end of the year, for payment a few weeks later.
   If you buy fund shares just before the record date, you put
yourself in the position of having some of your capital returned
almost immediately to you, burdened with a tax liability, before it
has had a chance to earn you any real return.
   ``You have acquired a share of the other stockholders'
profits,'' says Sheldon Jacobs in his Handbook For No-Load Fund
Investors.
   Suppose, for illustration purposes, that a fund's net asset
value stands at $20 a share when you buy it just before the
ex-distribution date. Then a $2 distribution is declared, lowering
the net asset value to $18.
   Presumably, you don't want this ``income'' in cash _ you just
put the money into the fund. But even if you have it automatically
reinvested in new shares, you can't duck the tax liability.
   No such problem arises if you wait until after the record date.
Whatever amount you had set aside to invest will buy
proportionately more shares at $18 than it would have at $20.
   Stock funds' distributions tend to be especially sizable in bull
market years, such as 1989.
   Information about a fund's plans should be readily available
through a simple phone call to the fund before you decide to buy.
   Of course, if the investment is being made in an individual
retirement account or other program that shelters it from current
taxes, the timing of distributions doesn't matter.
   But among taxable investors, those who show up at the wrong time
are presented with a share of the bill for a party they didn't
attend.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Nov 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Groom Adv19   11-15 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Groom, Adv 19,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Nov. 19 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arthur Groom: Flamboyant Jeweler Romances the Stones</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIDGEWOOD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the private and mysterious world of
high-powered jewelry dealing, Arthur Groom stands out like a
diamond in the rough.
   Groom, 39, whose firm sold $12 million worth of diamonds and
colored stones last year, frequently travels to jungles, cavernous
mines and other remote spots in Asia and Africa in a constant
search for the world's rarest rocks.
   Like the sailing merchants of centuries past, Groom will barter
and trade for many of his stones. He recently swapped a shipload of
cement for $1 million worth of diamond ``roughs'' from the African
nation of Sierra Leone.
   Groom seeks stones in dangerous, strife-ridden nations, such as
Burma, where he says he is only the third American since 1962 to
gain the rights to deal in rubies. Most recently, Groom closed a
deal to become the sole distributor of American soft drinks in
Burma.
   And while most diamond dealers prefer to keep their actions
cloaked in secrecy, Groom, whose manner is outspoken and friendly,
seeks the spotlight. He employs his own media publicist who pitches
Groom as a modern-day Indiana Jones.
   ``There have been very few dealers who are so public,'' said Abe
Michael Shainberg, executive director of New York's exclusive
Diamond Dealers Club, considered the world's most important diamond
exchange. ``The average diamond dealer, for security reasons, does
not want such publicity. He's an honest and honorable man. His
publicity is good for his business, and good for the rest of us,
too.''
   Sitting in a small office at his fashionable store in Ridgewood,
Groom proudly showed off stones with $100,000 price tags. The
shirt-sleeved New Jersey man, who wore no jewelry, smiled and
insisted he is ``not Indiana Jones.''
   ``No intrigue,'' he said. ``But I do have a message.''
   Groom says American business can exert a positive influence
throughout the world. He is convinced the world respects the
American system, but Americans must also understand and respect
other cultures.
   ``In many cultures, the American way does not hold up,'' he
said. ``How dare we have that attitude that ours is the only way.''
   Groom's story, however, is the stuff of the American dream. He
left a successful job as a stockbroker for Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. 15
years ago after his friend's father urged him to take a gem course
that left him ``absolutely fascinated'' with precious stones.
   Groom said he struggled at first, working 15-hour days in a
one-room enterprise as his friends climbed their respective
corporate ladders. Arthur Groom &amp; Co. in Ridgewood and his American
Trading Co. in New York slowly grew into a business with offices
around the globe.
   Groom doesn't just cut deals on the telephone. He hops on planes
and goes directly to faraway mines to pick out his own stones and
diamond roughs. One of the few dealers who sells both diamonds and
colored stones, Groom is the consummate frequent flyer, logging
more than 150,000 miles each year.
   ``I wanted to do things differently,'' he said. ``I think
running just a single jewelry store is boring.''
   Avoiding boredom means taking risks.
   Amid a treasure trove of jewelry in the vault at his store is an
envelope that bears the remnants of a dramatic failure. It was a
diamond that, at the final stages of cutting in his New York
operation, ``exploded.'' The diamond's glitter was suddenly
replaced by a dull mist.
   ``It was my fault,'' he said, explaining that he had failed to
check a crucial stress point in the rock. ``It's absolutely
worthless now. It would have sold for $80,000. Eighty thousand
dollars down the drain.''
   Groom said he draws energy from his work.
   ``There's a science to picking stones in the jungle,'' he said.
``Then you go to the Diamond Dealers Club and pull up your shirt
sleeves and wheel and deal. Some Saturdays, I'll simply work the
floor of this stoor, helping an old lady who needs a $10 soldering
job on a broken chain.''
   Groom said he has changed since his younger days.
   ``I have mellowed,'' Groom said. ``Once, there was pure
aggressiveness, the hardball selling technique. Now I have a
different philosophy. We went through a period when we did things
just for money. I don't do it for the money. I can go to sleep
every night knowing we do things with integrity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Sunday Nov. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
