<FIRST>r f PM-Georgia-Pacific 1stLd-Writethru f0015 11-15 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georgia-Pacific, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0015,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rhetoric Takes Center Stage in Takeover Battle Between Papermakers</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf pvs `The battle ...' to update with Georgia-Pacific
announcing financing commitments; picks up 5th graf pvs, `Also Tuesday
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rhetoric is heating up as Georgia-Pacific
Corp. pursues its spurned bid to buy Great Northern Nekoosa Corp.
for $3.1 billion, though both forest-products companies deny any
nasty intent.
   Great Northern earlier this week rejected the Georgia-Pacific
offer in a pair of sharply worded letters, one to its shareholders
and the other to T. Marshall Hahn Jr., Georgia-Pacific's chairman.
   Georgia-Pacific responded with a statement to the media that
bluntly questioned the motives of Great Northern's management in
turning down the $58-a-share offer.
   Georgia-Pacific announced today that it has lined up commitments
for $4.5 billion from 19 domestic and international banks to fund
the takeover. The company said Bank of America, its primary bank
since the 1950s, has agreed to provide $1.25 billion of the amount.
   Also Tuesday, Great Northern announced it was challenging a
ruling by the Interstate Commerce Commission that cleared
Georgia-Pacific to include Great Northern's four railroads in the
proposed acquisition.
   Norwalk, Conn.-based Great Northern said the ICC approved the
clearance in one day when the process usually takes months.
   Georgia-Pacific ``cut corners'' and engaged in ``questionable
tactics'' to get the ruling, Great Northern said.
   But Great Northern Chairman William R. Laidig told The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution that he did not mean for his letter to Hahn to
seem sarcastic or harsh.
   And Georgia-Pacific President Ronald P. Hogan said in an
interview at his company's Atlanta headquarters Tuesday that he saw
straightforwardness, not anger, in Great Northern's statements.
   Hogan also said he did not expect Georgia-Pacific, which he once
described as ``a company of nice people,'' to get nasty as it
tangles over the offer.
   ``I would hope not,'' he said. ``If you come and offer me 50
percent or more (profit) for more of my assets, I would think
you're an awfully friendly guy. And I would probably embrace you
for doing that.
   ``So I don't see how offering a company 50 percent or more
premium for what its assets have been selling for for the past two
years would be considered unfriendly,'' he said.
   Hogan said Georgia-Pacific plans to continue its pursuit of
Great Northern, but declined to discuss strategy.
   Hogan said all aspects of the proposal are negotiable, though he
said the offer as it stands provides excellent short-term benefits
for Great Northern shareholders and good long-term prospects for
his company.
   Hogan also dismissed concerns raised by Great Northern about
antitrust implications of the proposed deal. He said he was not
worried, either, about an anti-takeover regulations in Maine, where
Great Northern is incorporated, that some say could block the deal.
   Hogan said various conditions _ Georgia-Pacific's confidence in
the strength of the industry, the company's ability to handle the
debt from a takeover and the compatibility of the two companies _
made the time right to launch the bid.
   A takeover of Great Northern would be one of the largest
acquisitions ever for Georgia-Pacific, a company that has often
used buyouts to grow over 62 years.
   Georgia-Pacific started in 1927 as a lumberyard in Augusta, when
founder Owen Cheatham made a $12,000 investment to start a hardwood
wholesale business known originally as the Georgia Hardwood Lumber
Co.
   The company soon began to manufacture hardwood lumber, too.
During World War II, it was the largest supplier of lumber to the
military.
   After the war, in 1947, the company made its first West Coast
acquisition, a plywood plant in Bellingham, Wash. A string of
acquisitions followed over the next 10 years.
   It was during the 1950s, too, that the company changed its name
to Georgia-Pacific and moved its headquarters to Portland, Ore.,
where it remained until coming to Atlanta in 1982.
   The company's roster of acquisitions continued to grow in the
'60s and '70s; purchases from coast to coast included paper mills,
a gypsum company, chemical plants, a kraft pulp mill, timberlands,
sawmills and an oil company.
   Last year, the company spent $841 million on acquisitions.
   Georgia-Pacific also decided about 1983 to focus more narrowly
on its pulp-and-paper and building products businesses. That
resulted in the divestiture of some of its underperforming assets,
notably the commodity chemicals business, which became Georgia Gulf
Corp.
   Great Northern, as Georgia-Pacific sees it, fits right in with
the company's growth pattern. It explains why Georgia-Pacific is
not worried about a ``white knight'' riding in to win Great
Northern in a bidding war, Hogan said.
   ``We believe that through the strategic combinations of the two
businesses ... Great Northern is more valuable to Georgia-Pacific
than it is to any other company,'' Hogan said.
   Great Northern had 1988 sales of $3.6 billion. The company owns
3.5 million acres of timberland and has 20,000 employees at mills
and factories in Arkansas, Colorado, Georgia, Maine, Mississippi
and Wisconsin.
   Georgia-Pacific had $9.5 billion in sales last year, making
paper, other forest products and building materials. It owns 6.5
million acres of timberland and 380 plants and mills employing
44,000 workers.
</TEXT>
