<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell Wednesday against most major
currencies in thin, choppy European trading. Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said there was little activity in the markets before
Thursday's release of U.S. merchandise trade figures for September.
   ``After the dollar's steep drop overnight, we had sort of a
reaction,'' said a trader at a large U.S. bank in Frankfurt. ``The
U.S. trade figures tomorrow are also preventing major activity.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell to 143.37 Japanese yen from 143.80 yen
Tuesday. Later, in London, it edged back up to 143.45 yen.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.5810, unchanged
from late Tuesday's rate.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8382 West German marks, down from 1.8540; 1.6220 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6380; 6.2420 French francs, down from 6.2925; 2.0790
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0925; 1,348.25 Italian lire, down from
1,357.00; and 1.1726 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1710.
   Gold bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $391.25 a
troy ounce, up from $390 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold rose to
a late bid of $391 an ounce from $389 bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 43 cents to close at a bid
$391.94 an ounce.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $5.46 a
troy ounce, up from $5.31 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
