<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-OffshoreOilPort Adv19   11-15 0946</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Offshore Oil Port, Adv 19,0978</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Nov. 19 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Only U.S. Superport: It's Clean, But Will It Ever Make A Profit?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's only offshore port for
supertankers hasn't had a serious spill in eight years of
operation, but it hasn't had a profit, either.
   The clean but poor Louisiana Offshore Oil Port is touted as a
savior of the environment by some and a financial failure by
others, leaving uncertain whether it will be a model for other
ports around the country.
   Known as LOOP, the Louisiana Offshore Oil Port sits 19 miles off
the coast in 115 feet of water _ deep enough for the biggest
tankers in the world to tie up and unload their crude cargo.
   When it was proposed in 1972, supporters said it would cost $250
million, create tens of thousands of jobs and stimulate onshore
investments.
   Environmentalists fought the idea, warning that it was had the
potential for oil spills that could devastate Louisiana's fragile
wetlands.
   Both sets of predictions were confounded.
   LOOP cost more than $700 million and has yet to make a profit.
However, it has been so clean that Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan
thinks building more deep-water ports around the country would help
avoid spills like one in Alaska's Prince William Sound.
   ``The loss of oil has been just a thimble-full from every barrel
that's been through there,'' he said after a visit to the port in
September.
   ``And it confirms my original thought that the way to avoid oil
spills is to make sure that tankers don't run aground. That's
what's happened in all our oil spills.''
   LOOP looks like a three-deck offshore oil platform. Around it,
1{ miles away, are three buoys like floating, 42-foot-tall bird
cages. Tankers tie up to those buoys while they pump oil through
long hoses attached to concrete bases on the ocean floor.
   The five owners, in order of the size of their stakes, are USX
Corp.'s Marathon Oil Co., Texaco Inc., Royal Dutch Shell's Shell
Oil Co., Ashland Oil Inc., and Murphy Oil Corp. The consortium is
responsible for paying off the bonds for the project, which were
issued by a state agency to qualify for tax-exempt status.
   Former Gov. Edwin Edwards told reporters in 1974, shortly before
taking office: ``The projections are that it could pay for itself
in less than 10 years.''
   Instead LOOP, after eight years of operation, still owes $565
million on $731 million in bonds, said controller Paul Simoneaux.
   It is handling about half the projected 63 million gallons of
crude oil a day. It lost money until last year, when it broke even
for the first time.
   Will it make a profit this year?
   ``I'd rather not comment on that,'' said R.C. Thompson,
president of LOOP, Inc., a consortium of five oil companies which
own and operate the platform.
   LOOP depends on strong demand for imported oil, and backers were
stunned when Americans responded to the 1970s jump in oil prices by
conserving.
   U.S. imports of oil rose far less than expected in the 1970s and
actually fell into the mid-1980s.
   LOOP's prospects have improved now that oil imports are rising
again. Nationally, imports averaged about 8 million barrels a day
for the first 10 months of 1989.
   LOOP is geared to oil hauled from the Middle East in
supertankers _ behemoths which cannot get into most U.S. ports.
   ``Ironically, for LOOP to be successful, you have to import
foreign oil,'' Lujan said earlier this year.
   Oil imports are up around the country. ``That makes me believe
that oil ports would be successful in other places,'' Lujan said.
   LOOP has been almost squeaky clean. Thompson estimates that, out
of 1.5 billion barrels of oil brought ashore since 1981, 850 have
spilled. That works out to about a teaspoonful for every 2,300
gallons moved.
   Three gallons spilled in all of 1987.
   LOOP's location eliminates the threat of groundings and lessens
the chance that a spill could come ashore. Radar keeps a continuous
sweep over a 36-square-mile safety zone and special mooring masters
guide the big ships to and from LOOP's buoys.
   ``Exxon said it's going to cost them $1.5 billion to clean up
Prince William Sound and the surrounding area. ... Wouldn't it be
better to spend $1.5 billion to prevent oil spills than to spend it
cleaning it up?'' Lujan said.
   Environmentalists aren't convinced that superports are the
answer. Alternatives could include building tankers with double
hulls, improving traffic control and reactivating Coast Guard
stations, said Lisa Speer, senior scientist at the Natural
Resources Defense Council in New York.
   In addition, said Speer, construction and maintenance of such
ports also could hurt the environment, and beaches can be affected
by spills 20 miles away.
   ``In Rhode Island, within a few hours you had a spill that had
covered 25 square miles,'' she said. ``Offshore spills can still
impact the shore.''
   And $1.5 billion is a drop in the barrel of possible costs for a
system of offshore ports such as Lujan envisions, with deep-water
ports off of Houston, Los Angeles, Philadelphia and Alaska.
   To replicate LOOP would cost more than $800 million and probably
more than $1 billion, by various estimates. Sean Connaughton,
marine transportation associate with the American Petroleum
Institute, said he's seen estimates as high as $2 billion.
   On top of that, oil users such as refineries that now get direct
deliveries would have to hook up to a network of as-yet-unbuilt
pipelines. Building those could be even more expensive than
building the ports, Connaughton said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Sunday Nov. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
