<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BritishAirways     11-15 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-British Airways,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Airways' Profit Up 16.5 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways PLC on Wednesday reported that its
net profit jumped 16.5 percent in the second quarter of its fiscal
year, boosted by strong passenger traffic.
   The airline, one of the world's largest, said its net profit in
the three months ended Sept. 30 rose to 106 million British pounds,
or around $172 million, from 91 million pounds, or $147.4 million,
a year earlier.
   Per-share earnings increased 16.7 percent to 14.7 pence, or 23.8
cents, from 12.6 pence, or 20.4 cents.
   ``Our profits for the second quarter are the highest yet
reported for those three months by any airline in the world,'' Lord
King, British Airways' chairman, said in a statement.
   The airline reported increased passenger traffic for the period,
including a one-month record in September of 2.2 million passengers
carried. Much of the growth came on flights between the United
States and Britain, the company said.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 13.4 percent to 1.4 billion pounds,
or $2.2 billion, from 1.2 billion pounds, or $1.9 billion.
   Last month, British Airways withdrew from a group led by pilots
and top managers seeking to buy UAL Corp. for $6.75 billion, after
the group failed to obtain adequate financing for the deal. The
British airline had planned to invest $750 million in Chicago-based
UAL, the parent of United Airlines, in return for a 15 percent
stake in the company.
   King said in the statement British Airways was ``disappointed''
that its proposed investment in UAL fell through.
   ``We will of course look for any new investment opportunities,''
he said.
   Talks on British Airways possibly taking a stake in the Belgian
airline Sabena are continuing, King said.
   He said fuel costs increased 22 percent in the six months ended
Sept. 30 and, like most European airlines, British Airways also had
to bear the costs of delays and disruptions caused by inadequate
air traffic control facilities in Europe.
   In addition, British Airways' capacity has been reduced by the
late delivery of its new Boeing 747-400 aircraft, King said. The
Machinists union has been on strike against Seattle-based Boeing
Co. since Oct. 4.
   For the six months ended Sept. 30, net profit rose 16.7 percent
to 168 million pounds, or around $265 million, from 144 million
pounds, or $227 million.
   Per-share earnings were up 16.5 percent to 23.3 pence, or 36.8
cents, from 20.0 pence, or 32.4 cents.
   Six-month revenue advanced 14.2 percent to 2.53 billion pounds,
or $3.99 billion, from 2.2 billion pounds, or $3.47 billion.
</TEXT>
