<HEAD>Wheat Market Leads Grain Futures To Mostly Higher Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, paced by strength
in the wheat market linked to dryness in U.S. winter wheat growing
areas.
   The Agriculture Department's confirmation of new sales of wheat
to Egypt and the Philippines _ 50,000 metric tons apiece _ also
helped the wheat market, as did a report of frost damage to wheat
in Argentina.
   ``The Argentine wheat crop has been in trouble all year,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Soybean futures finished mixed, weakened by a report of
larger-than-expected stocks of Malaysian palm oil, a soybean-oil
competitor.
   Corn futures also closed mixed despite rumors of new Soviet
interest in buying U.S. corn.
   At the close, wheat futures were 2 cents to 4} cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.05 a bushel; corn was \
cent lower to 2 cents higher with December at $2.39} a bushel; oats
were } cent to 1} cents higher with December at $1.45} a bushel;
and soybeans were } cent lower to 5 cents higher with November at
$5.79{ a bushel.
