<FIRST>u f AM-HomeForeclosures     11-15 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Foreclosures,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slumping Regional Real Estate Market Leading to Rise In Foreclosures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An increasing number of residential properties are
being sold on the auction block as the region's slumping real
estate market prompts foreclosures on homes and developments that
have trouble attracting buyers.
   ``We are seeing some foreclosures in our area. Where there used
to be one or two, now there seems to be more,'' Carol Sager,
co-owner of Century 21 Sager Real Estate in Lowell, said Wednesday.
   The state Land Court in Boston has seen a steep increase in
foreclosures and auctions of all kinds across Massachusetts,
although banking officials say owners of single-family homes have
not been hit as hard as condominium developers.
   In 1987, 253 foreclosure filings culminated with an auction,
meaning no one stepped in to pay off the mortgage. Last year the
number rose to 546 and this year the total already has reached
1,100.
   Charles Trombly, recorder for the court, said the figures are
not broken down into specific categories.
   ``It's everything,'' he said. ``It's condos. It's people who get
laid off at Wang who get in over their heads.''
   Banking officials blame much of the trouble on a real estate
boom earlier this decade that led to an oversupply of building
space, especially in condominiums.
   Robert Eisenberg, president of New England Financial Resources
Inc. in Boston, which manages assets for banks, said some of the
outlying areas from Boston have been particularly troublesome for
developers trying to sell condominiums.
   ``I think it's very clear in southern New Hampshire there was a
bit more optimism exhibited than there should have been,''
Eisenberg said. ``Certainly there was not a lot of sober thought
given to some of these projects.''
   ``The foreclosures have accelerated at an accelerating pace,''
he said. ``Bankruptcy is a growth industry. And unfortunately,
there is a lot of human suffering.''
   Such an example came earlier this year, when Andrew Lane of
Southborough, the state's largest housing developer headquartered
in Massachusetts, filed for bankruptcy protection. Lane blamed the
region's slow real estate market for his company's problems.
   Bankruptcy filings in New England are up about 50 percent from
last year, and more than half are related to real estate projects,
said Virginia Greiman, U.S. trustee whose office monitors
bankruptcy cases for the New England region.
   Greiman said many people file for bankruptcy protection from
creditors to buy time in the foreclosure process.
   ``You have developers with all these condo projects and no one
buying them, so they have no cash flow to meet their expenses,''
she said.
   While condominium developers have been hit hard, bank officials
say owners of single-family homes have not had as much trouble.
Foreclosures on houses correlate less directly to the real estate
market and stem more from general economic conditions, such as
unemployment, which result in people having trouble paying their
bills.
   Despite a wave recent layoffs in the high tech industry,
regional unemployment remains relatively low, so forecasts of a
recession have not yet translated to a surge of foreclosures on
houses, said Bill Jones, vice president at BancBoston Mortgage
Corp., a subsidiary of Bank of Boston.
   Jones said that about 1.6 percent of his bank's residential
loans are delinquent, compared with about 1.5 percent at the same
time last year.
   Firms that conduct auctions, nonetheless, report that some
homeowners are losing their houses to foreclosure.
   Mark Enik, president of U.S. Auction Inc. in Hyannis, said many
of these people bought second homes, such as around Cape Cod, and
now are having trouble making payments.
   These people also have trouble selling the homes because they
were bought when prices were peaking, and the houses end up being
auctioned.
   ``They thought they can always sell the property in the worst
case,'' Enik said. ``But a lot of them cannot sell.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
