<DOCNO> AP891115-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SearsTower     11-15 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears Tower,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears Takes Tower Off Market, Borrows $850 Million Against It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. removed the ``for sale''
sign Wednesday from the world's tallest building, saying it had
decided not to sell Sears Tower but to use it as collateral for an
$850 million loan.
   Sears said it expected to sign by mid-summer a 15-year
convertible mortgage agreement with AEW Partners, a limited
partnership formed by Aldrich, Eastman &amp; Waltch Inc., a pension
fund real-estate investment manager based in Boston.
   The deal will provide Sears with $815 million after expenses and
give AEW an option to buy the 110-story downtown Chicago landmark
at the end of the loan period, said Douglas Fairweather, a Sears
spokesman.
   If AEW chooses to take possession of the 1,707-foot building
rather than accept repayment of the loan, Fairweather said, the
partnership would be required to pay Sears the balance of the
tower's full 1989 value as well as a portion of its appreciated
value.
   Chicago-based Sears, the nation's largest retailer and a
financial-services leader, announced just over a year ago that it
would sell its 15-year-old headquarters building as part of a
corporate restructuring designed to halt a slide in its profits.
   But after a prospective sale of the tower to Canadian developer
Olympia &amp; York Developments Inc. fell through in September, Sears
decided to take advantage of a drop in interest rates and refinance
the tower, which it owns free and clear.
   When Sears announced plans on Oct. 31, 1988, to sell the
building, ``we said that what we wanted to do was take out the
appreciated value of this asset to invest in our core businesses
and repurchase 10 percent of our shares,'' Fairweather said.
   ``While a sale seemed to be a better way to achieve our
objectives when we made this announcement, by the time we did this
deal, financing the building was a better alternative,'' he said.
   Interest rates on long-term loans for prime real estate such as
Sears Tower have fallen by as much as a full percentage point, to
about 9 percent, in the past year, said John Oharenko, managing
partner in the Chicago office of Cushman &amp; Wakefield Inc., a
commercial real-estate firm.
   Commercial real-estate loans typically reflect up to 80 percent
of a property's fair market value, he said.
   Fairweather said Sears will use proceeds from the tower deal to
pay down debt incurred through its repurchase over the past year of
about 40 million shares of its stock at about $40 a share, and to
invest in its core businesses, which include the Sears retailing
division, Dean Witter Reynolds brokerage services, Allstate
insurance and Coldwell Banker real estate.
   Sears' restructuring also includes a plan to move its retailing
headquarters from Sears Tower to a yet-to-be built office complex
in suburban Hoffman Estates by the end of 1992.
   Some of Chicago's commercial real estate experts have said the 2
million square feet of office space to be vacated by the retailing
division is badly in need of remodeling, both to modernize the
facilities and to subdivide it into smaller areas.
   Fairweather indicated that Sears would be doing some remodeling
in the tower.
   ``Even though it's a world-class building, we're aware of the
fact there are opportunities to enhance its value and we'll be
doing that,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
