<SECOND>AM-Aristech,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aristech Still Mulling Huntsman Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Aristech Chemical Corp. said it
will respond by the end of November to an $817 million takeover bid
by Utah industrialist Jon M. Huntsman.
   The board said in a statement Tuesday that ``further study and
deliberation are required'' before it will respond to Huntsman's
$25-per-share offer, which was made Oct. 12.
   Aristech spokesman J. Harry Varner declined further comment.
   In trading Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Aristech
was down 37{ cents a share at $22.12{.
   Huntsman, of Salt Lake City and whose family owns Huntsman
Chemical Co., the nation's largest privately held chemical company,
said he believes the board is seriously considering his offer and
not stalling for time.
   ``Irrespective of aberrations in the marketplace, and the
weakening of bridge financing and junk bonds, I've left my offer
intact,'' he said. ``I think they appreciate my consistency and
steadfastness.''
   According to a filing Oct. 16 with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Huntsman's group owned an 8.4 percent stake in Aristech.
   Aristech earned $67 million, or $1.93 a share, in the nine
months ended Sept. 30, on revenue of $773.8 million. It earned
$153.3 million, or $4.07 a share, in the same period in 1988 on
revenue of $806.7 million.
   The 1988 results included a $23.7 million credit due to an
accounting change.
</TEXT>
