<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1648EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-15 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heating Oil Futures Sag on Warm Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale home heating oil prices fell
Wednesday, weighed down by sluggish demand due to unusually warm
weather on the East Coast. Crude oil and gasoline futures prices
rose.
   Contracts for December delivery of No.2 heating oil declined
0.32 cent to 57.13 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile
Exchange after losing 0.23 cent on Tuesday. Later contract months
also finished lower.
   Jerry Samuels, an energy broker at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.,
said the latest production and inventory report from the American
Petroleum Institute showed higher-than-expected heating oil stocks,
reflecting slack demand.
   ``It is going to get cold here one day but there isn't much
demand now for heating oil because of the exceptionally warm
weather'' in the East, said Samuels.
   Crude oil and gasoline futures held up despite the selling in
the heating oil pits.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 17 cents to settle at $19.67 per
42-gallon barrel after declining 9 cents on Tuesday. Contracts for
delivery through March 1990 posted more modest gains.
   Contracts for wholesale unleaded gasoline for December increased
0.30 cent to 50.61 a gallon, recouping some of Tuesday's 0.75-cent
drop. Contracts for later delivery also advanced.
   Samuels said gasoline prices got support from the weekly API
report, which was released late Tuesday after trading was done for
the day. There was a larger amount of gasoline drawn from
inventories than expected, the API said.
</TEXT>
