<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CBOEInvestigation Bjt   11-15 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CBOE Investigation, Bjt,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Probes Possible Manipulation of Stock-Options Exchange</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange is
investigating reports of program-trading abuses to determine
whether rules were violated during days of hectic trading, exchange
officials said Wednesday.
   The world's largest options marketplace is looking at trading in
Standard &amp; Poor's 100 stock-index options during the Oct. 13 market
plunge as well as on other volatile trading days, said CBOE
President Charles Henry.
   The CBOE is the fourth major exchange to search for
program-trading abuses. The New York Stock Exchange, the Chicago
Board of Trade and Chicago Mercantile Exchange are conducting
separate probes of computer-assisted program trading in stocks and
stock-index futures.
   Those three exchanges have tightened surveillance measures and
imposed stiff fines after long-term federal scrutiny resulted in
numerous indictments and convictions.
   Henry downplayed the CBOE investigation, saying the exchange has
routinely monitored days of heavy trading since 1987.
   ``We have an ongoing study,'' he said in a telephone interview.
``We also make sure participants in our market behave as they are
supposed to.''
   Program trading is the rapid buying and selling of stocks by
computer to take advantage of temporary price differences. A stock
index option is the right to buy or sell the underlying value of a
stock index, such as the S&amp;P 100, at a specified price within a
specified time.
   The CBOE is looking at ``sources of volatility,'' including
trades _ program or otherwise _ that may have involved manipulation
or other forms of rule-breaking, Henry said.
   For years, the exchange has been the subject of rumors about
program-trading abuses _ rumors prompted partly by the complexity
of options-related program-trading strategies.
   Program trading involving stock-index options, commonly called
OEX, has also been blamed as a contributor to stock market
volatility.
   Tom Bond, CBOE vice president, pointed to three particular days
of heavy trading that are under scrutiny.
   One was Oct. 13 when the Dow Jones industrial average fell
190.58 points, its second biggest one-day point loss ever. The
second was Oct. 16 when the Dow rallied 88.12 points. The third day
was Oct. 24, when the Dow Jones industrials dropped 80 points
before rallying to finish the day with a 3.69-point loss.
   The CBOE's scrutiny of trading practices may date back to a
class-action lawsuit filed against the exchange after the October
1987 stock market crash.
   A group of more than 1,000 investors contend in the lawsuit that
the CBOE and floor traders responsible for making markets in
certain options on the S&amp;P 100 violated federal law and the
exchange's own rules by charging inflated prices for options
contracts.
   In May, the Securities and Exchange Commission censured the CBOE
for failing to enforce its own rules on trading manipulation
involving stocks and options on Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index.
   Program trades involving the S&amp;P 100 options accounted for 8
percent to 19 percent of total index arbitrage volume between
November 1988 and April 1989, the SEC noted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891115-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     11-15 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Struggling Eastern Airlines Keeps Winter Fares Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Money-losing Eastern Airlines is keeping cut-rate
fares to Florida this winter in an effort to bring back passengers,
officials said Wednesday.
   ``What we're really doing is generating revenue,'' said George
Brennan, Eastern's vice president for marketing. ``We know a lot
about Florida and how to stimulate travel ... We have an awful lot
of seats coming into Florida this winter.
   ``The existing fare structure ... is a fare structure that is
doing nothing to stimulate travel into Florida,'' Brennan said.
``Our objective obviously is to make money.''
   The fares, with relatively few restrictions, are effective
immediately for travel between nine Florida cities and 45 other
U.S. cities.
   They are significant because the airline industry usually boosts
winter season fares to vacation points, Eastern officials said. The
majority of fliers to Florida are discretionary, or leisure
travelers, Brennan said, spurring Eastern to offer incentives to
them.
   A Miami-to-New York fare, based on round-trip purchase, would be
$99 each way midweek, compared with a current fare of $139. In many
cases, Eastern is maintaining ``back-in-business'' discount fares
aimed at regaining business lost since the airline was hit by a
strike on March 4 and entered Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization
five days later.
   Passengers must make reservations before Dec. 15 and purchase
their tickets _ if space is available _ seven days in advance. The
tickets are fully refundable, Brennan said. Although the fares are
part of a winter promotion, reservations can be made for anytime in
the future, he said, and will be honored with seven-day advance
purchase.
   The fares require two-night stays, but the nights don't have to
be on a weekend, he said. Blackout dates, on which normal fares
apply, are southbound (into Florida) Dec. 21-26 and northbound (out
of Florida) Jan. 1-3.
   A fare structure effective Jan. 6 will continue to offer
discounts below industry averages but about $20 each way higher
than Eastern's bargain fares.
   Miami-based Eastern is flying 335 flights in and out of the nine
Florida cities: Miami, Fort Lauderdale, West Palm Beach, Tampa,
Orlando, Daytona Beach, Sarasota, Fort Myers and Melbourne.
   Eastern's announcement came after last week's third-quarter
report showed a net loss of $185.2 million amid indications the
airline has informed its major creditors of a $200 million cash
shortfall.
   ``It is used more as a marketing tool to attract attention,''
said Robert Joedicke, an airline analyst with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York. ``It's calculated to create a loss, but
it's calculated to regain critical mass, or market share. (Eastern
must) be particularly active to win people back.''
   Eastern officials, trying to rebuild without the unions, have
said the airline will emerge from bankruptcy early next year at
nearly 90 percent its pre-strike size. Eastern is back to 775 daily
flights, compared with nearly 1,100 before the ongoing strike began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
