<FIRST>r f AM-Argentina-Citicorp     11-15 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Citicorp,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citicorp Chairman: Argentina Must Pay Overdue Interest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp Chairman John Reed said
Wednesday that Argentina will have to pay at least part of its
overdue interest before foreign banks will consider loaning it more
money.
   ``There is no doubt the banks that hold Argentina's external
debt are concerned'' by the overdue interest, Reed told a news
conference.
   Argentina is the third biggest debtor nation in the developing
world. Early last year the government fell behind in interest
payments. Principal payments were deferred several years ago.
   Argentina's debt to foreign commercial banks, governments and
agencies like the World Bank amounts to about $60 billion, plus
about $4.5 billion in overdue interest.
   Citibank, which is operated by Citicorp, is owed about $1.5
billion, more than any other U.S. bank except Manufacturers Hanover
Trust.
   Reed said foreign bankers approve of President Carlos Menem's
program of economic austerity and structural reform.
   Initial debt talks with commercial banks in New York were held
last month. Argentina reportedly is seeking to borrow another $3
billion.
</TEXT>
