<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1755EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-15 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Silver Soars, Gold and Platinum Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Silver futures prices soared to six-month highs Wednesday while
gold and platinum, the recent leaders of the surging precious
metals group, fell back.
   On other commodity markets, pork futures prices rose sharply
amid talk of further food aid to Poland, grains and soybeans were
mostly higher and energy futures were mixed.
   Silver futures settled 13 cents to 15.1 cents higher on New
York's Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in
December at $5.538 a troy ounce, the highest price for a near-month
silver contract since May 12.
   Gold finished $1.90 to $2.10 lower on the Comex with December at
$392.80 a troy ounce; platinum settled $5.20 to $5.30 lower on the
New York Mercantile Exchange with January at $520.40 a troy ounce.
   Precious metals prices have risen broadly since Oct. 13, when a
190-point plunge in the Dow Jones industrials average triggered a
rush of investment dollars to the perceived safety of the metals.
   But the silver market has lagged behind gold and platinum,
possibly because silver is in greater supply. From Oct. 13 through
Tuesday, gold prices had risen by 7.5 percent, platinum by 6.9
percent and silver by just 4.9 percent.
   Silver played catch-up on Wednesday, pushing its gains since
Friday the 13th to 7.8 percent.
   ``I view it as the rubber-band effect,'' said Bernard Savaiko,
senior metals analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York. ``Platinum
and gold had already had good moves and investors veiwed silver as
too cheap relative to gold.''
   Some traders express the silver-gold price relationship in terms
of the number of ounces of silver it would take to equal the value
of one ounce of gold. A ratio in excess of 70-to-1 is often
interpreted by professional traders as a signal to buy silver and
sell gold, said James Steel, an analyst with Refco Inc.
   At the close of trading Tuesday, the silver-gold ratio was about
73-to-1, and it approached 74-to-1 early in Wednesday's session. At
that point, Steel said, ``the logical thing was to switch into the
silver market.''
   Pork futures prices skyrocketed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange after White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
United States probably would send more food aid to Poland.
   The government already has committed to send 10,000 metric tons
of pork bellies to Poland as part of a food-aid package.
   Firm cash markets also supported the pork and cattle markets.
   Live cattle settled .23 cent to .55 cent higher with December at
74.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .45 cent higher
with November at 83.30 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent to
1.37 cents higher with December at 49.27 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .72 cent to 1.38 cents higher with February at 63.87
cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade, paced by strength in the wheat market linked to
dryness in U.S. winter wheat growing areas.
   The Agriculture Department's confirmation of new sales of wheat
to Egypt and the Philippines _ 50,000 metric tons apiece _ also
helped the wheat market, as did a report of frost damage to wheat
in Argentina.
   Wheat settled 2\ cents to 4} cents higher with December at $4.05
a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to 2 cents higher with December at
$2.39} a bushel; oats were } cent to 1{ cents higher with December
at $1.45} a bushel; soybeans were } cent lower to 4} cents higher
with November at $5.79{ a bushel.
   Wholesale home heating oil prices fell on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, weighed down by sluggish demand due to
unusually warm weather on the East Coast. Crude oil and gasoline
futures were mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .08 cent lower to .17
cent higher with December at $19.67 a barrel; heating oil was .05
cent to .61 cent lower with December at 57.13 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .20 cent lower to .30 cent higher with
December at 50.61 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
