<FIRST>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     11-15 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japonica Planning To Review Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc., which had
indicated it would not seriously consider a takeover bid from
Japonica Partners, has decided to let the New York investment group
review its confidential records, a Japonica spokesman said.
   ``We're pleased that the board is now apparently cooperating,
and are looking forward to completing a transaction that is in the
best interests of creditors and shareholders,'' said the spokesman,
Fredric Spar.
   Edward M. Romanoff, an Allegheny International spokesman,
Wednesday declined to comment on Spar's comments.
   Last week, company attorney Bruce McCullough said in a U.S.
Bankruptcy Court hearing that the board ``probably won't spend much
time'' considering the $683.8 million buyout bid by Japonica.
   The consumer products company, which a year ago actively sought
buyers, recently has maintained it is not for sale.
   Japonica has said it might increase its bid to $700 million or
more if it received additional information from the company.
   Allegheny's board has designated two non-executive directors,
Thomas Maddux and Richard Farkas, to act as liaisons to Japonica,
Spar said.
   Allegheny International, the manufacturer of Sunbeam and Oster
appliances, has spent nearly two years trying to reorganize under
Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws.
</TEXT>
